r": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEpisode list", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laverne_%26_Shirley_(1981_TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Gareth Owen (sound designer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Gareth Owen\n| image         =Gareth Owen - Sound Designer - Biog Photo - Full Size.jpg\n| birth_name     = Gareth John Owen\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1977|8|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = Sheffield, England\n| nationality    = British\n| education    = University of Plymouth\n| occupation    = Theatrical Sound Designer\n| years_active   = 1998\u2013present\n| children      = 2\n| website         = {{official URL}}\n| imagesize     =\n}}\n\n'''Gareth Owen''' is an eight-time Tony & Olivier Award-winning/nominated [[sound design]]er specialising in musical theatre in London's West End, on Broadway and internationally.\n\n==Career==\n\nOwen was nominated for his first [[Tony Award]] in 2010 for his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of [[Trevor Nunn]]'s musical, ''[[A Little Night Music]]'' starring [[Catherine Zeta-Jones]] and [[Angela Lansbury]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibdb.com/awardperson.asp?id=485023 |title=IBDB Person Awards |work=Internet Broadway Database |access-date=4 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023134441/http://www.ibdb.com/awardperson.asp?id=485023 |archive-date=23 October 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe was then nominated for an [[Olivier Award]] for his [[West End theatre|West End]] production of [[Terry Johnson (dramatist)|Terry Johnson]]'s musical, [[End of the Rainbow]] starring multi-award-winning [[Tracie Bennett]] as [[Judy Garland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olivierawards.com/nominations/view/item114060/Best-Sound-Design/ |title=Olivier Award for Sound Design |work=The Olivier Awards |access-date=14 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110714235819/http://www.olivierawards.com/nominations/view/item114060/Best-Sound-Design/ |archive-date=14 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> The show later transferred to Broadway where he went on to pick up a further Tony nomination for Best Sound Design.\n\nIn recent years Owen collected a 2nd Oliver nomination for ''[[Top Hat (musical)|Top Hat]]'', and, after five nominations, finally won the Oliver for Best Sound Design in 2014 with the London production of ''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''.\n\nIn 2015 Owen won the Olivier for Sound Design for the second consecutive year, this time for [[Memphis (musical)|Memphis]] at the Shaftesbury Theatre, starring [[Beverley Knight]]. Composed by [[David Bryan]] from [[Bon Jovi]], and directed by [[Christopher Ashley]], this marked his sixth win/nomination in a row. He also received the prestigious Pro Sound Award for his work on the same production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prosoundawards.com//|title=Pro Sound Award for Best Theatre Sound|work=The Pro Sound Awards|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Owen won several awards for the Broadway musical [[Come from Away|''Come From Away'']] including the [[Outer Critics Circle Award]] and the [[Craig Noel|Craig Noel Award]], as well as a [[Helen Hayes Award]] nomination.\n\nGareth has worked on over two hundred and seventy-five commercial sound designs throughout the world including: ''[[42nd Street (musical)|42nd Street,]] [[Starlight Express]], [[Bat Out of Hell]], [[Wind in the Willows (musical)|Wind in the Willows,]]'' ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (musical)|Disney's Hunchback of Notre Dame]]'', ''[[Spring Awakening (musical)|Spring Awakening]]'', ''[[Young Frankenstein (musical)|Young Frankenstein]]'',''[[The Bodyguard (musical)|The Bodyguard]]'', ''[[Let It Be (musical)|Let it Be]]'', ''[[The Little Mermaid (musical)|Disney's Little Mermaid]]'', ''[[Sister Act (musical)|Sister Act]]'', ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'', ''[[Beauty and the Beast (musical)|Disney's Beauty & The Beast]]'', ''[[Singin' in the Rain (musical)|Singin' in the Rain]]'', ''[[Aspects of Love]]'', ''[[Footloose (musical)#Original London production|Footloose]]'', ''[[Flashdance]]'', ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'', ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'', ''[[Fame the Musical|Fame]]'', ''[[Saturday Night Fever (musical)|Saturday Night Fever]]'' and ''[[La Cage aux Folles (musical)|La Cage Aux Folles]]''.\n\n==Selected Awards==\n{{Awards table|2}}\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''The Donna Summer Musical''\n| NAACP Theatre Award for Best Sound Larger Theatre\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Starlight Express (Bochum)'' \n| Pro Sound Award \n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Carmen La Cubana]]''\n|Broadway World Germany Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|Broadway World Toronto Award for Best Original Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Bat Out of Hell The Musical]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|Broadway World Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Summer: The Donna Summer Musical]]''\n|Craig Noel Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Bat Out of Hell The Musical]]''\n|AV Technology Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[Outer Critics Circle Award]] for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Bat Out of Hell The Musical]]''\n|Broadway World Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|Dora Awards for Best Sound Design\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''Individual Recognition''\n|Pro Sound Award for Sound Engineer of the Year\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|Helen Hayes Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[A Bronx Tale (musical)|A Bronx Tale]]''\n|Broadway World Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Memphis (musical)|Memphis the Musical]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (musical)|Hunchback of Notre Dame]]''\n| Broadway World Awards for Best Sound Design\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2013\n| ''[[Top Hat (musical)|Top Hat]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n| ''[[I Can't Sing!]]''\n| Pro-Sound Award for Best Theatre Sound\n| {{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2012\n| ''[[End of the Rainbow]]''\n| [[Tony Award]] for Best Sound Design of a Musical\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2011\n| ''[[End of the Rainbow]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[A Little Night Music]]''\n| [[Tony Award]] for Best Sound Design of a Musical\n| {{Nominated}}\n| \n{{end}}\n\nIn 2015 Owen was elected Treasurer of The Association of Sound Designers, a UK based association representing nearly all the theatrical sound engineers in the country.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.garethowensound.com Official site]\n* {{IBDB name}}\n*[http://www.theasd.uk Association of Sound Designers]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Garethowensound/ Facebook Page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owen, Gareth}}\n[[Category:Sound designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Gareth Owen\n| image         =Gareth Owen - Sound Designer - Biog Photo - Full Size.jpg\n| birth_name     = Gareth John Owen\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1977|8|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = Sheffield, England\n| nationality    = British\n| education    = University of Plymouth\n| occupation    = Theatrical Sound Designer\n| years_active   = 1998\u2013present\n| children      = 2\n| website         = {{official site}}\n| imagesize     =\n}}\n\n'''Gareth Owen''' is an eight-time Tony & Olivier Award-winning/nominated [[sound design]]er specialising in musical theatre in London's West End, on Broadway and internationally.\n\n==Career==\n\nOwen was nominated for his first [[Tony Award]] in 2010 for his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of [[Trevor Nunn]]'s musical, ''[[A Little Night Music]]'' starring [[Catherine Zeta-Jones]] and [[Angela Lansbury]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibdb.com/awardperson.asp?id=485023 |title=IBDB Person Awards |work=Internet Broadway Database |access-date=4 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023134441/http://www.ibdb.com/awardperson.asp?id=485023 |archive-date=23 October 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe was then nominated for an [[Olivier Award]] for his [[West End theatre|West End]] production of [[Terry Johnson (dramatist)|Terry Johnson]]'s musical, [[End of the Rainbow]] starring multi-award-winning [[Tracie Bennett]] as [[Judy Garland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olivierawards.com/nominations/view/item114060/Best-Sound-Design/ |title=Olivier Award for Sound Design |work=The Olivier Awards |access-date=14 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110714235819/http://www.olivierawards.com/nominations/view/item114060/Best-Sound-Design/ |archive-date=14 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> The show later transferred to Broadway where he went on to pick up a further Tony nomination for Best Sound Design.\n\nIn recent years Owen collected a 2nd Oliver nomination for ''[[Top Hat (musical)|Top Hat]]'', and, after five nominations, finally won the Oliver for Best Sound Design in 2014 with the London production of ''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''.\n\nIn 2015 Owen won the Olivier for Sound Design for the second consecutive year, this time for [[Memphis (musical)|Memphis]] at the Shaftesbury Theatre, starring [[Beverley Knight]]. Composed by [[David Bryan]] from [[Bon Jovi]], and directed by [[Christopher Ashley]], this marked his sixth win/nomination in a row. He also received the prestigious Pro Sound Award for his work on the same production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prosoundawards.com//|title=Pro Sound Award for Best Theatre Sound|work=The Pro Sound Awards|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Owen won several awards for the Broadway musical [[Come from Away|''Come From Away'']] including the [[Outer Critics Circle Award]] and the [[Craig Noel|Craig Noel Award]], as well as a [[Helen Hayes Award]] nomination.\n\nGareth has worked on over two hundred and seventy-five commercial sound designs throughout the world including: ''[[42nd Street (musical)|42nd Street,]] [[Starlight Express]], [[Bat Out of Hell]], [[Wind in the Willows (musical)|Wind in the Willows,]]'' ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (musical)|Disney's Hunchback of Notre Dame]]'', ''[[Spring Awakening (musical)|Spring Awakening]]'', ''[[Young Frankenstein (musical)|Young Frankenstein]]'',''[[The Bodyguard (musical)|The Bodyguard]]'', ''[[Let It Be (musical)|Let it Be]]'', ''[[The Little Mermaid (musical)|Disney's Little Mermaid]]'', ''[[Sister Act (musical)|Sister Act]]'', ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'', ''[[Beauty and the Beast (musical)|Disney's Beauty & The Beast]]'', ''[[Singin' in the Rain (musical)|Singin' in the Rain]]'', ''[[Aspects of Love]]'', ''[[Footloose (musical)#Original London production|Footloose]]'', ''[[Flashdance]]'', ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'', ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'', ''[[Fame the Musical|Fame]]'', ''[[Saturday Night Fever (musical)|Saturday Night Fever]]'' and ''[[La Cage aux Folles (musical)|La Cage Aux Folles]]''.\n\n==Selected Awards==\n{{Awards table|2}}\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''The Donna Summer Musical''\n| NAACP Theatre Award for Best Sound Larger Theatre\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Starlight Express (Bochum)'' \n| Pro Sound Award \n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Carmen La Cubana]]''\n|Broadway World Germany Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|Broadway World Toronto Award for Best Original Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Bat Out of Hell The Musical]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|Broadway World Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Summer: The Donna Summer Musical]]''\n|Craig Noel Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Bat Out of Hell The Musical]]''\n|AV Technology Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[Outer Critics Circle Award]] for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Bat Out of Hell The Musical]]''\n|Broadway World Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|Dora Awards for Best Sound Design\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''Individual Recognition''\n|Pro Sound Award for Sound Engineer of the Year\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|Helen Hayes Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[A Bronx Tale (musical)|A Bronx Tale]]''\n|Broadway World Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Memphis (musical)|Memphis the Musical]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (musical)|Hunchback of Notre Dame]]''\n| Broadway World Awards for Best Sound Design\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2013\n| ''[[Top Hat (musical)|Top Hat]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n| ''[[I Can't Sing!]]''\n| Pro-Sound Award for Best Theatre Sound\n| {{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2012\n| ''[[End of the Rainbow]]''\n| [[Tony Award]] for Best Sound Design of a Musical\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2011\n| ''[[End of the Rainbow]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[A Little Night Music]]''\n| [[Tony Award]] for Best Sound Design of a Musical\n| {{Nominated}}\n| \n{{end}}\n\nIn 2015 Owen was elected Treasurer of The Association of Sound Designers, a UK based association representing nearly all the theatrical sound engineers in the country.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.garethowensound.com Official site]\n* {{IBDB name}}\n*[http://www.theasd.uk Association of Sound Designers]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Garethowensound/ Facebook Page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owen, Gareth}}\n[[Category:Sound designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n", "name_user": "Foolscap2000a", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gareth_Owen_(sound_designer)"}
{"title_page": "Jedhe", "text_new": "'''Jedhe''' is a [[Deshmukh]] sub clan of the [[Maratha]] caste in [[Maharashtra]], India.\n\nThe village of [[Kari, Bhor|Kari]], in modern [[Bhor taluka]] was the capital of the Jedhe Deshmukh.<ref name=\"Pagdi1974\">{{Cite book|author=Setumadhava Rao Pagdi|title=Chhatrapati Shivaji|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BKwdAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=22 June 2011|year=1974|publisher=Continental Prakashan}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=October 2012}} \n\nMoreover, the Jedhe were the pioneer house of Deshmukh among Marathas who supported Shivaji's kingdom and helped the [[Maratha Empire]] grow in its early stages.<ref name=\"PatwardhanRawlinson1978\">{{Cite book|author1=R. P. Patwardhan|author2=Hugh George Rawlinson|title=Source book of Maratha history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HtABAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=22 June 2011|year=1978|publisher=K. P. Bagchi}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=October 2012}} \n\n==Notables==\n*[[Kanhoji Jedhe]], 17th-century Marathi warrior\n*Keshavrao Jedhe, <ref name=\"Kotani19972\">{{Cite book|author=Hiroyuki Kotani|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kEZuAAAAMAAJ|title=Caste system, untouchability, and the depressed|publisher=Manohar Publishers & Distributors|year=1997|isbn=978-81-7304-204-1|accessdate=22 June 2011}}</ref>20th-century political leader also one of the founding member of PWPI\n*Sakaram Jedhe, 20th- century industrialist, he also one of three brothers of Keshavrao jedhe\n*Gulabrao Jedhe, 20th-century elected as member of parliament  baramati,pune by [[Indian National Congress]]\n*\n\n.<ref name=\"Kotani1997\">{{Cite book|author=Hiroyuki Kotani|title=Caste system, untouchability, and the depressed|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kEZuAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=22 June 2011|year=1997|publisher=Manohar Publishers & Distributors|isbn=978-81-7304-204-1}}</ref>\n\n\n*Mrunalini Balekundri, 21th- century a decorated military officer is also a notable descendant\n*Ayush Jedhe, 21th- century entrepreneur also member of '''Students' Federation of India''' [affiliated to the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]]]\n*\n\n==See also==\n* [[Maratha]]\n* [[Maratha Empire]]\n* [[Maratha clan system]]\n* [[List of Maratha dynasties and states]]\n* [[Bhonsle]]\n* [[Gaekwad]]\n* [[Scindia]]\n* [[Puars]]\n* [[Holkar]]\n* [[Peshwa]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Surnames]]\n", "text_old": "'''Jedhe''' is a [[Deshmukh]] sub clan of the [[Maratha]] caste in [[Maharashtra]], India.\n\nThe village of [[Kari, Bhor|Kari]], in modern [[Bhor taluka]] was the capital of the Jedhe Deshmukh.<ref name=\"Pagdi1974\">{{Cite book|author=Setumadhava Rao Pagdi|title=Chhatrapati Shivaji|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BKwdAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=22 June 2011|year=1974|publisher=Continental Prakashan}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=October 2012}} \n\nMoreover, the Jedhe were the pioneer house of Deshmukh among Marathas who supported Shivaji's kingdom and helped the [[Maratha Empire]] grow in its early stages.<ref name=\"PatwardhanRawlinson1978\">{{Cite book|author1=R. P. Patwardhan|author2=Hugh George Rawlinson|title=Source book of Maratha history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HtABAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=22 June 2011|year=1978|publisher=K. P. Bagchi}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=October 2012}} \n\n==Notables==\n*[[Kanhoji Jedhe]], 17th-century Marathi warrior\n.<ref name=\"Kotani1997\">{{Cite book|author=Hiroyuki Kotani|title=Caste system, untouchability, and the depressed|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kEZuAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=22 June 2011|year=1997|publisher=Manohar Publishers & Distributors|isbn=978-81-7304-204-1}}</ref>\n*Mrunalini Balekundri, a decorated military officer is also a notable descendant\n\n==See also==\n* [[Maratha]]\n* [[Maratha Empire]]\n* [[Maratha clan system]]\n* [[List of Maratha dynasties and states]]\n* [[Bhonsle]]\n* [[Gaekwad]]\n* [[Scindia]]\n* [[Puars]]\n* [[Holkar]]\n* [[Peshwa]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Surnames]]\n", "name_user": "Ayush jedhe", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated the information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jedhe"}
{"title_page": "Operation Identification", "text_new": "'''Operation Identification''' is a citizen's burglary prevention program for use in homes and businesses<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tucsonaz.gov/files/police/nhw_operation_id.pdf |title=Operation ID |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Tucson Police Department |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> that was developed in the United States during the 1960s.\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Operation Identification Miami-Dade.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Operation Identification sign in [[Miami-Dade County]], Florida]]\n\nThe Operation Identification program is designed to reduce theft, help police make arrests if a burglary does occur, and improve the recoverability of stolen property.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://mypropertyidregistry.com/2019/01/01/five-old-fashioned-ways-to-help-police/  |title=Five Old-Fashioned Ways to Help Police |last= |first= |date=2019-01-01 |publisher=My Property ID Registry |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe program encouraged participation to:<ref name=\":0\"/>\n*mark valuable property with a unique identifier such that it can be traced back to the owner.\n*make a secure list of marked property: its make, model, and the [[serial number]].\n*place visible signs or stickers to inform others that the content of a home or business contains property marked with identifiers.\n\nThe program aims to make it more difficult for burglars to dispose of stolen goods as they can be traced back to the original owner and improve the likelihood of participates recovering their stolen property. Also, people found in possession of marked goods provide the police with solid evidence of criminal activity. Operation Identification signs and stickers are used to act as a deterrent to would-be criminals who may decide to try elsewhere when informed of the added traceability of the goods.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mdle.net/brochures/ident.pdf  |title=Operation Identification |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Maryland Police and Correctional Training Commissions |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nOperation Identification was developed at a similar time as [[Neighborhood Watch]] was being promoted.<ref name=\":0\"/> Unlike Neighborhood Watch, Operation Identification did not find widespread use, even though it was endorsed by significant organizations such as the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mypropertyidregistry.com/2018/08/04/operation-id-marketing-flop/  |title=Operation ID: Biggest Marketing Flop in U.S. History |last= |first= |date=2018-08-04 |publisher=My Property ID Registry |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Despite this, Operation Identification is still promoted by many police departments and colleges across the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cityoftaylor.com/655/Operation-Identification  |title=Operation Identification  |last= |first= |date= |publisher=City of Taylor |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\"Operation Identification\">{{cite web |url=https://www.amherst.edu/offices/campus_police/programs/operation_id/node/29577  |title=Operation Identification |last= |first= |date= |publisher=University of Amherst |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Operation Identification City Park Denver.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Operation Identification sign in [[Denver]], Colorado]]\n\nOperation Identification was initially developed in the United States by the police in 1963.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mypropertyidregistry.com/2018/11/07/police-endorse-operation-id/  |title=Law Enforcement Professionals Endorse Operation ID |last= |first= |date=2018-11-07 |publisher=My Property ID Registry |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> This was in response to the growing incidence of theft across the nation. Between 1974 and 1978, the [[Law Enforcement Assistance Administration]] reported roughly $26 million ($115 million in 2020 dollars) of funding for 378 crime prevention projects with an Operation Identification component. Police departments would sponsor Operation Identification programs for residents, and many neighborhood organizations promoted and implemented marking programs.<ref name=gao>{{cite web |url=https://www.gao.gov/assets/130/126467.pdf  |title=Memo B-171019 |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Government Accountability Office |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nProperty marking was also encouraged by private companies and insurance companies. A national insurance association offered clients free engravers, literature, and participation stickers with other insurance companies offering discounts to clients who marked their property. One company provided customers a service where they would be provided an engraver, window stickers, and inventory sheets. Then the identity and current address of the enrolee, along with the assigned number, were stored in a data bank for retrieval.<ref name=gao/>\n\nMost of the effort to encourage property marking was aimed at the personal property of private citizens but some businesses along with state and local governmental units also participated.<ref name=gao/>\n\nA 1979 survey by the [[Government Accountability Office]] (GAO) primarily performed in New York State and at federal agencies in [[Washington D.C.]] indicated that Operation Identification was being widely implemented and showing benefits although it had not been pursued by any Federal agency. Of the 28 police departments contacted during the survey, 21 were implementing property marking programs.<ref name=gao/> Following this survey, Operation Identification was rolled out by the US Department of Justice in 1979.<ref name=\":1979\">{{cite web |url=https://mypropertyidregistry.com/2017/06/21/government-accountability-office-gao-validates-operation-identification-1979/  |title=Government Accountability Office (GAO) Validates Operation Identification |last= |first= |date=2017-06-21 |publisher=My Property ID Registry |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe program was endorsed by the:<ref name=\":1979\"/>\n\n*[[National Sheriff's Association]]\n*[[International Association of Chiefs of Police]]\n*[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]\n*[[National Crime Information Center]]\n*[[National Crime Prevention Association]]\n*[[National Council on Crime and Delinquency]]\n*[[Independent insurance agent|Independent Insurance Agents and Brokers of America]]<ref>[https://www.independentagent.com/default.aspx Independent Insurance Agents and Brokers of America]</ref>\n*[[American Farm Bureau]]\n*[[Law Enforcement Assistance Administration]]\n\n===Identifiers===\nOperation Identification was hindered by the lack of a single unique identifier or a system of identifiers being installed to aid police operations. The use of numerous different identifiers inhibited the police efforts to return stolen property to its owners.\n\nOf the 21 police departments implementing a form of property marking programs contacted during the 1979 GAO survey:\n\n*5 recommended [[driver's license]] numbers\n*5 recommended [[Social Security number]]s\n*2 utilized a state-devised identifier\n*9 did not encourage the use of a specific identifier\n\nEven with a recommended identifier, participants in the program used vague identifiers such as initials or identifiers that were subject to change such as [[ZIP code]]s and telephone numbers making the return of stolen goods difficult.\n\nAn evaluation funded by the [[Law Enforcement Assistance Administration]] in 1975 found that Operation Identification participants did experience few burglaries than their neighbors. However, the evaluation reported that burglars did not find it more difficult to dispose of marked property and that marked property recovered by police was not more likely to be returned to the owners. The evaluation stated the absence of a unique and permanent identifier for each property owner in the United States as a reason for these shortcomings of the program.<ref name=gao/>\n\n==Current use==\nOperation Identification is still endorsed by police in the United States with many departments actively promoting the program.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cityoftaylor.com/655/Operation-Identification  |title=Operation Identification |last= |first= |date= |publisher=City of Taylor |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> As well as police departments, Operation Identification is encouraged for students by colleges across the country.<ref name=\"Operation Identification\"/>\n\nThere are some private companies that partner directly with the police, giving them ready access to [[serial number]]s collected and entered by citizens. These companies frequently dispense with marking property or use pre-Internet marking strategies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.serialnumberregistry.ca/  |title=Serial Number Registry |last= |first= |date= |publisher= |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.immobilise.com/  |title=Immobilise |last= |first= |date= |publisher= |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThere are newer companies that issue uniquely numbered identifier tags associated with a unique website that allows only the rightful owner of the property to enter and access serial numbers. If an account holder is a victim of a crime, it is up to them to provide police with serial numbers, so they can be entered into the [[National Crime Information Center]]. This strategy, via the internet, also connects a [[Good Samaritan]] with the rightful owner if the identifying tag is intact, using a regulated [[Anonymous P2P]] communication strategy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mypropertyidregistry.com/  |title=My Property ID Registry |last= |first= |date= |publisher= |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n===Outside the United States===\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], the [[Metropolitan Police]] recommend similar property marking techniques to Operation Identification. They suggest the use of approved marking solutions in the form of a special marker pen or paint only visible under ultraviolet (UV) light to mark or etch personal property with the postcode, house or flat number or the first three letters of the owner's address. They also encourage that valuable items are registered with an accredited property database.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.met.police.uk/cp/crime-prevention/residential-burglary/mark-your-property/  |title=Mark your property to deter burglars |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Metropolitan Police |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==LPCB guidelines==\nIn 1996, the Loss Prevention Certification\u00a0Board (LPCB) issued its first set of guidelines\u00a0for the migration of Operation Identification to the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bregroup.com/products/lpcb  |title=LPCB standards and certification |last= |first= |date= |publisher=BRE Group |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n*''Loss Prevention Standard LPS 1224'' Issue 3.1 (2014) lists the requirements for companies providing secure asset registration services. This standard specifies requirements for asset registration companies providing secure asset registration services designed to support the identification and repatriation of assets when those assets are lost or stolen.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.redbooklive.com/download/pdf/LPS1224.pdf  |title=Loss Prevention Standard LPS 1224 Issue 3.1 |last= |first= |date=2014 |publisher=Red Book Live |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n*''Loss Prevention Standard (LPS) 1225'' Issue 3.2 (2014) lists the requirements for asset marking systems. This standard specifies requirements for the composition and performance of an asset marking system such that, when used according to the manufacturer's instructions, the asset marking device may: i) enable the marked asset to be traced to the legal owner via a secure database register linked to the marking system employed, and ii) act as a theft deterrent in the first instance by virtue of a visible marking.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.redbooklive.com/download/pdf/LPS1225.pdf |title=Loss Prevention Standard LPS 1224 Issue 3.2 |last= |first= |date=2014 |publisher=Red Book Live |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Neighborhood watch]]\n*[[Crime prevention]]\n*[[Bike registry]]\n*[[Vehicle registration plate]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Neighborhood watch organizations]]\n[[Category:Civil crime prevention]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement techniques]]\n[[Category:Online databases]]\n", "text_old": "'''Operation Identification''' is a citizen's burglary prevention program for use in homes and businesses<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tucsonaz.gov/files/police/nhw_operation_id.pdf |title=Operation ID |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Tucson Police Department |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> that was developed in the United States during the 1960s.\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Operation Identification Miami-Dade.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Operation Identification sign in [[Miami-Dade County]], Florida]]\n\nThe Operation Identification program is designed to reduce theft, help police make arrests if a burglary does occur, and improve the recoverability of stolen property.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://mypropertyidregistry.com/2019/01/01/five-old-fashioned-ways-to-help-police/  |title=Five Old-Fashioned Ways to Help Police |last= |first= |date=2019-01-01 |publisher=My Property ID Registry |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe program encouraged participation to:<ref name=\":0\"/>\n*mark valuable property with a unique identifier such that it can be traced back to the owner.\n*make a secure list of marked property: its make, model, and the [[serial number]].\n*place visible signs or stickers to inform others that the content of a home or business contains property marked with identifiers.\n\nThe program aims to make it more difficult for burglars to dispose of stolen goods as they can be traced back to the original owner and improve the likelihood of participates recovering their stolen property. Also, people found in possession of marked goods provide the police with solid evidence of criminal activity. Operation Identification signs and stickers are used to act as a deterrent to would-be criminals who may decide to try elsewhere when informed of the added traceability of the goods.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mdle.net/brochures/ident.pdf  |title=Operation Identification |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Maryland Police and Correctional Training Commissions |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nOperation Identification was developed at a similar time as [[Neighborhood Watch]] was being promoted.<ref name=\":0\"/> Unlike Neighborhood Watch, Operation Identification did not find widespread use, even though it was endorsed by significant organizations such as the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mypropertyidregistry.com/2018/08/04/operation-id-marketing-flop/  |title=Operation ID: Biggest Marketing Flop in U.S. History |last= |first= |date=2018-08-04 |publisher=My Property ID Registry |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Despite this, Operation Identification is still promoted by many police departments and colleges across the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cityoftaylor.com/655/Operation-Identification  |title=Operation Identification  |last= |first= |date= |publisher=City of Taylor |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\"Operation Identification\">{{cite web |url=https://www.amherst.edu/offices/campus_police/programs/operation_id/node/29577  |title=Operation Identification |last= |first= |date= |publisher=University of Amherst |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOperation Identification was initially developed in the United States by the police in 1963.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mypropertyidregistry.com/2018/11/07/police-endorse-operation-id/  |title=Law Enforcement Professionals Endorse Operation ID |last= |first= |date=2018-11-07 |publisher=My Property ID Registry |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> This was in response to the growing incidence of theft across the nation. Between 1974 and 1978, the [[Law Enforcement Assistance Administration]] reported roughly $26 million ($115 million in 2020 dollars) of funding for 378 crime prevention projects with an Operation Identification component. Police departments would sponsor Operation Identification programs for residents, and many neighborhood organizations promoted and implemented marking programs.<ref name=gao>{{cite web |url=https://www.gao.gov/assets/130/126467.pdf  |title=Memo B-171019 |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Government Accountability Office |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nProperty marking was also encouraged by private companies and insurance companies. A national insurance association offered clients free engravers, literature, and participation stickers with other insurance companies offering discounts to clients who marked their property. One company provided customers a service where they would be provided an engraver, window stickers, and inventory sheets. Then the identity and current address of the enrolee, along with the assigned number, were stored in a data bank for retrieval.<ref name=gao/>\n\nMost of the effort to encourage property marking was aimed at the personal property of private citizens but some businesses along with state and local governmental units also participated.<ref name=gao/>\n\nA 1979 survey by the [[Government Accountability Office]] (GAO) primarily performed in New York State and at federal agencies in [[Washington D.C.]] indicated that Operation Identification was being widely implemented and showing benefits although it had not been pursued by any Federal agency. Of the 28 police departments contacted during the survey, 21 were implementing property marking programs.<ref name=gao/> Following this survey, Operation Identification was rolled out by the US Department of Justice in 1979.<ref name=\":1979\">{{cite web |url=https://mypropertyidregistry.com/2017/06/21/government-accountability-office-gao-validates-operation-identification-1979/  |title=Government Accountability Office (GAO) Validates Operation Identification |last= |first= |date=2017-06-21 |publisher=My Property ID Registry |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe program was endorsed by the:<ref name=\":1979\"/>\n\n*[[National Sheriff's Association]]\n*[[International Association of Chiefs of Police]]\n*[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]\n*[[National Crime Information Center]]\n*[[National Crime Prevention Association]]\n*[[National Council on Crime and Delinquency]]\n*[[Independent insurance agent|Independent Insurance Agents and Brokers of America]]<ref>[https://www.independentagent.com/default.aspx Independent Insurance Agents and Brokers of America]</ref>\n*[[American Farm Bureau]]\n*[[Law Enforcement Assistance Administration]]\n\n===Identifiers===\nOperation Identification was hindered by the lack of a single unique identifier or a system of identifiers being installed to aid police operations. The use of numerous different identifiers inhibited the police efforts to return stolen property to its owners.\n\nOf the 21 police departments implementing a form of property marking programs contacted during the 1979 GAO survey:\n\n*5 recommended [[driver's license]] numbers\n*5 recommended [[Social Security number]]s\n*2 utilized a state-devised identifier\n*9 did not encourage the use of a specific identifier\n\nEven with a recommended identifier, participants in the program used vague identifiers such as initials or identifiers that were subject to change such as [[ZIP code]]s and telephone numbers making the return of stolen goods difficult.\n\nAn evaluation funded by the [[Law Enforcement Assistance Administration]] in 1975 found that Operation Identification participants did experience few burglaries than their neighbors. However, the evaluation reported that burglars did not find it more difficult to dispose of marked property and that marked property recovered by police was not more likely to be returned to the owners. The evaluation stated the absence of a unique and permanent identifier for each property owner in the United States as a reason for these shortcomings of the program.<ref name=gao/>\n\n==Current use==\nOperation Identification is still endorsed by police in the United States with many departments actively promoting the program.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cityoftaylor.com/655/Operation-Identification  |title=Operation Identification |last= |first= |date= |publisher=City of Taylor |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> As well as police departments, Operation Identification is encouraged for students by colleges across the country.<ref name=\"Operation Identification\"/>\n\nThere are some private companies that partner directly with the police, giving them ready access to [[serial number]]s collected and entered by citizens. These companies frequently dispense with marking property or use pre-Internet marking strategies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.serialnumberregistry.ca/  |title=Serial Number Registry |last= |first= |date= |publisher= |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.immobilise.com/  |title=Immobilise |last= |first= |date= |publisher= |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThere are newer companies that issue uniquely numbered identifier tags associated with a unique website that allows only the rightful owner of the property to enter and access serial numbers. If an account holder is a victim of a crime, it is up to them to provide police with serial numbers, so they can be entered into the [[National Crime Information Center]]. This strategy, via the internet, also connects a [[Good Samaritan]] with the rightful owner if the identifying tag is intact, using a regulated [[Anonymous P2P]] communication strategy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mypropertyidregistry.com/  |title=My Property ID Registry |last= |first= |date= |publisher= |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n===Outside the United States===\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], the [[Metropolitan Police]] recommend similar property marking techniques to Operation Identification. They suggest the use of approved marking solutions in the form of a special marker pen or paint only visible under ultraviolet (UV) light to mark or etch personal property with the postcode, house or flat number or the first three letters of the owner's address. They also encourage that valuable items are registered with an accredited property database.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.met.police.uk/cp/crime-prevention/residential-burglary/mark-your-property/  |title=Mark your property to deter burglars |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Metropolitan Police |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==LPCB guidelines==\nIn 1996, the Loss Prevention Certification\u00a0Board (LPCB) issued its first set of guidelines\u00a0for the migration of Operation Identification to the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bregroup.com/products/lpcb  |title=LPCB standards and certification |last= |first= |date= |publisher=BRE Group |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n*''Loss Prevention Standard LPS 1224'' Issue 3.1 (2014) lists the requirements for companies providing secure asset registration services. This standard specifies requirements for asset registration companies providing secure asset registration services designed to support the identification and repatriation of assets when those assets are lost or stolen.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.redbooklive.com/download/pdf/LPS1224.pdf  |title=Loss Prevention Standard LPS 1224 Issue 3.1 |last= |first= |date=2014 |publisher=Red Book Live |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n*''Loss Prevention Standard (LPS) 1225'' Issue 3.2 (2014) lists the requirements for asset marking systems. This standard specifies requirements for the composition and performance of an asset marking system such that, when used according to the manufacturer's instructions, the asset marking device may: i) enable the marked asset to be traced to the legal owner via a secure database register linked to the marking system employed, and ii) act as a theft deterrent in the first instance by virtue of a visible marking.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.redbooklive.com/download/pdf/LPS1225.pdf |title=Loss Prevention Standard LPS 1224 Issue 3.2 |last= |first= |date=2014 |publisher=Red Book Live |access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Neighborhood watch]]\n*[[Crime prevention]]\n*[[Bike registry]]\n*[[Vehicle registration plate]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Neighborhood watch organizations]]\n[[Category:Civil crime prevention]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement techniques]]\n[[Category:Online databases]]\n", "name_user": "Sgt. Dan Smythe", "label": "safe", "comment": "Denver signage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_Identification"}
{"title_page": "Peter Davies (economic historian)", "text_new": "[[File:Professor Peter Davies in Tokyo, Japan, October 2011.jpg|thumb|Peter Davies in Tokyo, Japan, October 2011]]\n\n'''Peter N. Davies''' (born [[Birkenhead]], 14 July 1927, died [[Caldy]], [[Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|Wirral]] 19 March 2020) was a British economic historian with interests in the port of [[Liverpool]], sea-based trade with [[West Africa]], the [[Canary Islands]] and [[Japan]], the international fruit trade and the military history of the [[Khwae Yai River|River Kwai]] campaign in [[World War II]]. He was an Emeritus Professor in the School of History at the [[University of Liverpool]], [[England]].\n\nDavies was the author of several books including, \"The Trade Makers, [[Elder Dempster]] in West Africa\" (Allen and Unwin, 1973), \"Trading in West Africa\" (Croom Helm, 1976), \"Sir Alfred Jones: Shipping Entrepreneur par Excellence\" (Europa, 1978), \"[[Fyffes]] and the Banana, Musa Sapientum\" (Athlone Press, 1990), \"Japanese Shipping and Shipbuilding Industries: A History of Their Modern Growth\" (with T. Chida, Athlone Press, 1990), \"The Man Behind the Bridge: Colonel Toosey and the [[Khwae Yai River|River Kwai]]\" (Athlone Press, 1991), and \"From Orchard to Market\" (with D.Hope-Mason, Lockwood Press, 2005).\n\nDuring a long career at the [[University of Liverpool]] which began when he entered as an undergraduate in 1958, Davies continued the tradition of commitment to Maritime History which had been initiated by Francis Hyde and maintained by John Harris (subsequently Professor of Economic History at the [[University of Birmingham]]) and Sheila Marriner. Taken together, Hyde, Harris, Marriner and Davies have become known as the \"Liverpool School of Maritime Historians\".<ref>Davies PN, \"The Liverpool School of Maritime History\". International Journal of Maritime History (2005);XVII, 2 pp249\u2013260.</ref><ref>Milne G, \"Trade and Traders in Mid-Victorian Liverpool: Mercantile Business and the Making of a World Port\" (Liverpool University Press, 2000) pp 5\u20136.</ref>\n\n\"The Business, Life and Letters of Frederick Cornes : Aspects of the Evolution of Commerce in Modern Japan, 1861-1912\"  (Global Oriental: {{ISBN|1-905246-34-X}}) was published in September 2008. In this book Davies examined the surprisingly well-preserved papers of Frederick Cornes, a merchant from [[Cheshire]], England who spent much of his life trading in Japan's port city of [[Yokohama]] during and after the [[Meiji Restoration]], including the entire correspondence of \"Cornes and Company\" extending over a forty-year period in the early years of Anglo-Japanese trade.\n\nDavies's last book, \"Across the Three Pagodas Pass: The Story of the Thai-Burma Railway\" (Renaissance Books: {{ISBN|978-1-898823-07-0}}), was published in August 2013. Davies acted as editor to Ewart Escritt's translation of the personal records of Japanese Railway Engineer Yoshihiko Futamatsu. Davies had come to know Futamatsu through his research for the 1991 biography of [[Philip Toosey]] \"The Man Behind the Bridge\" and secured his agreement that his memoirs could be published in English after his death.<ref>Davies PN (ed), Futamatsu Y \"Across the Three Pagodas Pass: The Story of the Thai-Burma Railway\" (Renaissance Books: {{ISBN|978-1-898823-07-0}}).</ref> The book is therefore a rare account from the Japanese viewpoint of the construction of the Thai-Burma Railway (and the [[Khwae Yai River|River Kwai]] Bridge) during [[World War II]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Peter}}\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Birkenhead]]\n[[Category:Economic historians]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n[[Category:British maritime historians]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Professor Peter Davies in Tokyo, Japan, October 2011.jpg|thumb|Peter Davies in Tokyo, Japan, October 2011]]\n\n'''Peter N. Davies''' (born [[Birkenhead]], 14 July 1927, died [[Caldy]],[[Wirral]], 19 March 2020) was a British economic historian with interests in the port of [[Liverpool]], sea-based trade with [[West Africa]], the [[Canary Islands]] and [[Japan]], the international fruit trade and the military history of the [[Khwae Yai River|River Kwai]] campaign in [[World War II]]. He was an Emeritus Professor in the School of History at the [[University of Liverpool]], [[England]].\n\nDavies was the author of several books including, \"The Trade Makers, [[Elder Dempster]] in West Africa\" (Allen and Unwin, 1973), \"Trading in West Africa\" (Croom Helm, 1976), \"Sir Alfred Jones: Shipping Entrepreneur par Excellence\" (Europa, 1978), \"[[Fyffes]] and the Banana, Musa Sapientum\" (Athlone Press, 1990), \"Japanese Shipping and Shipbuilding Industries: A History of Their Modern Growth\" (with T. Chida, Athlone Press, 1990), \"The Man Behind the Bridge: Colonel Toosey and the [[Khwae Yai River|River Kwai]]\" (Athlone Press, 1991), and \"From Orchard to Market\" (with D.Hope-Mason, Lockwood Press, 2005).\n\nDuring a long career at the [[University of Liverpool]], Davies continued the tradition of commitment to Maritime History which had been initiated by Francis Hyde and maintained by John Harris (subsequently Professor of Economic History at the [[University of Birmingham]]) and Sheila Marriner. Taken together, Hyde, Harris, Marriner and Davies have become known as the \"Liverpool School of Maritime Historians\".<ref>Davies PN, \"The Liverpool School of Maritime History\". International Journal of Maritime History (2005);XVII, 2 pp249\u2013260.</ref><ref>Milne G, \"Trade and Traders in Mid-Victorian Liverpool: Mercantile Business and the Making of a World Port\" (Liverpool University Press, 2000) pp 5\u20136.</ref>\n\n\"The Business, Life and Letters of Frederick Cornes : Aspects of the Evolution of Commerce in Modern Japan, 1861-1912\"  (Global Oriental: {{ISBN|1-905246-34-X}}) was published in September 2008. In this book Davies examined the surprisingly well-preserved papers of Frederick Cornes, a merchant from [[Cheshire]], England who spent much of his life trading in Japan's port city of [[Yokohama]] during and after the [[Meiji Restoration]], including the entire correspondence of \"Cornes and Company\" extending over a forty-year period in the early years of Anglo-Japanese trade.\n\nDavies's last book, \"Across the Three Pagodas Pass: The Story of the Thai-Burma Railway\" (Renaissance Books: {{ISBN|978-1-898823-07-0}}), was published in August 2013. Davies acted as editor to Ewart Escritt's translation of the personal records of Japanese Railway Engineer Yoshihiko Futamatsu. Davies had come to know Futamatsu through his research for the 1991 biography of [[Philip Toosey]] \"The Man Behind the Bridge\" and secured his agreement that his memoirs could be published in English after his death.<ref>Davies PN (ed), Futamatsu Y \"Across the Three Pagodas Pass: The Story of the Thai-Burma Railway\" (Renaissance Books: {{ISBN|978-1-898823-07-0}}).</ref> The book is therefore a rare account from the Japanese viewpoint of the construction of the Thai-Burma Railway (and the [[Khwae Yai River|River Kwai]] Bridge) during [[World War II]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Peter}}\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Birkenhead]]\n[[Category:Economic historians]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n[[Category:British maritime historians]]\n", "name_user": "Simonjcdavies", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected link to Wirral", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Davies_(economic_historian)"}
{"title_page": "Adventures of Pip", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Adventures of Pip\n| image = Adventures of Pip cover.png\n| alt = \n| developer = Tic Toc Games\n| publisher = Tic Toc Games\n| composer = [[Jake Kaufman]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Wii U]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]], [[iOS]]\n| released = '''Windows, OS X'''{{Video game release|WW|June 4, 2015}}'''Wii  U'''{{Video game release|NA|June 4, 2015|EU|January 21, 2016}}'''iOS'''{{Video game release|NA|July 2, 2015}}'''PlayStation 4'''{{Video game release|NA|August 18, 2015|EU|February 9, 2016}}'''Xbox One'''{{Video game release|WW|August 21, 2015}}\n| genre = [[Action game|Action]], [[Platform game|platform]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n'''''Adventures of Pip''''' is a 2D side scrolling action platform video game developed and published by [[independent video game developer]] Tic Toc Games. The game launched in June 2015 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], and [[Wii U]] and in July 2015 for [[iOS]]. [[Xbox One]] and [[PlayStation 4]] versions were released in August 2015.\n\n== Gameplay ==\nIn ''Adventures of Pip'', the player plays as Pip, a single [[pixel]] born into a world of [[high resolution|hi-res]] and [[low resolution|lo-res]] characters.  As Pip defeats his enemies, he gains the ability to evolve into an 8-bit [[hero]] and later a 16-bit hero.  Each evolution has its advantages and disadvantages.  Pip must switch between his evolutions to complete levels. Players will need to evolve and devolve, wall jump, run, shove, break blocks, float, collect, and fight their way through bosses and henchmen till they get to the Evil Queen DeRezia.<ref>[http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/wiiu-eshop/adventures_of_pip Adventures of Pip (Wii U eShop) Review], Nintendo World Report, Retrieved 2015-06-25</ref><ref>[http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/wiiu-eshop/adventures_of_pip Adventures of Pip], [[Nintendo Life]], Retrieved 2015-06-25</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nAn evil witch has come and turned the King and Queen into pixels and kidnapped Princess Adeline. It's up to Pip to venture forth and navigate the strange landscapes to rescue the damsel in distress from the clutches of Queen DeRezzia.<ref>[http://www.gaming-age.com/2015/06/adventures-of-pip-review-for-wii-u/ Adventures of Pip review for Wii U], Gaming-age.com, Retrieved 2015-06-25</ref><ref>[http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/06/05/review-adventures-of-pip/152043/ Review: Adventures of Pip], Hardcore Gamer, Retrieved 2015-06-25</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = PC: 72/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/adventures-of-pip |title=Adventures of Pip for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-08-04}}</ref><br />WIIU: 78/100<ref name=\"MCWIIU\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/adventures-of-pip |title=Adventures of Pip for Wii U Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2015-07-05}}</ref><br />PS4: 74/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/adventures-of-pip |title=Adventures of Pip for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-08-04}}</ref>\n| EGM = 8/10<ref name=\"EGM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/adventures-of-pip-review/|title=Adventures of Pip review|author=Andrew Fitch|work=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]|date=2015-06-09|accessdate=2015-07-05}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''Hardcore Gamer''\n| rev1Score = 4/5<ref name=\"hardcore gamer review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/06/05/review-adventures-of-pip/152043/|title=Review: Adventures of Pip |work=Hardcore Gamer|publisher=Hardcore Gamer|first=Dermot|last=Creegan|date= 5 June 2015|accessdate=2015-07-05}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[TouchArcade]]''\n| rev2Score = iOS: {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toucharcade.com/2015/07/13/adventures-of-pip-review/ |title='Adventures of Pip' Review \u2013 I Came In Like A Rectangle |last=Reinauer |first=Nathan |date=2015-07-13 |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=2018-08-04}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Adventures of Pip'' has received mostly positive reviews from critics, with the Wii U version scoring 78/100 on [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MCWIIU\" />\n\nDermot Creegan of ''Hardcore Gamer'' gave the game a 4 out of 5 saying, \"Adventures of Pip is a delightful little platformer full of charm, challenge and impeccable level design.\"<ref name=\"hardcore gamer review\" /> Andrew Fitch from ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' rated the game a 8/10 saying, \"Tic Toc Games\u2019 impressive pedigree at WayForward is on full display in Adventures of Pip\u2014one of the only problems is that it's not quite as feature-rich as you'd like.\"<ref name=\"EGM\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tictocgames.com/adventures-of-pip/ ''Adventures of Pip'' at Tic Toc Games]\n\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Kickstarter-funded video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Platform games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling video games]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Jake Kaufman]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Wii U games]]\n[[Category:Wii U eShop games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Adventures of Pip\n| image = Adventures of Pip cover.png\n| alt = \n| developer = Tic Toc Games\n| publisher = Tic Toc Games\n| composer = [[Jake Kaufman]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Wii U]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]], [[iOS]]\n| released = '''Windows, OS X'''{{Video game release|WW|June 4, 2015}}'''Wii  U'''{{Video game release|NA|June 4, 2015|EU|January 21, 2016}}'''iOS'''{{Video game release|NA|July 2, 2015}}'''PlayStation 4'''{{Video game release|NA|August 18, 2015|EU|February 9, 2016}}'''Xbox One'''{{Video game release|WW|August 21, 2015}}\n| genre = [[Action game|Action]], [[Platform game|platform]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n'''''Adventures of Pip''''' is a 2D side scrolling action platform video game developed and published by [[independent video game developer]] Tic Toc Games. The game launched in June 2015 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], and [[Wii U]] and in July 2015 for [[iOS]]. [[Xbox One]] and [[PlayStation 4]] versions were released in August 2015.\n\n== Gameplay ==\nIn ''Adventures of Pip'', the player plays as Pip, a single [[pixel]] born into a world of [[high resolution|hi-res]] and [[low resolution|lo-res]] characters.  As Pip defeats his enemies, he gains the ability to evolve into an 8-bit [[hero]] and later a 16-bit hero.  Each evolution has its advantages and disadvantages.  Pip must switch between his evolutions to complete levels. Players will need to evolve and devolve, wall jump, run, shove, break blocks, float, collect, and fight their way through bosses and henchmen till they get to the Evil Queen DeRezia.<ref>[http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/wiiu-eshop/adventures_of_pip Adventures of Pip (Wii U eShop) Review], Nintendo World Report, Retrieved 2015-06-25</ref><ref>[http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/wiiu-eshop/adventures_of_pip Adventures of Pip], [[Nintendo Life]], Retrieved 2015-06-25</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nAn evil witch has come and turned the King and Queen into pixels and kidnapped Princess Adeline. It\u2019s up to Pip to venture forth and navigate the strange landscapes to rescue the damsel in distress from the clutches of Queen DeRezzia.<ref>[http://www.gaming-age.com/2015/06/adventures-of-pip-review-for-wii-u/ Adventures of Pip review for Wii U], Gaming-age.com, Retrieved 2015-06-25</ref><ref>[http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/06/05/review-adventures-of-pip/152043/ Review: Adventures of Pip], Hardcore Gamer, Retrieved 2015-06-25</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = PC: 72/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/adventures-of-pip |title=Adventures of Pip for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-08-04}}</ref><br />WIIU: 78/100<ref name=\"MCWIIU\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/adventures-of-pip |title=Adventures of Pip for Wii U Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2015-07-05}}</ref><br />PS4: 74/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/adventures-of-pip |title=Adventures of Pip for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-08-04}}</ref>\n| EGM = 8/10<ref name=\"EGM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/adventures-of-pip-review/|title=Adventures of Pip review|author=Andrew Fitch|work=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]|date=2015-06-09|accessdate=2015-07-05}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''Hardcore Gamer''\n| rev1Score = 4/5<ref name=\"hardcore gamer review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/06/05/review-adventures-of-pip/152043/|title=Review: Adventures of Pip |work=Hardcore Gamer|publisher=Hardcore Gamer|first=Dermot|last=Creegan|date= 5 June 2015|accessdate=2015-07-05}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[TouchArcade]]''\n| rev2Score = iOS: {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toucharcade.com/2015/07/13/adventures-of-pip-review/ |title='Adventures of Pip' Review \u2013 I Came In Like A Rectangle |last=Reinauer |first=Nathan |date=2015-07-13 |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=2018-08-04}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Adventures of Pip'' has received mostly positive reviews from critics, with the Wii U version scoring 78/100 on [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MCWIIU\" />\n\nDermot Creegan of ''Hardcore Gamer'' gave the game a 4 out of 5 saying, \"Adventures of Pip is a delightful little platformer full of charm, challenge and impeccable level design.\"<ref name=\"hardcore gamer review\" /> Andrew Fitch from ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' rated the game a 8/10 saying, \"Tic Toc Games\u2019 impressive pedigree at WayForward is on full display in Adventures of Pip\u2014one of the only problems is that it\u2019s not quite as feature-rich as you\u2019d like.\"<ref name=\"EGM\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tictocgames.com/adventures-of-pip/ ''Adventures of Pip'' at Tic Toc Games]\n\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Kickstarter-funded video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Platform games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling video games]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Jake Kaufman]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Wii U games]]\n[[Category:Wii U eShop games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "name_user": "Nealbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: you\u2019d \u2192 you'd, It\u2019s \u2192 It's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adventures_of_Pip"}
{"title_page": "Softwood", "text_new": "{{about||the plant propagation technique known as softwood cutting|Cutting (plant)|the software company|SoftWood}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2019}}\n[[file:Pinus sylvestris wood ray section 1 beentree.jpg|thumb|[[Scots Pine]], a typical and well-known softwood]]\n\n'''Softwood''' is [[wood]] from [[gymnosperm]] trees such as [[conifer]]s, as well as ''[[Amborella]]''. The term is opposed to [[hardwood]], which is the wood from [[angiosperm]] trees.\n\n==Characteristics==\nSoftwood is '''usually'' [[wood]] from [[sperm]] trees such as [[peen]]s. Softwoods are not necessarily softer than hardwoods.<ref name=\"Buckley\">{{cite web|last1=Buckley|first1=Michael|title=A basic guide to softwoods and hardwoods|url=http://www.worldhardwoods.com/files/articles_basicguide.pdf|publisher=worldhardwoods.com|date=2005|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> In both groups there is an enormous variation in actual wood hardness, the range of density in hardwoods completely including that of softwoods.  Some hardwoods (e.g. [[balsa]]) are softer than most softwoods, while the hardest hardwoods are much harder than any softwood. The woods of [[longleaf pine]], [[Douglas fir]], and [[Taxus|yew]] are much harder in the mechanical sense than several hardwoods.\n\nSoftwoods are generally most used by the construction industry and are also used to produce [[paper pulp]], and card products.<ref name=\"Ryan\">{{cite web|last1=Ryan|first1=V.|title=REVISION CARDS - SOFTWOODS |url=http://www.technologystudent.com/joints/softwoods1.html |date=2012|publisher=technologystudent.com|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> In many of these applications, there is a constant need for density and thickness monitoring and gamma-ray sensors have shown good performance in this case.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Beigzadeh |first1=A.M. |title=Design, modelling and construction of a continuous nuclear gauge for measuring the fluid levels |journal=Measurement |date=2019 |volume=138 |pages=157\u2013161 |doi=10.1016/j.measurement.2019.02.017 }}</ref>\n\nCertain species of softwood are more resistant to insect attack from [[woodworm]], as certain insects prefer damp hardwood.\n\nSoftwood reproduces using [[pine cones|cones]] and occasionally [[nut (fruit)|nuts]].\n\n==Examples of softwood trees and uses==\n* [[Douglas fir]] - [[Woodworking joints|joinery]], doors and heavy construction\n* [[Eastern white pine]] - furniture\n* [[European spruce]] - used throughout construction, panelling and cladding\n* [[Larch]] - used for cladding and boats\n* [[Lodgepole pine]] - roofing, flooring and in making chipboard and [[particle board]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Things we make from softwood trees|url=https://www.forestry.gov.uk/forestry/infd-52jc96|date=11 July 2017|publisher=forestry.gov.uk|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Parana pine]] - stair treads and joinery\n* [[Scots pine]] - construction industry, mostly for interior work\n* [[Sitka spruce]] - <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harding|first1=T.|title=British Softwoods:Properties and Uses |date=1988 |url=https://www.forestry.gov.uk/PDF/FCBU077.pdf/$FILE/FCBU077.pdf |publisher=forestry.gov.uk|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Southern yellow pine]] - joinery, flooring and [[Deck (building)|decking]]\n* [[Western hemlock]] - doors, joinery and furniture\n* [[Western red cedar]] (or red cedar) - furniture, decking, [[Cladding (construction)|cladding]], and [[roof shingles]] \n* [[Yew]] - interior and exterior furniture e.g. chairs, gate posts and wood turning\n\n==Applications==\nSoftwood is the source of about 80% of the world's production of [[timber]],<ref>United Nations {{google books|jSZxq4DQjIIC|Forest Products Annual Market Review 2007-2008|page=46}}</ref> with traditional centres of production being the [[Baltic region]] (including [[Scandinavia]] and [[Russia]]), [[North America]] and China. Softwood is typically used in construction as structural carcassing timber, as well as finishing timber.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of woods]]\n* [[United States \u2013 Canada softwood lumber dispute]]\n*[[Hardwood]]\n*[[Janka hardness test]]\n*[[Brinell scale]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Woodworking}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Trees}}\n\n[[Category:Forestry]]\n[[Category:Timber industry]]\n[[Category:Wood products]]\n[[Category:Woodworking]]\n[[Category:Wood|softwood]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the plant propagation technique known as softwood cutting|Cutting (plant)|the software company|SoftWood}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2019}}\n[[file:Pinus sylvestris wood ray section 1 beentree.jpg|thumb|[[Scots Pine]], a typical and well-known softwood]]\n\n'''Softwood''' is [[wood]] from [[gymnosperm]] trees such as [[conifer]]s, as well as ''[[Amborella]]''. The term is opposed to [[hardwood]], which is the wood from [[angiosperm]] trees.\n\n==Characteristics==\nSoftwood is usually [[wood]] from [[gymnosperm]] trees such as [[pine]]s and [[spruce]]s. Softwoods are not necessarily softer than hardwoods.<ref name=\"Buckley\">{{cite web|last1=Buckley|first1=Michael|title=A basic guide to softwoods and hardwoods|url=http://www.worldhardwoods.com/files/articles_basicguide.pdf|publisher=worldhardwoods.com|date=2005|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> In both groups there is an enormous variation in actual wood hardness, the range of density in hardwoods completely including that of softwoods.  Some hardwoods (e.g. [[balsa]]) are softer than most softwoods, while the hardest hardwoods are much harder than any softwood. The woods of [[longleaf pine]], [[Douglas fir]], and [[Taxus|yew]] are much harder in the mechanical sense than several hardwoods.\n\nSoftwoods are generally most used by the construction industry and are also used to produce [[paper pulp]], and card products.<ref name=\"Ryan\">{{cite web|last1=Ryan|first1=V.|title=REVISION CARDS - SOFTWOODS |url=http://www.technologystudent.com/joints/softwoods1.html |date=2012|publisher=technologystudent.com|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> In many of these applications, there is a constant need for density and thickness monitoring and gamma-ray sensors have shown good performance in this case.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Beigzadeh |first1=A.M. |title=Design, modelling and construction of a continuous nuclear gauge for measuring the fluid levels |journal=Measurement |date=2019 |volume=138 |pages=157\u2013161 |doi=10.1016/j.measurement.2019.02.017 }}</ref>\n\nCertain species of softwood are more resistant to insect attack from [[woodworm]], as certain insects prefer damp hardwood.\n\nSoftwood reproduces using [[pine cones|cones]] and occasionally [[nut (fruit)|nuts]].\n\n==Examples of softwood trees and uses==\n* [[Douglas fir]] - [[Woodworking joints|joinery]], doors and heavy construction\n* [[Eastern white pine]] - furniture\n* [[European spruce]] - used throughout construction, panelling and cladding\n* [[Larch]] - used for cladding and boats\n* [[Lodgepole pine]] - roofing, flooring and in making chipboard and [[particle board]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Things we make from softwood trees|url=https://www.forestry.gov.uk/forestry/infd-52jc96|date=11 July 2017|publisher=forestry.gov.uk|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Parana pine]] - stair treads and joinery\n* [[Scots pine]] - construction industry, mostly for interior work\n* [[Sitka spruce]] - <ref>{{cite web|last1=Harding|first1=T.|title=British Softwoods:Properties and Uses |date=1988 |url=https://www.forestry.gov.uk/PDF/FCBU077.pdf/$FILE/FCBU077.pdf |publisher=forestry.gov.uk|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Southern yellow pine]] - joinery, flooring and [[Deck (building)|decking]]\n* [[Western hemlock]] - doors, joinery and furniture\n* [[Western red cedar]] (or red cedar) - furniture, decking, [[Cladding (construction)|cladding]], and [[roof shingles]] \n* [[Yew]] - interior and exterior furniture e.g. chairs, gate posts and wood turning\n\n==Applications==\nSoftwood is the source of about 80% of the world's production of [[timber]],<ref>United Nations {{google books|jSZxq4DQjIIC|Forest Products Annual Market Review 2007-2008|page=46}}</ref> with traditional centres of production being the [[Baltic region]] (including [[Scandinavia]] and [[Russia]]), [[North America]] and China. Softwood is typically used in construction as structural carcassing timber, as well as finishing timber.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of woods]]\n* [[United States \u2013 Canada softwood lumber dispute]]\n*[[Hardwood]]\n*[[Janka hardness test]]\n*[[Brinell scale]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Woodworking}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Trees}}\n\n[[Category:Forestry]]\n[[Category:Timber industry]]\n[[Category:Wood products]]\n[[Category:Woodworking]]\n[[Category:Wood|softwood]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:22f:e00:a160:7f0e:8453:b47c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCharacteristics)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Softwood"}
{"title_page": "Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Redirect|San Rafael Bridge|the bridge in Utah|San Rafael Bridge (Utah)}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n|bridge_name     = Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge\n|image           = Richmond-San Rafeal Bridge.jpg\n|caption         = The Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge from its western terminus\n|official_name   = Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge or John F. McCarthy Memorial Bridge\n|also_known_as   = Richmond Bridge <br /> San Rafael Bridge\n|named_for       = [[John F. McCarthy]]\n|carries         = 5 lanes (2 WB on upper level, 2-3 EB on lower) of {{jct|state=CA|I|580}}, bike/pedestrian\n|crosses         = [[San Francisco Bay]] and [[San Pablo Bay]]\n|locale          = [[San Rafael, California]] and [[Richmond, California]]\n|owner           = [[State of California]]\n|maint           = [[California Department of Transportation]] and the [[Bay Area Toll Authority]]\n|heritage        = \n|id              = 28 0100\n|id_type         = \n|preceded        = \n|design          = [[Double-deck bridge|Double-Decked]] Dual [[Cantilever bridge]] with [[Pratt Truss]] Approach\n|mainspan        = {{convert|1070|ft}} cantilever structure\n|number_spans    = 77 in total, consisting of:<br/>\n19 girder spans (west)<br/>\n14 truss spans (west)<br/>\n3 spans (western cantilever)<br/>\n9 truss spans (center)<br/>\n3 spans (eastern cantilever)<br/>\n12 truss spans (east)<br/>\n17 girder spans (east)\n|piers_in_water  = 70<ref name=CHPW-19540304 />\n|length          = {{convert|29040|ft|mi km|abbr=on}}\n|width           = \n|height          = \n|clearance_above = \n|clearance_below = {{convert|185|ft}} (main channel) <br/> {{convert|135|ft}} (secondary channel)\n|traffic         = 66,800 (2011)<br/>\n67,800 (2012)<br/>\n72,300 (2013)<br/>\n75,600 (2014)<br/>\n79,200 (2015)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marinij.com/article/NO/20150809/NEWS/150809801 |title=Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Traffic volume hits five-year high |author=Prado, Mark |date=August 9, 2015 |newspaper=Marin Independent Journal |accessdate=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n|open            = {{start date and age|September 1, 1956}}\n|closed          = \n|cost            = {{US$|62000000|1956|round=-5}}\n|architect       = \n|designer        = Norman Raab\n|winner          = \n|engineering     = \n|builder         = Gerwick\u2014Kiewit Joint Venture (substructure) <br/> Kiewit\u2014Soda\u2014Judson Pacific-Murphy Joint Venture (superstructure)\n|fabricator      = \n|begin           = March 1953\n|complete        = \n|replaces        = \n|toll            = Cars (westbound only) <br /> $6.00 (cash or [[FasTrak]]), $3.00 (carpools during peak hours, FasTrak only)\n|coordinates     = {{coord|37.9347|-122.4338|scale:50000_region:US-CA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|mapframe_zoom   = 9\n|map_caption     = Interactive map highlighting the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge\n}}\n\nThe '''Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge''' (also officially named the '''John F. McCarthy Memorial Bridge'''<ref>[http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/tsip/hseb/products/Named_Freeways_Final.pdf 2013 Named Freeways, Highways, Structures and Other Appurtenances in California], California Department of Transportation, 2013, pp. 150, 154 and 246. This State of California document indicates that the bridge has two official names, both enacted by legislative resolution, in 1955 and 1981 respectively.</ref>) is the northernmost of the east\u2013west crossings of the [[San Francisco Bay]] in [[California]], [[United States|USA]]. Officially named after California State Senator [[John F. McCarthy]], it bridges [[Interstate 580 (California)|Interstate 580]] from [[Richmond, California|Richmond]] on the east to [[San Rafael, California|San Rafael]] on the west. It opened in 1956, replacing ferry service by the [[Richmond\u2013San Rafael Ferry Company]].<ref name=\"quarry\">{{cite book | chapterurl = http://content.cdlib.org/view?docId=hb2m3nb1b0&chunk.id=div00033&doc.view=entire_text | chapter = Changes in the Richmond Waterfront |  accessdate = February 25, 2009 | title = Memories of the Richmond-San Rafael Ferry Company | last1 = Snodgrass | first1 = Marion Myers | last2 = Dunning | first2 = Judith K | year = 1992 | url = http://content.cdlib.org/view?docId=hb2m3nb1b0 | location = Berkeley, Calif. | publisher = [[Bancroft Library]]}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early proposals===\nProposals for a bridge were advanced in the 1920s, preceding the completion of the Golden Gate Bridge. In 1927, Roy O. Long of The Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge, Incorporated, applied for a franchise to construct and operate a private toll bridge. The proposed 1927 Long bridge would have been a steel suspension bridge, carrying a {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} roadway for a distance of {{convert|14600|ft}} at an estimated construction cost of {{US$|12000000|1927|round=-5}}. The bridge would afford a maximum vertical clearance of {{convert|135|ft}} with a {{convert|1200|ft|adj=on}} main span.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19270409.2.3&srpos=33 |title=Bridge Hearing Put Over Till Monday, 11th |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 9, 1927 |volume=XXXXIII |number=15 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> Charles Derleth, Jr. was selected as the consulting engineer, after having served in that role for the recently completed [[Carquinez Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19270226.2.13&srpos=16 |title=Propose to Construct Steel Bridge Over San Pablo Bay |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 26, 1927 |volume=XXXXIII |number=9 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> The Long bridge would have spanned [[San Pablo Bay]] between Point Orient (in [[Contra Costa County, California|Contra Costa County]]) to just below McNear's Point (in [[Marin County, California|Marin County]]), and Long was granted the franchise in February 1928 by the Contra Costa County Board of Supervisors.<ref name=SN-19280211>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280211.2.38&srpos=5 |title=Local News |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 11, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=6 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nA competing proposed bridge also came out in 1927, from Charles Van Damme of the Richmond-San Rafael Ferry Company. The 1927 Van Damme bridge would have carried a {{convert|27|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} roadway for a distance of {{convert|19000|ft}} at an identical estimated construction cost of {{US$|12000000|1927|round=-5}}.<ref name=SN-19271231>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19271231.2.10&srpos=6 |title=Ferry Head to Apply for Span Permit |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 31, 1927 |volume=XXXXIII |number=53 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> It would have spanned San Pablo Bay from [[Castro Point]] (Contra Costa County) to [[San Quentin, California|Point San Quentin]] (Marin County), approximately the same routing as the eventually completed 1956 bridge.<ref name=SN-19280211 /> Although the 1927 Long bridge had been granted a franchise in February 1928, Van Damme subsequently petitioned to reopen the case, since the ferry company owned the land at the proposed eastern terminus and therefore should have been favored in the franchise selection process.<ref name=SN-19280331>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280331.2.28&srpos=4 |title=One Bridge Gets Franchise, Other Given Rehearing |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 31, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=13 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> Also, since the ferry company's franchise rights were not set to expire until the 1950s, Long's 1927 bridge cost would have increased to reimburse losses to ferry revenues.<ref name=SN-19271231 /> Soon after winning the franchise rights, Long approached Van Damme with an offer to buy the Richmond-San Rafael Ferry Company for {{US$|1250000|1928|round=-5}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280225.2.41&srpos=3 |title=Richmond Ferry is Sold to Bridge Co. |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 25, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=8 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nVan Damme and Long later agreed in September 1928 to merge their interests for a combined bridge proposal between [[Point San Pablo Yacht Harbor|Point San Pablo]] (Contra Costa County) and McNear's Point (Marin County).<ref name=SN-19280928>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280928.2.30&srpos=1 |title=Rivals Agree On Contra Costa to Marin Crossing |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 28, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=38 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> The combined project, now headed by Oscar Klatt for the American Toll Bridge Company, received approval for the routing from then-[[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[James William Good|Good]] in May 1929, although vertical and horizontal clearances for the proposed bridge were not fully established at the time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MT19290513.2.7&srpos=3 |title=Bay Span Plan Gets Approval |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=May 13, 1929 |newspaper=Madera Tribune |agency=United Press Dispatch |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> In November 1929, vertical clearance had been increased to {{convert|160|ft}} to satisfy Navy requirements.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19291122.2.58&srpos=2 |title=Favorable Bridge Plans are Filed|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=November 22, 1929 |volume=XXXXXV |number=47 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> The construction permit was issued in February 1930.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MT19300211.2.33&srpos=1 |title=Bay Bridge Permit Given |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 11, 1929 |newspaper=Madera Tribune |agency=United Press Dispatch |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nKlatt's 1929 bridge was dormant for nearly a decade following the issuance of a construction permit in 1930. An extension was filed in 1938 to allow construction to start as late as February 1942,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19381020.2.91&srpos=29 |title=Bridge Franchise Extension Asked |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=October 20, 1938 |volume=LIII |number=42 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> and fresh plans for a bridge district to facilitate financing were announced in 1939.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19390420.2.18&srpos=30 |title=Richmond-S.R. Bridge Plan Under Way |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 20, 1939 |volume=LIV |number=16 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> In 1947, interest was revived in bridging Marin and Contra Costa Counties.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19470918.2.71&srpos=72 |title=Revive Richmond-S.R. Bridge Plan |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 18, 1947 |volume=62 |number=43 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Tomasini's San Francisco\u2013Alameda\u2013Marin crossings===\nA third bridge was proposed in late 1927 by the enigmatic T.A. Tomasini.<ref>Thomas A. Tomasini, resident in San Francisco, is also noted as the inventor of the 1916 {{patent|US|1200049|\"Automobile Spring\"}} as well as being a participant in the [[1915 American Grand Prize|1915 automobile Vanderbilt Cup Race]], where he did not start due to crashing in practice.</ref> Tomasini's 1927 bridge called for two lanes of automobile traffic straddling a central rail line from San Pedro Hill (Marin) to San Pablo station (Contra Costa), a distance of over {{convert|5|mi}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19271217.2.13&srpos=18 |title=Span Interests Eastern Capital |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 17, 1927 |volume=XXXXIII |number=51 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016}}</ref> In 1928, Tomasini presented a revised proposal for a bridge farther south than the other two bridges\u2014spanning the water from [[Albany, California|Albany]] (in [[Alameda County, California|Alameda County]]) to [[Tiburon, California|Tiburon]]. The 1928 Tomasini Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge was the longest of the three proposed bridges by a significant margin.<ref name=SN-19280331 /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280114.2.48&srpos=11 |title=Battle Expected Against Bay Span |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=January 14, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=2 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> The proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge would have been similar in concept to the 1967 [[San Mateo\u2013Hayward Bridge]], with a high-level western section approximately {{convert|7700|ft}} long transitioning to a low-level eastern causeway. The western section featured two {{convert|1000|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} spans to cross the navigation channels, with the western navigation span having a minimum vertical clearance of {{convert|150|ft}} and the eastern navigation span having a minimum vertical clearance of {{convert|135|ft}}.<ref name=SN-19280921 /> The {{convert|1000|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} navigation channels for the proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge were opposed by shipping interests, who wanted the channels to be {{convert|1500|ft}} wide instead. The cost of the longer spans required would have made the proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge impractical, and Tomasini argued that \"any mariner who could not negotiate a bridge such as proposed should lose his license.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19281019.2.20&srpos=30 |title=Shipping Men Try to Block Tomasini Bay Bridge Plan |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=October 19, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=41 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:San Francisco Bay bridges Tomasini.svg|thumb|left|250px|Tomasini's proposed 1928 San Francisco Bay crossings, shown in orange. Red bridges are those that were built, including the 1956 Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge (1). 1937 [[Golden Gate Bridge]] (2), and 1936 [[San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge|San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge]] (3) . {{ordered list |list_style_type=upper-alpha\n  |1=<!--A-->Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge\n  |2=<!--B-->Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge\n  |3=<!--C-->San Francisco\u2013Marin\u2013Alameda tunnel & bridge\n}}]]\nTomasini would later add a bridge spanning [[Richardson Bay]] in March 1928 from [[Sausalito, California|Sausalito]] to [[Belvedere, California|Belvedere]] to his proposal.<ref name=SN-19280928 /> The additional Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge would have been {{convert|7300|ft}} long and {{convert|22|ft}} wide with a lift span to allow the passage of large vessels, at an estimated cost of {{US$|750000|1928|round=-5}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280317.2.2&srpos=45 |title=Belvedere Bridge Could be Erected by Summer of '29 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 17, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=11 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=SN-19280421>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280421.2.6&srpos=41 |title=Belvedere Span Hearing is Set |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 21, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=16 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> Meanwhile, in April 1928 Tomasini recruited the prominent [[Ralph Modjeski]] to serve as the consulting head engineer for the proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon span,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280414.2.14&srpos=43 |title=Tomasini Signs Up Modjeski for Tiburon Bridge |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 14, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=15 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> and Modjeski promptly complimented the plans that had been drawn up by Tomasini's chief engineer, Erle L. Cope.<ref name=SN-19280421 /> The design for a [[Moveable bridge|lift span]] in the proposed Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge was changed to a [[Bascule bridge|bascule]] after public comments were received from a local shipbuilder.<ref name=SN-19280914>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280914.2.2&srpos=11 |title=S.F. Delays Plan of Tomasini for North Bay Bridge |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 14, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=36 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> Tomasini received a permit for the Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge from the War Department in December 1928.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19281228.2.3&srpos=9 |title=Tomasini Gets Sausalito-Belvedere Bridge Permit |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 28, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=51 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> Tomasini had planned to commence construction of the Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge in July 1930,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19300627.2.3&srpos=2 |title=Tomasini to Start Construction Work on Richardson Bay |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=June 27, 1930 |volume=XXXXVI |number=26 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> but he was met with opposition from the Tiburon-Belvedere Chamber of Commerce, who felt the creation of a bridge would eliminate the promised San Francisco-Tiburon ferry service.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19300711.2.41&srpos=3 |title=Tiburon-Belvedere Now Doesn't Want Tomasini Crossing |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=July 11, 1930 |volume=XXXXVI |number=28 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> In 1931, the Richardson Bay Redwood Bridge was opened, which was the largest structure in the world constructed of redwood.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19311113.2.69 |title=Plan is Perfected for South Marin Highway Affair |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=November 13, 1931 |volume=XXXXVII |number=46 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 29, 2016 }}</ref> The Redwood Bridge carried the Redwood Highway (present-day US 101) and spanned the upper reach of Richardson Bay,<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.marinmagazine.com/May-2009/History-of-a-Highway/ |title=History of a Highway: Marin's 101 was first established in 1909 |author=Wood, Jim |date=May 2009 |journal=Marin Magazine |accessdate=February 29, 2016 }}</ref> eliminating some of the need for the proposed Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge. The Redwood Bridge would be replaced by a concrete structure in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marinij.com/events/20110323/moving-marin-the-enormous-role-of-bridges-ferries-trains-highways |title=Moving Marin: The enormous role of bridges, ferries, trains, highways |author=Prado, Mark |date=March 23, 2011 |newspaper=Marin Independent Journal |accessdate=February 29, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nTomasini continued to add to the project scope in July 1928 by proposing a [[Fixed link|bridge and tunnel]] to join San Francisco to the proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge. The tunnel would run roughly northeast from Bay Street and Grant Avenue, not far from present-day [[Pier 39]], at a depth of {{convert|50|ft}} below low tide water level for {{convert|11200|ft}}. At that point, the tunnel would surface northwest of [[Yerba Buena Island|Goat Island]], and then transition to a bridge nearly {{convert|4|mi}} long with a minimum vertical clearance of {{convert|50|ft}} and two lift spans connecting to the proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge. The cost of the entire project was {{US$|55670000|1928|round=-5}}, split as {{US$|20000000|1928|round=-5}} for the Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge, {{US$|670000|1928|round=-5}} for the Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge, and {{US$|35000000|1928|round=-5}} for the San Francisco\u2013Marin\u2013Alameda tunnel and bridge.<ref name=SN-19280713>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280713.2.10&srpos=15 |title=Plans Marin-S.F. Connection with Bridge and Tube |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=July 13, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=27 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> Tomasini organized each of the three proposed structures as independent projects, preferably to be built simultaneously, but in the event that one was not approved, it would not delay the construction of the other two.<ref name=SN-19280713 /> San Francisco's board of supervisors rejected Tomasini's San Francisco\u2013Marin\u2013Alameda tunnel and bridge in September 1928, although the board's action was non-binding.<ref name=SN-19280921>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280921.2.2&srpos=10 |title=S.F. Turns Down Span Connection to Marin County |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 21, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=37 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBy February 1932, Tomasini's proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge had changed to a combination bridge\u2014tunnel. The bridge portion was a low trestle approximately {{convert|19800|ft}} long, extending westward from [[Fleming Point|Point Fleming]] in Albany in Alameda County. The proposed tunnel would have been {{convert|17200|ft}} long and ventilated by four towers, emerging at Bluff Point near Tiburon in Marin County.<ref name=MDT-19320716>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MT19320716.2.2&srpos=7 |title=Approve Bay Bridge Plan |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=July 16, 1932 |volume=LX |number=63 |newspaper=Madera Daily Tribune and Madera Mercury |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> Total estimated cost for the two structures was now {{US$|35000000|1932|round=-5}} and despite opposition from the US Navy, who cited potential navigation hazards,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19320401.2.37&srpos=19 |title=Tomasini's Bridge Plan Protested |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 1, 1932 |volume=XXXXVIII |number=14 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> the bridge\u2014tunnel was approved by the War Department in July 1932.<ref name=MDT-19320716 /> Although he had the permit to begin work, Tomasini filed numerous annual extensions to retain the rights through 1941,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19401205.2.83&srpos=5 |title=Tomasini Bridge Permit Extension Again Asked<!--Wow, what a salty headline!--> |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 5, 1940 |volume=LV |number=48 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> apparently due to a lack of funding to start work. Tomasini was still scrambling for funding in August 1941, seeking the issue of bonds worth {{US$|20000000|1941|round=-5}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19410821.2.22&srpos=4 |title=20 Million Bond Issue Sought for Span-Tube |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=August 21, 1941 |volume=LVI |number=34 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> Tomasini lost the rights to the crossing in October 1941,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19411002.2.8&srpos=3 |title=Rights to Span Tube Lost by Tomasini |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=October 2, 1941 |volume=LVI |number=40 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> which was not the first time he was opposed by [[Earl Warren]], who had questioned the validity of Tomasini's franchise as early as 1933.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19330407.2.44&srpos=7 |title=Tomasini Says He Is Going to Build Span |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 7, 1933 |volume=XLVIII |number=14 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> Still, Tomasini was doggedly trying to advance his plans as late as 1948.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19481216.2.58&srpos=1 |title=Richardson Bay Bridge Plan Again Revived |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 16, 1948 |volume=63 |number=51 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Construction: 1953\u20131956===\nIn 1949, the County of Marin and the City of Richmond commissioned a preliminary engineering report from Earl and Wright of San Francisco, which concluded that a bridge would be feasible.<ref name=CHPW1953>{{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1953_novdec.pdf |title=New Bay Crossing: Story of the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge |pages=1\u20136; 64 |volume=32 |number=11\u201312 |author=Raab, Norman A. |date=November\u2013December 1953 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}</ref> A follow-up 1950 study, conducted by the Division of San Francisco Bay Toll Crossings, was commissioned by Marin County and the City of Richmond using {{US$|200000|1950|round=-4}} in state funding. The 1950 report concluded the bridge could be built in accordance with the California Toll Bridge Authority Act.<ref name=CHPW1953 /> The preliminary design was approved on 1951-08-08 and California approved the preliminary report on 1951-11-27. The California Toll Bridge Authority authorized the issue of {{US$|72000000|1952|round=-5}} in bonds on 1952-11-07 and subsequently sold {{US$|62000000|1953|round=-5}} on 1953-02-26 to construct a single-deck bridge. The remaining {{US$|10000000|1953|round=-5}} was reserved for construction contingencies and to complete the lower deck of the bridge.<ref name=CHPW1956-0708 /> The $62 million raised from bond sales was divided into three parts: {{US$|50000000|1953|round=-5}} for construction, {{US$|10000000|1953|round=-5}} to address interest obligations on the bonds during the construction period, and {{US$|2000000|1953|round=-5}} in construction contingency.<ref name=CHPW1956-0708 /> In 1954, [[Goodwin Knight|Governor Knight]] declared the second deck should not be delayed in the public interest, and {{US$|6000000|1955|round=-5}} was loaned from the State School Land Fund in 1955 to complete the second deck. The bridge was finished $4 million under budget.<ref name=BridgeTheBay />\n\nDuring the study period, an earth and rock-fill bridge with lift structures was considered, but the high-level bridge was chosen as the cost of a low bridge with navigation locks and lifting structures was prohibitive.<ref name=CHPW1953 />\n\nThe majority of construction costs were tied up in two contracts that opened for bidding on 1952-12-19. The first contract, for the substructure, was awarded to the low bidder,  the Ben C. Gerwick, Inc. \u2014 Peter Kiewit Sons' Co. Joint Venture for {{US$|14234550|1953|round=-5}}. The second contract, for the superstructure, was awarded to the low bid of {{US$|21099319|1953|round=-5}} by a joint venture between Peter Kiewit Sons' Co. \u2014 A. Soda & Son \u2014 Judson Pacific Murphy Corp.<ref name=CHPW1953 /> The substructure construction moved rapidly, with an estimated 45% of piers completed approximately a year after the contract was awarded.<ref name=CHPW-19540304 />\n\nAt the time the bridge was completed, it was hailed as the world's second-longest bridge, behind the San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zCEhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=72QEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2923%2C2231090 |title=Frisco Adds Another Bridge To Skyline |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=August 16, 1956 |newspaper=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |accessdate=March 1, 2016}}</ref> and the longest continuous steel bridge.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nORQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mSUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7048%2C1698009 |title=Straits Bridge Claim Challenged on Coast |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=June 24, 1958 |newspaper=The Milwaukee Journal |accessdate=March 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Historical notes===\nOriginally a part of [[California State Route 17|State Route 17]], the bridge is now part of [[Interstate 580 (California)|Interstate 580]].\n\nUpon its opening, the Richmond\u2013San Rafael bridge was the last bridge across San Francisco Bay to replace a previous ferry service, leaving the [[Benicia\u2013Martinez Bridge|Benicia\u2013Martinez Ferry]] across Carquinez Strait as the only remaining auto ferry in the Bay Area (it would be replaced by a bridge in 1962).\n\n==Description==\n[[File:San_Francisco_Bay_Bridges_map_en.svg|thumb|Bridges in the San Francisco Bay]]\n[[File:Caltrans District4 7836D059.jpg|thumb|Vertical undulation of the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge between the two cantilever spans]]\nThe bridge\u2014including approaches\u2014measures 5.5 miles (29,040 feet / 8,851.39 m / 8.9&nbsp;km) long. At the time it was built, it was one of the world's longest bridges. The bridge spans two ship channels and has two separate main [[cantilever bridge|cantilever]] spans. Both main cantilever spans are raised to allow ship traffic to pass, and in between, there is a \"dip\" in the elevation of the center section,<ref name=CSeim>{{cite interview |url=http://digitalassets.lib.berkeley.edu/roho/ucb/text/seim_chuck.pdf |title=Charles Seim: The Bay Bridge Oral History Project |interviewer=Sam Redman |subject=Seim, Chuck |page=21 |date=2013 |publisher=The Bancroft Library, University of California |location=Berkeley |accessdate=February 6, 2015 |quote=When it comes to the Richmond-San Rafael designed by Norman C. Raab, first of all, it zigzags because of the two alignments of the navigation channels. It goes up, and then it sags down, and then it goes up. The cardinal rule of aesthetics in a bridge is it has to soar. You can't sag it in the middle. The other is it connects from here to there as a straight line or as a curve line. You don't make an \"S\" out of it. Those violate both of those very strong principles. This engineer [Raab] was soundly criticized for creating this ugly bridge. Of course, his defense was, \"I saved a million dollars by putting the sag in it.\" Which is probably true.}}</ref> giving the bridge a vertical undulation or \"[[roller coaster]]\" appearance and also the nickname \"roller coaster span\". To save money, the cantilever main spans share identical symmetric designs, so the \"uphill\" grade on the approach required for the elevated span is duplicated on the other \"downhill\" side, resulting in a depressed center truss section.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marinij.com/article/ZZ/20060901/NEWS/609019964 |title=With little fanfare... |date=September 1, 2006 |author=Prado, Mark |newspaper=Marin Independent Journal |accessdate=February 26, 2016}}</ref> In addition, because the navigation channels are not parallel to each other, the bridge also does not follow a straight line.<ref>''Interview with Chuck Seim'' (2013), p. 8 & 30. \"Now, the twin spans, they were spanned by what we call a steel cantilever span. But the interesting thing is that these shipping channels were not parallel to one another. They angled.\"</ref> This appearance has also been referred to as a \"bent coat hanger\".<ref name=BridgeTheBay>{{cite web |url=http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/news_events/bridge/rsr.html |title=Bridging the Bay: Bridging the Campus - Richmond-San Rafael |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 22, 1999 |website=UC Berkeley Library |accessdate=February 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter it was completed, many were disappointed by the aesthetics of the low budget bridge,<ref>''Interview with Chuck Seim'' (2013), p. 20. \"Of course, everybody criticized the truss bridge on the Richmond-San Rafael, that Raab designed and they said, 'We don't want an ugly truss here.' [...] Well, if you had to award the ugliest bridge in the world, I think the Richmond-San Rafael would certainly be in the running. If not the first one, then top three. It is an ugly bridge. But that's a story that maybe we shouldn't get into. It was driven by economics, and it was driven by the obstinance of this one engineer that I referred to. He wouldn't change. He then proposed a truss for the Hayward area, and everybody said, 'No, we don't want that. It's an ugly bridge.' He said, 'Well, it's the most economical.'\"</ref> including [[Frank Lloyd Wright]], who reportedly called for its destruction<ref name=TYLin>{{cite interview |url=http://content.cdlib.org/view?docId=kt4w1003s9&chunk.id=d0e11453 |title=\"The Father of Prestressed Concrete\": Teaching Engineers, Bridging Rivers and Borders, 1931 to 1999 |subject=Lin, TY |subject-link=Tung-Yen Lin |interviewer=Eleanor Swent |chapter=VIII Developing Prestressed Concrete Technology: The Richmond-San Rafael Bridge: Misjudgment to Save Money |language=English |date=1999 |publisher=The Regents of the University of California |place=Berkeley |accessdate=February 24, 2016 |quote=Lin: So, one architect asked [Wright], \"What do you think of the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge?\" \"I think it should be sabotaged!\" He meant that it should be bombed, it's so ugly looking.}}</ref> and called it \"the most awful thing I've ever seen\" in 1953, during its construction.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SCS19530501.1.6 |title=Architect Chides Design Of New North Bay Bridge |agency=AP |date=May 1, 1953 |newspaper=Santa Cruz Sentinel |accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref> The neighboring [[Golden Gate Bridge]] and the western span of [[San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge|Bay Bridge]] were considered engineering and historical marvels, and the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge was not considered in the same class. However, the senior engineers for the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge were the same engineers that worked on the Bay Bridge<ref>''Interview with Chuck Seim'' (2013), pp. 8\u201310. \"Everybody working on that bridge - I think it's safe to say all the higher-echelon engineers - were the same engineers that worked on the San Francisco Bay Bridge. I had a chance to work with engineers who actually worked on the San Francisco Bay Bridge, and I used to read about that when I was a kid.\"</ref> and the resulting design echoed the lessons learned from the eastern span of the Bay Bridge.<ref>''Interview with Chuck Seim'' (2013), p. 30. \"In 1956, the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge was opened. An interesting thing about that is that most of the senior engineers that worked on the Bay Bridge stayed over in San Francisco and worked on the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge, because they both used the same technology, with some minor variations.\"</ref>\n\nFrom west (Point San Quentin) to east (Castro Point), the bridge consists of:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/esc/tollbridge/Rich-SR/Rich-layout.pdf |title=Pier and Bent Layout: Richmond-San Rafael Bridge (Sheet No. RS-224) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Caltrans |accessdate=February 22, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=CHPW-19540304>{{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1954_marapr.pdf |title=Pier Construction: Rapid Progress on Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Project |pages=20\u201325; 32\u201333; 64 |author=Raab, Norman A. |date=March\u2013April 1954 |volume=33 |number=3\u20134 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}</ref>\n* A {{convert|2845|ft|adj=on}} [[trestle|trestle structure]] supported by fifty-seven [[bent (structural)|bents]]. The upper deck is {{convert|2845|ft}}, and the lower deck is slightly longer at {{convert|3635|ft}}.\n* {{convert|1900|ft}} of [[girder bridge|girder spans]], consisting of nineteen {{convert|100|ft|adj=on}} girder spans\n* {{convert|4125|ft}} of [[truss bridge|truss spans]], divided into fourteen trusses each {{convert|292|ft}} long, on average.\n* The western {{convert|2145|ft|adj=on}} [[cantilever bridge|cantilever structure]], with arms measuring {{convert|538|ft}} each flanking a central span of {{convert|1070|ft}}. The western cantilever span is the main {{convert|1070|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} navigation channel and features a vertical clearance of {{convert|185|ft}}.\n* {{convert|2955|ft}} of truss spans, consisting of ten spans each {{convert|292|ft}} long, on average.\n* The eastern {{convert|2145|ft|adj=on}} cantilever structure, with arms measuring {{convert|538|ft}} each flanking a central span of {{convert|1070|ft}}. The eastern cantilever span is the secondary {{convert|1070|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} navigation channel and features a reduced vertical clearance of {{convert|135|ft}}.\n* {{convert|3505|ft}} of truss spans, consisting of twelve spans each {{convert|292|ft}} long, on average.\n* {{convert|1715|ft}} of {{convert|100|ft|adj=on}} girder spans\nExcluding approaches, the bridge structures comprise a total length of {{convert|21335|ft}} on the upper deck and {{convert|22125|ft}} on the lower deck. Despite the varying height of the bridge, roadway grades are limited to 3% or less.<ref name=CHPW1953 /><ref name=CHPW-19540304 /> As completed, the bridge has two decks each capable of carrying three lanes of traffic. {{As of|2018}}, westbound traffic rides on the upper deck and is marked with two lanes of vehicle traffic and a shoulder, while eastbound traffic rides on the lower deck and features two lanes of vehicle traffic as well as a third lane that is activated during evening commute hours and serves as a shoulder when not in use. The extra lane features lights indicating that the lane is open or closed.<ref name=3rdLane /> The third lane has been used for various purposes other than traffic, such as carrying a [[water pipeline]] during a drought.\n\n[[Image:Richmond San Rafael Bridge 07802.JPG|thumb|left|View southwest from above Richmond]]\nThe bridge stands on 79 reinforced concrete piers supported on steel H-piles. Nine piers stand on land, eight are in cofferdams near the Contra Costa terminus, and the remaining 62 are bell-type piers with a flared base.<ref name=CHPW-19540304 /> The original deck was a {{convert|5.5|in|adj=on}} thick reinforced concrete slab, with a mortar wearing surface {{convert|0.5|in}} thick.<ref name=CHPW-19540708>{{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1954_julaug.pdf |title=Bridge Innovations: New Operation Facilities On Richmond-San Rafael Span |pages=14\u201315; 32\u201333 |author=Raab, Norman C. |volume=33 |number=7\u20138 |date=July\u2013August 1954 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}</ref> To facilitate maintenance, the bridge was designed with two {{convert|2.5|in}} lines (carrying compressed air and potable water) extending from end to end. Each deck was also equipped with three overhead maintenance tracks.<ref name=CHPW-19540708 />\n\n===Public transit service===\n[[Golden Gate Transit]] bus routes 40 and 580 provide public transportation across the bridge. Route 40 runs between the [[San Rafael Transit Center]] and the [[El Cerrito del Norte (BART station)|El Cerrito del Norte BART station]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goldengatetransit.org/schedules/current/route_40.php |title=Route 40 Basic Bus Route Effective December 13, 2015 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 13, 2015 |website=Golden Gate Transit |accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref> Golden Gate Transit Route 42, which provided service to [[Richmond Station (California)|Richmond BART/Amtrak]] station, was folded into Route 40 in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goldengate.org/news/transit/route-42-elimination-travel-alternatives.php |title=GGT Routes 40 & 42 Merging - Service to Richmond BART Station Discontinued |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=November 10, 2015 |website=Golden Gate Transit |accessdate=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Tolls==\n[[File:Caltrans District4 7916D003.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Toll plaza at Richmond in 2006 before newest reconstruction]]\nTolls are only collected from westbound traffic headed to San Rafael at the toll plaza on the east side of the bridge. Since January 2019, the toll rate for (two axle) passenger cars and motorcycles is $6.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bayareafastrak.org/en/howitworks/whereToUse.shtml#richmond|title=FasTrak|website=www.bayareafastrak.org|access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> During peak traffic hours, [[carpool|high-occupancy vehicles]] (defined as two-axle vehicles without trailers, carrying three or more people; two-axle vehicles designed with two passenger seats without trailers, carrying two people; or motorcycles) pay a discounted toll of $3.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = Frequently Asked Toll Questions | publisher = Bay Area Toll Authority | date = June 1, 2010 | url = http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/faq.htm#2 | accessdate = June 29, 2010| archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5tv1MQCqO | archivedate = November 1, 2010| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Toll Increase Information | publisher = Bay Area Toll Authority | date = June 1, 2010 | url =http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/ | accessdate = June 29, 2010| archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOZ | archivedate = November 1, 2010| url-status=live}}</ref> Since January 1, 2019, for vehicles with more than two axles, the toll rate is $16 for 3 axles and $5 per each additional axle over 3, up to a maximum toll of $36 for vehicles with seven or more axles.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Toll Increase Information: Multi-Axle Vehicles |publisher=Bay Area Toll Authority |date=July 1, 2012 |url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/multi-axle.htm |accessdate=December 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230234900/http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/multi-axle.htm |archivedate=December 30, 2013 }}</ref> Drivers may either pay by cash or use the [[FasTrak]] [[electronic toll collection]] device.\n\n=== Historical toll rates ===\nThe following initial toll rates were adopted on July 10, 1956 prior to the opening of the bridge:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''Inaugural toll schedule'''<ref name=CHPW1956-0708>{{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1956_julaug.pdf |title=Record Span New Crossing: Richmond-San Rafael Bridge About Ready for Traffic |pages=1\u20134; 22 |volume=35 |number=7\u20138 |author=Raab, Norman C. |date=July\u2013August 1956 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Vehicle type\n! scope=\"col\" | Axles/trailers\n! scope=\"col\" | Toll\n\n|-\n! rowspan=4 | Class 1{{efn |name= |Class 1 vehicles are defined as: automobiles, motorcycles, tri-cars, light delivery automobiles, ambulances, hearses, housecars, noncommercial trucks, station wagons, and taxis.}}\n| vehicle alone\n| {{US$|0.75|1956|round=2}}{{efn |Motorcycle toll was initially proposed as {{US$|0.25|1956|round=2}}, but Norman Raab successfully argued the tight pants worn by motorcyclists meant the driver would have to dismount to retrieve the coins for the toll.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YftXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=x_YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=753%2C986448 |title=Tight Pants Cause High Toll Request |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=June 20, 1956 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |accessdate=February 18, 2016 |agency=AP}}</ref>}}\n\n|-\n| Commutation book{{efn |Commutation books were sold with 50 one-way tickets good for a single passage at any time during the two consecutive calendar months, or fractional part thereof, for which sold.}}{{efn |Any Class 1 vehicle, with the exception of light delivery automobiles and noncommercial trucks, was eligible for the commutation book.}}\n| {{US$|18.75|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| with 1-axle trailer\n| {{US$|1.25|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| with 2-axle trailer\n| {{US$|1.50|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n! rowspan=6 |Truck{{efn |A truck shall include a truck-tractor, or any combination of truck, truck-tractor and trailer or semitrailer}}\n| 2-axle\n| {{US$|1.25|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 3-axle\n| {{US$|1.75|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 4-axle\n| {{US$|2.50|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 5-axle\n| {{US$|3.00|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 6-axle\n| {{US$|3.50|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 7-axle\n| {{US$|4.00|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n! rowspan=2 |Bus\n| 2-axle\n| {{US$|1.50|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 3-axle\n| {{US$|1.75|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| colspan=2 |Other vehicles not specified above\n| {{US$|5.00|1956|round=2}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" align=center|Inaugural toll table notes\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |{{notelist|30em}}\n|}\n\nThe basic toll (for automobiles) on the seven state bridges, including the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge, was raised to $1 by Regional Measure 1, approved by Bay Area voters in 1988.<ref>[http://bata.mtc.ca.gov/projects/rm1.htm Regional Measure 1 Toll Bridge Program]. ''bata.mtc.ca.gov''; [[Bay Area Toll Authority]]. {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOE?url=http://bata.mtc.ca.gov/projects/rm1.htm |date=November 1, 2010 }}</ref> A $1 seismic retrofit surcharge was added in 1998 by the state legislature, originally for eight years, but since then extended to December 2037 (AB1171, October 2001).<ref name='AB1171'>{{cite news|first=John |last=Dutra |title=AB 1171 Assembly Bill \u2013 Chaptered |date=October 14, 2001 |publisher=[[California State Assembly]] |url=http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/01-02/bill/asm/ab_1151-1200/ab_1171_bill_20011014_chaptered.html |accessdate=August 7, 2008 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOL?url=http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/01-02/bill/asm/ab_1151-1200/ab_1171_bill_20011014_chaptered.html |archivedate=November 1, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 2, 2004, voters approved Regional Measure 2, raising the toll by another dollar to a total of $3. An additional dollar was added to the toll starting January 1, 2007, to cover cost overruns concerning the replacement of the eastern span.\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Transportation Commission (San Francisco Bay Area)|Metropolitan Transportation Commission]], a regional transportation agency, in its capacity as the [[Bay Area Toll Authority]], administers RM1 and RM2 funds, allocating a significant portion to public transit capital improvements and operating subsidies in the transportation corridors the bridges serve. Caltrans administers the \"second dollar\" seismic surcharge, and receives some of the MTC-administered funds to perform other maintenance work on the bridges. The Bay Area Toll Authority is made up of appointed officials put in place by various city and county governments, and is not subject to direct voter oversight.<ref>{{cite web|title=About MTC |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Commission |date=October 15, 2009 |url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/about_mtc/about.htm |accessdate=October 15, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOg?url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/about_mtc/about.htm |archivedate=November 1, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDue to further funding shortages for seismic retrofit projects, the Bay Area Toll Authority again raised tolls on all seven of the state-owned bridges in July 2010. The toll rate for autos on the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge was thus increased to $5.<ref>{{cite web |title=Frequently Asked Toll Questions |publisher=Bay Area Toll Authority |date=June 1, 2010 |url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/faq.htm#2 |accessdate=June 29, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv1MQCqO?url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/faq.htm#2 |archivedate=November 1, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Bay Area voters approved Regional Measure 3 to further raise the tolls on all seven of the state-owned bridges to fund $4.5 billion worth of transportation improvements in the area.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/3-hike-to-Bay-Area-tolls-appears-to-have-support-12972027.php | title=Regional Measure 3: Work on transportation improvements could start next year | first=Michael | last=Cabanatuan | publisher=SFGate.com | date=June 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/bay-area-bridge-tolls-to-increase-one-dollar-in-january-except-golden-gate | title=Bay Area bridge tolls to increase one dollar in January, except Golden Gate | first=Christien | last=Kafton | publisher=KTVU | date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> Under the passed measure, the toll rate for autos on the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge will be increased to $6 on January 1, 2019; to $7 on January 1, 2022; and then to $8 on January 1, 2025.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://mtc.ca.gov/whats-happening/news/tolls-seven-bay-area-bridges-set-rise-next-month | title=Tolls on Seven Bay Area Bridges Set to Rise Next Month | publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Commission | date=December 11, 2018 | accessdate=December 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, the MTC approved a $4 million plan to eliminate toll takers and convert all seven of the state-owned bridges to [[all-electronic tolling]], citing that 80 percent of drivers are now using Fastrak and the change would improve traffic flow.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/california/article234765937.html | title=Do you drive to the Bay Area? A big change is coming to toll booths at the bridges | first=Darrell | last=Smith | newspaper=The Sacramento Bee | date=September 7, 2019 | accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 20, 2020, at midnight, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], all-electronic tolling was temporarily placed in effect for all seven state-owned toll bridges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mtc.ca.gov/whats-happening/news/cash-toll-collection-suspended-bay-area-bridges|title=Cash Toll Collection Suspended at Bay Area Bridges|date=March 20, 2020|website=Metropolitan Transportation Commission|language=en|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Improvements==\n\n===Seismic retrofit===\n[[Image:R-SR Pier Seismic Reconstruction Compared.png|thumb|left|250px|Comparison of piers at eastern cantilever span in 2003 before reconstruction (top) and at western cantilever span in 2011 after reconstruction (bottom).]]\nIn the fall of 2001, the bridge commenced an extensive [[seismic retrofit]] program,<ref name=Welcome-Retrofit>{{cite web |url=http://66.120.196.62/rsrbridge/ |title=Welcome to the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Seismic Retrofit Project |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2004 |website=Caltrans |accessdate=March 1, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040404101112/http://66.120.196.62/rsrbridge/ |archivedate=April 4, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> similar to other bridges in the area.<ref name=\"sfgate\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/SAN-RAFAEL-Seismic-work-jolts-commute-2784147.php |title=SAN RAFAEL / Seismic work jolts commute / Retrofit on Richmond Bridge on schedule, but drivers fuming |author=Cabanatuan, Michael |date=May 3, 2004 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=September 29, 2013}}</ref> The retrofit was designed by a three-way joint venture between [[COWI A/S|Gerwick]]/[[Sverdrup & Parcel|Sverdrup]]/[[AECOM|DMJM]] under a {{US$|19000000|1995|round=-5}} design contract awarded in 1995.<ref name=Ger9509>{{cite web |url=http://www.gerwick.com/document.asp?DocumentID=3 |title=Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Seismic Retrofit |author=Vincent, John |date=September 1995 |website=Ben C. Gerwick, Inc. |accessdate=March 1, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040429081357/http://www.gerwick.com/document.asp?DocumentID=3 |archivedate=April 29, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The retrofit is intended to allow the two-tier bridge to withstand a 7.4 magnitude earthquake on the [[Hayward Fault Zone|Hayward Fault]] and an 8.3 magnitude quake on the [[San Andreas Fault]]. The foundation piers were strengthened by wrapping the lower section of structural steel in a concrete casing, installing new shear piles, and adding bracing to the structural steel towers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gerwick.com/project-detail.asp?ProjectID=259 |title=Project Description: Richmond-San Rafael Bridge |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1998 |website=Ben C. Gerwick, Inc. |accessdate=March 1, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040405132128/http://www.gerwick.com/project-detail.asp?ProjectID=259 |archivedate=April 5, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Isolation joints and bearings were also added to the main bridge structures (cantilever spans over the navigation channels) to strengthen the structure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://66.120.196.62/rsrbridge/construction/default.asp |title=Construction |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2004 |website=Caltrans |accessdate=March 1, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040405103107/http://66.120.196.62/rsrbridge/construction/default.asp |archivedate=April 4, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe fifty-year-old bridge was showing its age and also needed age-related maintenance, which was performed in conjunction with the seismic upgrade work. There were reports of cars being damaged while traveling on the lower deck by fist-sized concrete chunks falling from the joints of upper deck slabs.\n\nA major part of the retrofit involved the long concrete causeway on the Marin side, which as part of the retrofit program, was nearly completely replaced. Because of the active use of the bridge, Caltrans designed the project to allow the bridge to remain open to traffic. For economy, schedule efficiency and traffic impact mitigation, much of the repair work was fabricated off site and shipped to the bridge by barge.\n\nTo reduce impacts to traffic the major work was performed at night.  Caltrans kept two lanes of traffic moving in each direction during daylight hours, then reduced that flow to a single lane in each direction at night. Thus, one trestle was completely closed, and the other trestle had two-way traffic.\n\nThe concrete segments of the trestle were precast in [[Petaluma, California|Petaluma]] and barged to the site. At monthly intervals, tugs positioned barges with one or two {{convert|100|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}}, 500-ton pre-cast concrete roadway segments, which a 900-ton barge-mounted crane lifted into place. Earlier, either two or four of the corroded, {{convert|50|ft|m|adj=mid}} concrete segments of the old roadway were removed by crane. Then, a pile driver moved into position and drove new piles. After the new concrete road segment was in place, steel plates were used to temporarily fill the gaps, and the roadway was ready for morning traffic. At times, construction backed up traffic to Highway 101 into central San Rafael.\n\nThe completion of this retrofit, on September 22, 2005 was celebrated as a success despite the many challenges, including the deaths of two workers.\n\nThe retrofit was originally estimated by Caltrans engineers at {{US$|329000000|1999|round=-5}},<ref name=\"sfgate\" /> but Caltrans adjusted the estimate to {{US$|393272000|2000|round=-5}} in 2000 during the bidding process.<ref name=Bid-Summary>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/esc/tollbridge/Rich-SR/0438U4/docs/bidsummary.pdf |title=Bid Summary, Contract No. 04-0438U4 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=August 9, 2000 |website=State of California Department of Transportation |accessdate=March 1, 2016}}</ref> While most of the resulting bids were close to {{US$|545000000|2000|round=-5}}, the low bid came in at {{US$|484403479|2000|round=-5}} from the Tutor-Saliba/Koch/Tidewater Joint Venture.<ref name=Bid-Summary /> Caltrans revised their estimate to {{US$|665000000|2001|round=-5}} in May 2001 when more funds were appropriated for California's Toll Bridge Seismic Retrofit Program in Assembly Bill 1171.<ref>{{cite California statute |year=2001 |chapter=907 |page=7396}} {{cite web |url=ftp://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/01-02/bill/asm/ab_1151-1200/ab_1171_bill_20011014_chaptered.html |title=Assembly Bill 1171 |publisher=California Legislative Information |format=PDF |access-date=November 20, 2015}}</ref> The cost was again adjusted during an August 2004 review by Caltrans, this time to {{US$|914000000|2004|round=-5}}.<ref name=\"programreport\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/baybridge/seismic_retrofit_program_reports/TBSRPSecondQuarterReportEndingJune302005.pdf |title=Toll Bridge Seismic Retrofit Program Report, Second Quarter 2005 |author=California Department of Transportation| access-date=November 20, 2015}}</ref> The final cost of the retrofit, however, was $778 million, or $136 million below this August 2004 estimate.<ref name=\"programreport\" />\n\n===Third lanes===\n[[File:Richmond California.JPG|thumb|right|Aerial photo of bay]]\n[[Image:Wfm richmond bridge.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial photo of the bridge and the surrounding area]]\n\nIn both directions, the bridge is wide enough to accommodate three lanes of traffic. Currently the third lane on the lower deck is used as a right-hand shoulder or a \"breakdown lane\" and is marked along the bridge with the signs \"Emergency Parking Only\". The third lane on the upper deck is a separated bicycle and pedestrian path<ref name=\"bike\"/>.\n\nIn 1977, Marin County was suffering one of its worst droughts in history. A temporary on-surface pipeline, six miles (10&nbsp;km) long, was placed in the third lane. The pipe transferred 8,000,000 gallons of water a day from the [[East Bay Municipal Utility District]]'s mains in Richmond to Marin's 170,000 residents.  By 1978, the drought subsided and the pipeline was removed.  The disused third lane was then restriped as a shoulder.\n\nIn 1989, after the [[Loma Prieta earthquake]], the third lane was opened up as a normal lane to accommodate increased traffic after the [[San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge|Bay Bridge]] was shut down because of a failure of that span.{{cn|date=May 2018}} Many commuters from San Francisco drove across the Golden Gate Bridge into Marin and then across the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge to go to Oakland (and vice versa). After the Bay Bridge was reopened, the third lane was again closed.\n\nOn February 11, 2015, the [[Bay Area Toll Authority]] approved a plan to install a protected bike and pedestrian path on the wide shoulder of the upper deck of the bridge. The path was expected to be complete in 2017, <ref name=\"bike\">{{cite web|last1=Rivera|first1=Renee|title=Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Bike Path approved|url=https://bikeeastbay.org/news/richmond-san-rafael-bridge-bike-path-approved|website=bikeeastbay.org|publisher=East Bay Bicycle Coalition|accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> however it opened on November 16, 2019.<ref>https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/11/17/long-awaited-richmond-san-rafael-bridge-transbay-bike-lane-opens/</ref> As part of the same project, a third eastbound lane<ref>{{cite news|last1=Prado|first1=Mark|title=Big changes planned for Richmond-San Rafael Bridge|url=http://www.marinij.com/general-news/20150211/big-changes-planned-for-richmond-san-rafael-bridge|accessdate=August 5, 2015|work=Marin Independent Journal|date=February 11, 2015}}</ref> was added the previous year on the lower deck to be available for evening commutes.<ref name=3rdLane>{{cite news|last1=Prado|first1=Mark|title=Third lane on Richmond-San Rafael Bridge open for business|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2018/04/23/third-lane-on-richmond-san-rafael-bridge-open-for-business/|accessdate=May 3, 2018|agency=East Bay Times|date=April 23, 2018}}</ref> \n\n\n\n{{Wide image|Richmond-San Rafeal Bridge wide.jpg<!--Note: The filename of this photo is a misspelling of the bridge's name.-->|500px|View from the east end of the bridge (Richmond) looking southwest toward Southern Marin. San Quentin State Prison is at the far end of the bridge (San Rafael), just beyond the edge of the picture on the right. Top right above the bridge is Mount Tamalpais. The broken pilings in the water in the middle left of the picture are the remains of the pier where the Richmond\u2013San Rafael ferry docked before the bridge was built.|alt=Looking west, across the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge.}}\n\n==Closures==\nLike most San Francisco Bay bridges, this bridge is occasionally closed due to strong crosswinds. The bridge was closed on the morning of Friday, January 4, 2008 as a southerly wind gusting to nearly {{convert|70|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} buffeted the span, knocking over four trucks on the lower deck and one truck on the upper deck. The bridge was closed for six hours. It was re-opened by late afternoon as the strong winds subsided.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nThis was not the first closure due to high winds. A tractor-trailer overturned in high winds in 1963, forcing the closure of two lanes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19630131.1.1 |title=Storm, Wind Lash Bay City |author= |agency=AP |date=January 31, 1963 |newspaper=San Bernardino Sun |accessdate=April 16, 2018}}</ref> At least one previous event occurred in the late 1970s when high northerly winds forced the CHP to close the bridge. Wind gusts (reported in the Marin Independent Journal) reached 80&nbsp;mph.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nOn October 27, 2000 the toll plaza allowed people to cross free of charge due to a \"shelter in place\" order affecting toll booth operators.  The order was given by the [[Richmond Fire Department]] in response to a release of toxic gas from a recycling plant.<ref>[http://www.berkeleydailyplanet.com/issue/2000-10-27/article/1831?headline=Man-dies-in-recycling-plant-explosion--Daily-Planet-wire-reports- Man dies in recycling plant explosion], October 27, 2000, access date July 3, 2012</ref>\n\nOn February 7, 2019 the bridge was closed for several hours due to concrete falling from the upper deck to the lower.<ref>[https://www.sfgate.com/traffic/article/580-richmond-san-rafael-bridge-closed-concrete-13598563.php Falling concrete closes Richmond-San Rafael Bridge in both directions] February 7, 2019</ref>\n\n==In popular culture & film==\nThe novel ''Abuse of Power'' by [[Michael Savage]] has several important scenes set on the bridge. In one, the hero Jack Hatfield escapes his enemies by climbing the work ladders built into the piers.In the film ''Magnum Force'', the bridge is in the background when Dirty Harry and the rookie cop are on motorcycles on the ship's decks where they attempt to subdue each other.<ref>Scene 34. Not Enough Experience. ''Magnum Force''</ref> The bridge is also visible in the 1982 film [[48 Hours (film)|48 Hours]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Richmond-San Rafael Bridge}}\n* [http://www.marinij.com/marin/ci_4271565 With Little Fanfare... ''Marin IJ'' article on the 50th anniversary of the bridge]\n* [http://www.mtc.ca.gov/news/info/RSR_bridge.htm Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge Retrofit Completed]\n*[http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/esc/tollbridge/Rich-SR/Rich-SR.html Caltrans Seismic Retrofit overview]\n* [http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/traffops/hwybrdg/tollbridge/History/richmond.html California Dept. of Transportation: Richmond\u2013San Rafae