, 2016 }}\n* {{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1956_julaug.pdf |title=Record Span New Crossing: Richmond-San Rafael Bridge About Ready for Traffic |pages=1\u20134; 22 |author=Raab, Norman C. |date=July\u2013August 1956 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}\n* {{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1957_novdec.pdf |title=Freeway Approach to Bridge Opened in Marin County |page=29 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=November\u2013December 1957 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}\n* {{cite report |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000055913 |title=Richmond-San Rafael Bridge report |author=Raab, N.C. |date=1953 |publisher=Division of San Francisco Bay Toll Crossings |accessdate=July 12, 2016}}\n* {{cite report |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/002026761 |title=A preliminary report to Department of Public Works on a San Francisco-Tiburon crossing of San Francisco Bay |author=Raab, N.C. |date=1953 |publisher=Division of San Francisco Bay Toll Crossings |accessdate=July 12, 2016}}\n\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure        = Crossings\n|place            = [[San Francisco Bay]]\n|bridge           = Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge\n|bridge signs     = [[Image:I-580 (CA).svg|24px|Interstate 580]]\n|upstream text    = North\n|upstream         = [[Carquinez Bridge]]\n|upstream signs   = [[Image:I-80 (CA).svg|20px|Interstate 80]]\n|downstream text  = South\n|downstream       = [[Golden Gate Bridge]]\n|downstream signs = [[Image:US 101 (CA).svg|23px|U.S. Route 101]] [[Image:California 1.svg|20px|State Route 1]]\n}}\n\n{{Richmond, California}}\n{{San Francisco Bay watershed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richmond-San Rafael Bridge}}\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1956]]\n[[Category:Bridges in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Richmond, California]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Bay]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in California]]\n[[Category:Tolled sections of Interstate Highways]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Contra Costa County, California]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Marin County, California]]\n[[Category:Double-decker bridges]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in California]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in San Rafael, California]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the Interstate Highway System]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Bay Trail]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cantilever bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Pratt truss bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Trestle bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:1956 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Redirect|San Rafael Bridge|the bridge in Utah|San Rafael Bridge (Utah)}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n|bridge_name     = Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge\n|image           = Richmond-San Rafeal Bridge.jpg\n|caption         = The Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge from its western terminus\n|official_name   = Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge or John F. McCarthy Memorial Bridge\n|also_known_as   = Richmond Bridge <br /> San Rafael Bridge\n|named_for       = [[John F. McCarthy]]\n|carries         = 5 lanes (2 WB on upper level, 2-3 EB on lower) of {{jct|state=CA|I|580}}, bike/pedestrian\n|crosses         = [[San Francisco Bay]] and [[San Pablo Bay]]\n|locale          = [[San Rafael, California]] and [[Richmond, California]]\n|owner           = [[State of California]]\n|maint           = [[California Department of Transportation]] and the [[Bay Area Toll Authority]]\n|heritage        = \n|id              = 28 0100\n|id_type         = \n|preceded        = \n|design          = [[Double-deck bridge|Double-Decked]] Dual [[Cantilever bridge]] with [[Pratt Truss]] Approach\n|mainspan        = {{convert|1070|ft}} cantilever structure\n|number_spans    = 77 in total, consisting of:<br/>\n19 girder spans (west)<br/>\n14 truss spans (west)<br/>\n3 spans (western cantilever)<br/>\n9 truss spans (center)<br/>\n3 spans (eastern cantilever)<br/>\n12 truss spans (east)<br/>\n17 girder spans (east)\n|piers_in_water  = 70<ref name=CHPW-19540304 />\n|length          = {{convert|29040|ft|mi km|abbr=on}}\n|width           = \n|height          = \n|clearance_above = \n|clearance_below = {{convert|185|ft}} (main channel) <br/> {{convert|135|ft}} (secondary channel)\n|traffic         = 66,800 (2011)<br/>\n67,800 (2012)<br/>\n72,300 (2013)<br/>\n75,600 (2014)<br/>\n79,200 (2015)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marinij.com/article/NO/20150809/NEWS/150809801 |title=Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Traffic volume hits five-year high |author=Prado, Mark |date=August 9, 2015 |newspaper=Marin Independent Journal |accessdate=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n|open            = {{start date and age|September 1, 1956}}\n|closed          = \n|cost            = {{US$|62000000|1956|round=-5}}\n|architect       = \n|designer        = Norman Raab\n|winner          = \n|engineering     = \n|builder         = Gerwick\u2014Kiewit Joint Venture (substructure) <br/> Kiewit\u2014Soda\u2014Judson Pacific-Murphy Joint Venture (superstructure)\n|fabricator      = \n|begin           = March 1953\n|complete        = \n|replaces        = \n|toll            = Cars (westbound only) <br /> $6.00 (cash or [[FasTrak]]), $3.00 (carpools during peak hours, FasTrak only)\n|coordinates     = {{coord|37.9347|-122.4338|scale:50000_region:US-CA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|mapframe_zoom   = 9\n|map_caption     = Interactive map highlighting the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge\n}}\n\nThe '''Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge''' (also officially named the '''John F. McCarthy Memorial Bridge'''<ref>[http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/tsip/hseb/products/Named_Freeways_Final.pdf 2013 Named Freeways, Highways, Structures and Other Appurtenances in California], California Department of Transportation, 2013, pp. 150, 154 and 246. This State of California document indicates that the bridge has two official names, both enacted by legislative resolution, in 1955 and 1981 respectively.</ref>) is the northernmost of the east\u2013west crossings of the [[San Francisco Bay]] in [[California]], [[United States|USA]]. Officially named after California State Senator [[John F. McCarthy]], it bridges [[Interstate 580 (California)|Interstate 580]] from [[Richmond, California|Richmond]] on the east to [[San Rafael, California|San Rafael]] on the west. It opened in 1956, replacing ferry service by the [[Richmond\u2013San Rafael Ferry Company]].<ref name=\"quarry\">{{cite book | chapterurl = http://content.cdlib.org/view?docId=hb2m3nb1b0&chunk.id=div00033&doc.view=entire_text | chapter = Changes in the Richmond Waterfront |  accessdate = February 25, 2009 | title = Memories of the Richmond-San Rafael Ferry Company | last1 = Snodgrass | first1 = Marion Myers | last2 = Dunning | first2 = Judith K | year = 1992 | url = http://content.cdlib.org/view?docId=hb2m3nb1b0 | location = Berkeley, Calif. | publisher = [[Bancroft Library]]}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early proposals===\nProposals for a bridge were advanced in the 1920s, preceding the completion of the Golden Gate Bridge. In 1927, Roy O. Long of The Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge, Incorporated, applied for a franchise to construct and operate a private toll bridge. The proposed 1927 Long bridge would have been a steel suspension bridge, carrying a {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} roadway for a distance of {{convert|14600|ft}} at an estimated construction cost of {{US$|12000000|1927|round=-5}}. The bridge would afford a maximum vertical clearance of {{convert|135|ft}} with a {{convert|1200|ft|adj=on}} main span.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19270409.2.3&srpos=33 |title=Bridge Hearing Put Over Till Monday, 11th |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 9, 1927 |volume=XXXXIII |number=15 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> Charles Derleth, Jr. was selected as the consulting engineer, after having served in that role for the recently completed [[Carquinez Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19270226.2.13&srpos=16 |title=Propose to Construct Steel Bridge Over San Pablo Bay |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 26, 1927 |volume=XXXXIII |number=9 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> The Long bridge would have spanned [[San Pablo Bay]] between Point Orient (in [[Contra Costa County, California|Contra Costa County]]) to just below McNear's Point (in [[Marin County, California|Marin County]]), and Long was granted the franchise in February 1928 by the Contra Costa County Board of Supervisors.<ref name=SN-19280211>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280211.2.38&srpos=5 |title=Local News |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 11, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=6 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nA competing proposed bridge also came out in 1927, from Charles Van Damme of the Richmond-San Rafael Ferry Company. The 1927 Van Damme bridge would have carried a {{convert|27|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} roadway for a distance of {{convert|19000|ft}} at an identical estimated construction cost of {{US$|12000000|1927|round=-5}}.<ref name=SN-19271231>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19271231.2.10&srpos=6 |title=Ferry Head to Apply for Span Permit |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 31, 1927 |volume=XXXXIII |number=53 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> It would have spanned San Pablo Bay from [[Castro Point]] (Contra Costa County) to [[San Quentin, California|Point San Quentin]] (Marin County), approximately the same routing as the eventually completed 1956 bridge.<ref name=SN-19280211 /> Although the 1927 Long bridge had been granted a franchise in February 1928, Van Damme subsequently petitioned to reopen the case, since the ferry company owned the land at the proposed eastern terminus and therefore should have been favored in the franchise selection process.<ref name=SN-19280331>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280331.2.28&srpos=4 |title=One Bridge Gets Franchise, Other Given Rehearing |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 31, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=13 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> Also, since the ferry company's franchise rights were not set to expire until the 1950s, Long's 1927 bridge cost would have increased to reimburse losses to ferry revenues.<ref name=SN-19271231 /> Soon after winning the franchise rights, Long approached Van Damme with an offer to buy the Richmond-San Rafael Ferry Company for {{US$|1250000|1928|round=-5}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280225.2.41&srpos=3 |title=Richmond Ferry is Sold to Bridge Co. |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 25, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=8 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nVan Damme and Long later agreed in September 1928 to merge their interests for a combined bridge proposal between [[Point San Pablo Yacht Harbor|Point San Pablo]] (Contra Costa County) and McNear's Point (Marin County).<ref name=SN-19280928>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280928.2.30&srpos=1 |title=Rivals Agree On Contra Costa to Marin Crossing |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 28, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=38 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> The combined project, now headed by Oscar Klatt for the American Toll Bridge Company, received approval for the routing from then-[[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[James William Good|Good]] in May 1929, although vertical and horizontal clearances for the proposed bridge were not fully established at the time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MT19290513.2.7&srpos=3 |title=Bay Span Plan Gets Approval |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=May 13, 1929 |newspaper=Madera Tribune |agency=United Press Dispatch |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> In November 1929, vertical clearance had been increased to {{convert|160|ft}} to satisfy Navy requirements.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19291122.2.58&srpos=2 |title=Favorable Bridge Plans are Filed|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=November 22, 1929 |volume=XXXXXV |number=47 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> The construction permit was issued in February 1930.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MT19300211.2.33&srpos=1 |title=Bay Bridge Permit Given |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 11, 1929 |newspaper=Madera Tribune |agency=United Press Dispatch |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nKlatt's 1929 bridge was dormant for nearly a decade following the issuance of a construction permit in 1930. An extension was filed in 1938 to allow construction to start as late as February 1942,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19381020.2.91&srpos=29 |title=Bridge Franchise Extension Asked |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=October 20, 1938 |volume=LIII |number=42 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> and fresh plans for a bridge district to facilitate financing were announced in 1939.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19390420.2.18&srpos=30 |title=Richmond-S.R. Bridge Plan Under Way |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 20, 1939 |volume=LIV |number=16 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> In 1947, interest was revived in bridging Marin and Contra Costa Counties.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19470918.2.71&srpos=72 |title=Revive Richmond-S.R. Bridge Plan |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 18, 1947 |volume=62 |number=43 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Tomasini's San Francisco\u2013Alameda\u2013Marin crossings===\nA third bridge was proposed in late 1927 by the enigmatic T.A. Tomasini.<ref>Thomas A. Tomasini, resident in San Francisco, is also noted as the inventor of the 1916 {{patent|US|1200049|\"Automobile Spring\"}} as well as being a participant in the [[1915 American Grand Prize|1915 automobile Vanderbilt Cup Race]], where he did not start due to crashing in practice.</ref> Tomasini's 1927 bridge called for two lanes of automobile traffic straddling a central rail line from San Pedro Hill (Marin) to San Pablo station (Contra Costa), a distance of over {{convert|5|mi}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19271217.2.13&srpos=18 |title=Span Interests Eastern Capital |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 17, 1927 |volume=XXXXIII |number=51 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016}}</ref> In 1928, Tomasini presented a revised proposal for a bridge farther south than the other two bridges\u2014spanning the water from [[Albany, California|Albany]] (in [[Alameda County, California|Alameda County]]) to [[Tiburon, California|Tiburon]]. The 1928 Tomasini Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge was the longest of the three proposed bridges by a significant margin.<ref name=SN-19280331 /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280114.2.48&srpos=11 |title=Battle Expected Against Bay Span |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=January 14, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=2 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> The proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge would have been similar in concept to the 1967 [[San Mateo\u2013Hayward Bridge]], with a high-level western section approximately {{convert|7700|ft}} long transitioning to a low-level eastern causeway. The western section featured two {{convert|1000|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} spans to cross the navigation channels, with the western navigation span having a minimum vertical clearance of {{convert|150|ft}} and the eastern navigation span having a minimum vertical clearance of {{convert|135|ft}}.<ref name=SN-19280921 /> The {{convert|1000|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} navigation channels for the proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge were opposed by shipping interests, who wanted the channels to be {{convert|1500|ft}} wide instead. The cost of the longer spans required would have made the proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge impractical, and Tomasini argued that \"any mariner who could not negotiate a bridge such as proposed should lose his license.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19281019.2.20&srpos=30 |title=Shipping Men Try to Block Tomasini Bay Bridge Plan |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=October 19, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=41 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:San Francisco Bay bridges Tomasini.svg|thumb|left|250px|Tomasini's proposed 1928 San Francisco Bay crossings, shown in orange. Red bridges are those that were built, including the 1956 Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge (1). 1937 [[Golden Gate Bridge]] (2), and 1936 [[San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge|San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge]] (3) . {{ordered list |list_style_type=upper-alpha\n  |1=<!--A-->Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge\n  |2=<!--B-->Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge\n  |3=<!--C-->San Francisco\u2013Marin\u2013Alameda tunnel & bridge\n}}]]\nTomasini would later add a bridge spanning [[Richardson Bay]] in March 1928 from [[Sausalito, California|Sausalito]] to [[Belvedere, California|Belvedere]] to his proposal.<ref name=SN-19280928 /> The additional Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge would have been {{convert|7300|ft}} long and {{convert|22|ft}} wide with a lift span to allow the passage of large vessels, at an estimated cost of {{US$|750000|1928|round=-5}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280317.2.2&srpos=45 |title=Belvedere Bridge Could be Erected by Summer of '29 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 17, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=11 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=SN-19280421>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280421.2.6&srpos=41 |title=Belvedere Span Hearing is Set |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 21, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=16 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> Meanwhile, in April 1928 Tomasini recruited the prominent [[Ralph Modjeski]] to serve as the consulting head engineer for the proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon span,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280414.2.14&srpos=43 |title=Tomasini Signs Up Modjeski for Tiburon Bridge |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 14, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=15 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> and Modjeski promptly complimented the plans that had been drawn up by Tomasini's chief engineer, Erle L. Cope.<ref name=SN-19280421 /> The design for a [[Moveable bridge|lift span]] in the proposed Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge was changed to a [[Bascule bridge|bascule]] after public comments were received from a local shipbuilder.<ref name=SN-19280914>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280914.2.2&srpos=11 |title=S.F. Delays Plan of Tomasini for North Bay Bridge |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 14, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=36 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> Tomasini received a permit for the Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge from the War Department in December 1928.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19281228.2.3&srpos=9 |title=Tomasini Gets Sausalito-Belvedere Bridge Permit |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 28, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=51 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> Tomasini had planned to commence construction of the Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge in July 1930,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19300627.2.3&srpos=2 |title=Tomasini to Start Construction Work on Richardson Bay |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=June 27, 1930 |volume=XXXXVI |number=26 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> but he was met with opposition from the Tiburon-Belvedere Chamber of Commerce, who felt the creation of a bridge would eliminate the promised San Francisco-Tiburon ferry service.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19300711.2.41&srpos=3 |title=Tiburon-Belvedere Now Doesn't Want Tomasini Crossing |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=July 11, 1930 |volume=XXXXVI |number=28 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> In 1931, the Richardson Bay Redwood Bridge was opened, which was the largest structure in the world constructed of redwood.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19311113.2.69 |title=Plan is Perfected for South Marin Highway Affair |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=November 13, 1931 |volume=XXXXVII |number=46 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 29, 2016 }}</ref> The Redwood Bridge carried the Redwood Highway (present-day US 101) and spanned the upper reach of Richardson Bay,<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.marinmagazine.com/May-2009/History-of-a-Highway/ |title=History of a Highway: Marin's 101 was first established in 1909 |author=Wood, Jim |date=May 2009 |journal=Marin Magazine |accessdate=February 29, 2016 }}</ref> eliminating some of the need for the proposed Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge. The Redwood Bridge would be replaced by a concrete structure in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marinij.com/events/20110323/moving-marin-the-enormous-role-of-bridges-ferries-trains-highways |title=Moving Marin: The enormous role of bridges, ferries, trains, highways |author=Prado, Mark |date=March 23, 2011 |newspaper=Marin Independent Journal |accessdate=February 29, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nTomasini continued to add to the project scope in July 1928 by proposing a [[Fixed link|bridge and tunnel]] to join San Francisco to the proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge. The tunnel would run roughly northeast from Bay Street and Grant Avenue, not far from present-day [[Pier 39]], at a depth of {{convert|50|ft}} below low tide water level for {{convert|11200|ft}}. At that point, the tunnel would surface northwest of [[Yerba Buena Island|Goat Island]], and then transition to a bridge nearly {{convert|4|mi}} long with a minimum vertical clearance of {{convert|50|ft}} and two lift spans connecting to the proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge. The cost of the entire project was {{US$|55670000|1928|round=-5}}, split as {{US$|20000000|1928|round=-5}} for the Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge, {{US$|670000|1928|round=-5}} for the Sausalito\u2013Belvedere bridge, and {{US$|35000000|1928|round=-5}} for the San Francisco\u2013Marin\u2013Alameda tunnel and bridge.<ref name=SN-19280713>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280713.2.10&srpos=15 |title=Plans Marin-S.F. Connection with Bridge and Tube |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=July 13, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=27 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 25, 2016 }}</ref> Tomasini organized each of the three proposed structures as independent projects, preferably to be built simultaneously, but in the event that one was not approved, it would not delay the construction of the other two.<ref name=SN-19280713 /> San Francisco's board of supervisors rejected Tomasini's San Francisco\u2013Marin\u2013Alameda tunnel and bridge in September 1928, although the board's action was non-binding.<ref name=SN-19280921>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19280921.2.2&srpos=10 |title=S.F. Turns Down Span Connection to Marin County |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 21, 1928 |volume=XXXXIV |number=37 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBy February 1932, Tomasini's proposed Albany\u2013Tiburon bridge had changed to a combination bridge\u2014tunnel. The bridge portion was a low trestle approximately {{convert|19800|ft}} long, extending westward from [[Fleming Point|Point Fleming]] in Albany in Alameda County. The proposed tunnel would have been {{convert|17200|ft}} long and ventilated by four towers, emerging at Bluff Point near Tiburon in Marin County.<ref name=MDT-19320716>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MT19320716.2.2&srpos=7 |title=Approve Bay Bridge Plan |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=July 16, 1932 |volume=LX |number=63 |newspaper=Madera Daily Tribune and Madera Mercury |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> Total estimated cost for the two structures was now {{US$|35000000|1932|round=-5}} and despite opposition from the US Navy, who cited potential navigation hazards,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19320401.2.37&srpos=19 |title=Tomasini's Bridge Plan Protested |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 1, 1932 |volume=XXXXVIII |number=14 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 24, 2016 }}</ref> the bridge\u2014tunnel was approved by the War Department in July 1932.<ref name=MDT-19320716 /> Although he had the permit to begin work, Tomasini filed numerous annual extensions to retain the rights through 1941,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19401205.2.83&srpos=5 |title=Tomasini Bridge Permit Extension Again Asked<!--Wow, what a salty headline!--> |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 5, 1940 |volume=LV |number=48 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> apparently due to a lack of funding to start work. Tomasini was still scrambling for funding in August 1941, seeking the issue of bonds worth {{US$|20000000|1941|round=-5}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19410821.2.22&srpos=4 |title=20 Million Bond Issue Sought for Span-Tube |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=August 21, 1941 |volume=LVI |number=34 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> Tomasini lost the rights to the crossing in October 1941,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19411002.2.8&srpos=3 |title=Rights to Span Tube Lost by Tomasini |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=October 2, 1941 |volume=LVI |number=40 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> which was not the first time he was opposed by [[Earl Warren]], who had questioned the validity of Tomasini's franchise as early as 1933.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19330407.2.44&srpos=7 |title=Tomasini Says He Is Going to Build Span |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 7, 1933 |volume=XLVIII |number=14 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref> Still, Tomasini was doggedly trying to advance his plans as late as 1948.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN19481216.2.58&srpos=1 |title=Richardson Bay Bridge Plan Again Revived |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 16, 1948 |volume=63 |number=51 |newspaper=Sausalito News |accessdate=February 26, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Construction: 1953\u20131956===\nIn 1949, the County of Marin and the City of Richmond commissioned a preliminary engineering report from Earl and Wright of San Francisco, which concluded that a bridge would be feasible.<ref name=CHPW1953>{{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1953_novdec.pdf |title=New Bay Crossing: Story of the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge |pages=1\u20136; 64 |volume=32 |number=11\u201312 |author=Raab, Norman A. |date=November\u2013December 1953 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}</ref> A follow-up 1950 study, conducted by the Division of San Francisco Bay Toll Crossings, was commissioned by Marin County and the City of Richmond using {{US$|200000|1950|round=-4}} in state funding. The 1950 report concluded the bridge could be built in accordance with the California Toll Bridge Authority Act.<ref name=CHPW1953 /> The preliminary design was approved on 1951-08-08 and California approved the preliminary report on 1951-11-27. The California Toll Bridge Authority authorized the issue of {{US$|72000000|1952|round=-5}} in bonds on 1952-11-07 and subsequently sold {{US$|62000000|1953|round=-5}} on 1953-02-26 to construct a single-deck bridge. The remaining {{US$|10000000|1953|round=-5}} was reserved for construction contingencies and to complete the lower deck of the bridge.<ref name=CHPW1956-0708 /> The $62 million raised from bond sales was divided into three parts: {{US$|50000000|1953|round=-5}} for construction, {{US$|10000000|1953|round=-5}} to address interest obligations on the bonds during the construction period, and {{US$|2000000|1953|round=-5}} in construction contingency.<ref name=CHPW1956-0708 /> In 1954, [[Goodwin Knight|Governor Knight]] declared the second deck should not be delayed in the public interest, and {{US$|6000000|1955|round=-5}} was loaned from the State School Land Fund in 1955 to complete the second deck. The bridge was finished $4 million under budget.<ref name=BridgeTheBay />\n\nDuring the study period, an earth and rock-fill bridge with lift structures was considered, but the high-level bridge was chosen as the cost of a low bridge with navigation locks and lifting structures was prohibitive.<ref name=CHPW1953 />\n\nThe majority of construction costs were tied up in two contracts that opened for bidding on 1952-12-19. The first contract, for the substructure, was awarded to the low bidder,  the Ben C. Gerwick, Inc. \u2014 Peter Kiewit Sons' Co. Joint Venture for {{US$|14234550|1953|round=-5}}. The second contract, for the superstructure, was awarded to the low bid of {{US$|21099319|1953|round=-5}} by a joint venture between Peter Kiewit Sons' Co. \u2014 A. Soda & Son \u2014 Judson Pacific Murphy Corp.<ref name=CHPW1953 /> The substructure construction moved rapidly, with an estimated 45% of piers completed approximately a year after the contract was awarded.<ref name=CHPW-19540304 />\n\nAt the time the bridge was completed, it was hailed as the world's second-longest bridge, behind the San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zCEhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=72QEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2923%2C2231090 |title=Frisco Adds Another Bridge To Skyline |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=August 16, 1956 |newspaper=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |accessdate=March 1, 2016}}</ref> and the longest continuous steel bridge.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nORQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mSUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7048%2C1698009 |title=Straits Bridge Claim Challenged on Coast |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=June 24, 1958 |newspaper=The Milwaukee Journal |accessdate=March 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Historical notes===\nOriginally a part of [[California State Route 17|State Route 17]], the bridge is now part of [[Interstate 580 (California)|Interstate 580]].\n\nUpon its opening, the Richmond\u2013San Rafael bridge was the last bridge across San Francisco Bay to replace a previous ferry service, leaving the [[Benicia\u2013Martinez Bridge|Benicia\u2013Martinez Ferry]] across Carquinez Strait as the only remaining auto ferry in the Bay Area (it would be replaced by a bridge in 1962).\n\n==Description==\n[[File:San_Francisco_Bay_Bridges_map_en.svg|thumb|Bridges in the San Francisco Bay]]\n[[File:Caltrans District4 7836D059.jpg|thumb|Vertical undulation of the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge between the two cantilever spans]]\nThe bridge\u2014including approaches\u2014measures 5.5 miles (29,040 feet / 8,851.39 m / 8.9&nbsp;km) long. At the time it was built, it was one of the world's longest bridges. The bridge spans two ship channels and has two separate main [[cantilever bridge|cantilever]] spans. Both main cantilever spans are raised to allow ship traffic to pass, and in between, there is a \"dip\" in the elevation of the center section,<ref name=CSeim>{{cite interview |url=http://digitalassets.lib.berkeley.edu/roho/ucb/text/seim_chuck.pdf |title=Charles Seim: The Bay Bridge Oral History Project |interviewer=Sam Redman |subject=Seim, Chuck |page=21 |date=2013 |publisher=The Bancroft Library, University of California |location=Berkeley |accessdate=February 6, 2015 |quote=When it comes to the Richmond-San Rafael designed by Norman C. Raab, first of all, it zigzags because of the two alignments of the navigation channels. It goes up, and then it sags down, and then it goes up. The cardinal rule of aesthetics in a bridge is it has to soar. You can't sag it in the middle. The other is it connects from here to there as a straight line or as a curve line. You don't make an \"S\" out of it. Those violate both of those very strong principles. This engineer [Raab] was soundly criticized for creating this ugly bridge. Of course, his defense was, \"I saved a million dollars by putting the sag in it.\" Which is probably true.}}</ref> giving the bridge a vertical undulation or \"[[roller coaster]]\" appearance and also the nickname \"roller coaster span\". To save money, the cantilever main spans share identical symmetric designs, so the \"uphill\" grade on the approach required for the elevated span is duplicated on the other \"downhill\" side, resulting in a depressed center truss section.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marinij.com/article/ZZ/20060901/NEWS/609019964 |title=With little fanfare... |date=September 1, 2006 |author=Prado, Mark |newspaper=Marin Independent Journal |accessdate=February 26, 2016}}</ref> In addition, because the navigation channels are not parallel to each other, the bridge also does not follow a straight line.<ref>''Interview with Chuck Seim'' (2013), p. 8 & 30. \"Now, the twin spans, they were spanned by what we call a steel cantilever span. But the interesting thing is that these shipping channels were not parallel to one another. They angled.\"</ref> This appearance has also been referred to as a \"bent coat hanger\".<ref name=BridgeTheBay>{{cite web |url=http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/news_events/bridge/rsr.html |title=Bridging the Bay: Bridging the Campus - Richmond-San Rafael |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 22, 1999 |website=UC Berkeley Library |accessdate=February 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter it was completed, many were disappointed by the aesthetics of the low budget bridge,<ref>''Interview with Chuck Seim'' (2013), p. 20. \"Of course, everybody criticized the truss bridge on the Richmond-San Rafael, that Raab designed and they said, 'We don't want an ugly truss here.' [...] Well, if you had to award the ugliest bridge in the world, I think the Richmond-San Rafael would certainly be in the running. If not the first one, then top three. It is an ugly bridge. But that's a story that maybe we shouldn't get into. It was driven by economics, and it was driven by the obstinance of this one engineer that I referred to. He wouldn't change. He then proposed a truss for the Hayward area, and everybody said, 'No, we don't want that. It's an ugly bridge.' He said, 'Well, it's the most economical.'\"</ref> including [[Frank Lloyd Wright]], who reportedly called for its destruction<ref name=TYLin>{{cite interview |url=http://content.cdlib.org/view?docId=kt4w1003s9&chunk.id=d0e11453 |title=\"The Father of Prestressed Concrete\": Teaching Engineers, Bridging Rivers and Borders, 1931 to 1999 |subject=Lin, TY |subject-link=Tung-Yen Lin |interviewer=Eleanor Swent |chapter=VIII Developing Prestressed Concrete Technology: The Richmond-San Rafael Bridge: Misjudgment to Save Money |language=English |date=1999 |publisher=The Regents of the University of California |place=Berkeley |accessdate=February 24, 2016 |quote=Lin: So, one architect asked [Wright], \"What do you think of the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge?\" \"I think it should be sabotaged!\" He meant that it should be bombed, it's so ugly looking.}}</ref> and called it \"the most awful thing I've ever seen\" in 1953, during its construction.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SCS19530501.1.6 |title=Architect Chides Design Of New North Bay Bridge |agency=AP |date=May 1, 1953 |newspaper=Santa Cruz Sentinel |accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref> The neighboring [[Golden Gate Bridge]] and the western span of [[San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge|Bay Bridge]] were considered engineering and historical marvels, and the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge was not considered in the same class. However, the senior engineers for the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge were the same engineers that worked on the Bay Bridge<ref>''Interview with Chuck Seim'' (2013), pp. 8\u201310. \"Everybody working on that bridge - I think it's safe to say all the higher-echelon engineers - were the same engineers that worked on the San Francisco Bay Bridge. I had a chance to work with engineers who actually worked on the San Francisco Bay Bridge, and I used to read about that when I was a kid.\"</ref> and the resulting design echoed the lessons learned from the eastern span of the Bay Bridge.<ref>''Interview with Chuck Seim'' (2013), p. 30. \"In 1956, the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge was opened. An interesting thing about that is that most of the senior engineers that worked on the Bay Bridge stayed over in San Francisco and worked on the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge, because they both used the same technology, with some minor variations.\"</ref>\n\nFrom west (Point San Quentin) to east (Castro Point), the bridge consists of:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/esc/tollbridge/Rich-SR/Rich-layout.pdf |title=Pier and Bent Layout: Richmond-San Rafael Bridge (Sheet No. RS-224) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Caltrans |accessdate=February 22, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=CHPW-19540304>{{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1954_marapr.pdf |title=Pier Construction: Rapid Progress on Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Project |pages=20\u201325; 32\u201333; 64 |author=Raab, Norman A. |date=March\u2013April 1954 |volume=33 |number=3\u20134 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}</ref>\n* A {{convert|2845|ft|adj=on}} [[trestle|trestle structure]] supported by fifty-seven [[bent (structural)|bents]]. The upper deck is {{convert|2845|ft}}, and the lower deck is slightly longer at {{convert|3635|ft}}.\n* {{convert|1900|ft}} of [[girder bridge|girder spans]], consisting of nineteen {{convert|100|ft|adj=on}} girder spans\n* {{convert|4125|ft}} of [[truss bridge|truss spans]], divided into fourteen trusses each {{convert|292|ft}} long, on average.\n* The western {{convert|2145|ft|adj=on}} [[cantilever bridge|cantilever structure]], with arms measuring {{convert|538|ft}} each flanking a central span of {{convert|1070|ft}}. The western cantilever span is the main {{convert|1070|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} navigation channel and features a vertical clearance of {{convert|185|ft}}.\n* {{convert|2955|ft}} of truss spans, consisting of ten spans each {{convert|292|ft}} long, on average.\n* The eastern {{convert|2145|ft|adj=on}} cantilever structure, with arms measuring {{convert|538|ft}} each flanking a central span of {{convert|1070|ft}}. The eastern cantilever span is the secondary {{convert|1070|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} navigation channel and features a reduced vertical clearance of {{convert|135|ft}}.\n* {{convert|3505|ft}} of truss spans, consisting of twelve spans each {{convert|292|ft}} long, on average.\n* {{convert|1715|ft}} of {{convert|100|ft|adj=on}} girder spans\nExcluding approaches, the bridge structures comprise a total length of {{convert|21335|ft}} on the upper deck and {{convert|22125|ft}} on the lower deck. Despite the varying height of the bridge, roadway grades are limited to 3% or less.<ref name=CHPW1953 /><ref name=CHPW-19540304 /> As completed, the bridge has two decks each capable of carrying three lanes of traffic. {{As of|2018}}, westbound traffic rides on the upper deck and is marked with two lanes of vehicle traffic and a shoulder, while eastbound traffic rides on the lower deck and features two lanes of vehicle traffic as well as a third lane that is activated during evening commute hours and serves as a shoulder when not in use. The extra lane features lights indicating that the lane is open or closed.<ref name=3rdLane /> The third lane has been used for various purposes other than traffic, such as carrying a [[water pipeline]] during a drought.\n\n[[Image:Richmond San Rafael Bridge 07802.JPG|thumb|left|View southwest from above Richmond]]\nThe bridge stands on 79 reinforced concrete piers supported on steel H-piles. Nine piers stand on land, eight are in cofferdams near the Contra Costa terminus, and the remaining 62 are bell-type piers with a flared base.<ref name=CHPW-19540304 /> The original deck was a {{convert|5.5|in|adj=on}} thick reinforced concrete slab, with a mortar wearing surface {{convert|0.5|in}} thick.<ref name=CHPW-19540708>{{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1954_julaug.pdf |title=Bridge Innovations: New Operation Facilities On Richmond-San Rafael Span |pages=14\u201315; 32\u201333 |author=Raab, Norman C. |volume=33 |number=7\u20138 |date=July\u2013August 1954 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}</ref> To facilitate maintenance, the bridge was designed with two {{convert|2.5|in}} lines (carrying compressed air and potable water) extending from end to end. Each deck was also equipped with three overhead maintenance tracks.<ref name=CHPW-19540708 />\n\n===Public transit service===\n[[Golden Gate Transit]] bus routes 40 and 580 provide public transportation across the bridge. Route 40 runs between the [[San Rafael Transit Center]] and the [[El Cerrito del Norte (BART station)|El Cerrito del Norte BART station]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goldengatetransit.org/schedules/current/route_40.php |title=Route 40 Basic Bus Route Effective December 13, 2015 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=December 13, 2015 |website=Golden Gate Transit |accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref> Golden Gate Transit Route 42, which provided service to [[Richmond Station (California)|Richmond BART/Amtrak]] station, was folded into Route 40 in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goldengate.org/news/transit/route-42-elimination-travel-alternatives.php |title=GGT Routes 40 & 42 Merging - Service to Richmond BART Station Discontinued |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=November 10, 2015 |website=Golden Gate Transit |accessdate=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Tolls==\n[[File:Caltrans District4 7916D003.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Toll plaza at Richmond in 2006 before newest reconstruction]]\nTolls are only collected from westbound traffic headed to San Rafael at the toll plaza on the east side of the bridge. Since January 2019, the toll rate for (two axle) passenger cars and motorcycles is $6.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bayareafastrak.org/en/howitworks/whereToUse.shtml#richmond|title=FasTrak|website=www.bayareafastrak.org|access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> During peak traffic hours, [[carpool|high-occupancy vehicles]] (defined as two-axle vehicles without trailers, carrying three or more people; two-axle vehicles designed with two passenger seats without trailers, carrying two people; or motorcycles) pay a discounted toll of $3.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = Frequently Asked Toll Questions | publisher = Bay Area Toll Authority | date = June 1, 2010 | url = http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/faq.htm#2 | accessdate = June 29, 2010| archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5tv1MQCqO | archivedate = November 1, 2010| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Toll Increase Information | publisher = Bay Area Toll Authority | date = June 1, 2010 | url =http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/ | accessdate = June 29, 2010| archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOZ | archivedate = November 1, 2010| url-status=live}}</ref> Since January 1, 2019, for vehicles with more than two axles, the toll rate is $16 for 3 axles and $5 per each additional axle over 3, up to a maximum toll of $36 for vehicles with seven or more axles.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Toll Increase Information: Multi-Axle Vehicles |publisher=Bay Area Toll Authority |date=July 1, 2012 |url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/multi-axle.htm |accessdate=December 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230234900/http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/multi-axle.htm |archivedate=December 30, 2013 }}</ref> Drivers may either pay by cash or use the [[FasTrak]] [[electronic toll collection]] device.\n\n=== Historical toll rates ===\nThe following initial toll rates were adopted on July 10, 1956 prior to the opening of the bridge:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''Inaugural toll schedule'''<ref name=CHPW1956-0708>{{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1956_julaug.pdf |title=Record Span New Crossing: Richmond-San Rafael Bridge About Ready for Traffic |pages=1\u20134; 22 |volume=35 |number=7\u20138 |author=Raab, Norman C. |date=July\u2013August 1956 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Vehicle type\n! scope=\"col\" | Axles/trailers\n! scope=\"col\" | Toll\n\n|-\n! rowspan=4 | Class 1{{efn |name= |Class 1 vehicles are defined as: automobiles, motorcycles, tri-cars, light delivery automobiles, ambulances, hearses, housecars, noncommercial trucks, station wagons, and taxis.}}\n| vehicle alone\n| {{US$|0.75|1956|round=2}}{{efn |Motorcycle toll was initially proposed as {{US$|0.25|1956|round=2}}, but Norman Raab successfully argued the tight pants worn by motorcyclists meant the driver would have to dismount to retrieve the coins for the toll.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YftXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=x_YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=753%2C986448 |title=Tight Pants Cause High Toll Request |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=June 20, 1956 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |accessdate=February 18, 2016 |agency=AP}}</ref>}}\n\n|-\n| Commutation book{{efn |Commutation books were sold with 50 one-way tickets good for a single passage at any time during the two consecutive calendar months, or fractional part thereof, for which sold.}}{{efn |Any Class 1 vehicle, with the exception of light delivery automobiles and noncommercial trucks, was eligible for the commutation book.}}\n| {{US$|18.75|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| with 1-axle trailer\n| {{US$|1.25|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| with 2-axle trailer\n| {{US$|1.50|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n! rowspan=6 |Truck{{efn |A truck shall include a truck-tractor, or any combination of truck, truck-tractor and trailer or semitrailer}}\n| 2-axle\n| {{US$|1.25|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 3-axle\n| {{US$|1.75|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 4-axle\n| {{US$|2.50|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 5-axle\n| {{US$|3.00|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 6-axle\n| {{US$|3.50|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 7-axle\n| {{US$|4.00|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n! rowspan=2 |Bus\n| 2-axle\n| {{US$|1.50|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| 3-axle\n| {{US$|1.75|1956|round=2}}\n\n|-\n| colspan=2 |Other vehicles not specified above\n| {{US$|5.00|1956|round=2}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" align=center|Inaugural toll table notes\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |{{notelist|30em}}\n|}\n\nThe basic toll (for automobiles) on the seven state bridges, including the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge, was raised to $1 by Regional Measure 1, approved by Bay Area voters in 1988.<ref>[http://bata.mtc.ca.gov/projects/rm1.htm Regional Measure 1 Toll Bridge Program]. ''bata.mtc.ca.gov''; [[Bay Area Toll Authority]]. {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOE?url=http://bata.mtc.ca.gov/projects/rm1.htm |date=November 1, 2010 }}</ref> A $1 seismic retrofit surcharge was added in 1998 by the state legislature, originally for eight years, but since then extended to December 2037 (AB1171, October 2001).<ref name='AB1171'>{{cite news|first=John |last=Dutra |title=AB 1171 Assembly Bill \u2013 Chaptered |date=October 14, 2001 |publisher=[[California State Assembly]] |url=http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/01-02/bill/asm/ab_1151-1200/ab_1171_bill_20011014_chaptered.html |accessdate=August 7, 2008 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOL?url=http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/01-02/bill/asm/ab_1151-1200/ab_1171_bill_20011014_chaptered.html |archivedate=November 1, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 2, 2004, voters approved Regional Measure 2, raising the toll by another dollar to a total of $3. An additional dollar was added to the toll starting January 1, 2007, to cover cost overruns concerning the replacement of the eastern span.\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Transportation Commission (San Francisco Bay Area)|Metropolitan Transportation Commission]], a regional transportation agency, in its capacity as the [[Bay Area Toll Authority]], administers RM1 and RM2 funds, allocating a significant portion to public transit capital improvements and operating subsidies in the transportation corridors the bridges serve. Caltrans administers the \"second dollar\" seismic surcharge, and receives some of the MTC-administered funds to perform other maintenance work on the bridges. The Bay Area Toll Authority is made up of appointed officials put in place by various city and county governments, and is not subject to direct voter oversight.<ref>{{cite web|title=About MTC |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Commission |date=October 15, 2009 |url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/about_mtc/about.htm |accessdate=October 15, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv15npOg?url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/about_mtc/about.htm |archivedate=November 1, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDue to further funding shortages for seismic retrofit projects, the Bay Area Toll Authority again raised tolls on all seven of the state-owned bridges in July 2010. The toll rate for autos on the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge was thus increased to $5.<ref>{{cite web |title=Frequently Asked Toll Questions |publisher=Bay Area Toll Authority |date=June 1, 2010 |url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/faq.htm#2 |accessdate=June 29, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tv1MQCqO?url=http://www.mtc.ca.gov/tolls/faq.htm#2 |archivedate=November 1, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Bay Area voters approved Regional Measure 3 to further raise the tolls on all seven of the state-owned bridges to fund $4.5 billion worth of transportation improvements in the area.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/3-hike-to-Bay-Area-tolls-appears-to-have-support-12972027.php | title=Regional Measure 3: Work on transportation improvements could start next year | first=Michael | last=Cabanatuan | publisher=SFGate.com | date=June 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/bay-area-bridge-tolls-to-increase-one-dollar-in-january-except-golden-gate | title=Bay Area bridge tolls to increase one dollar in January, except Golden Gate | first=Christien | last=Kafton | publisher=KTVU | date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> Under the passed measure, the toll rate for autos on the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge will be increased to $6 on January 1, 2019; to $7 on January 1, 2022; and then to $8 on January 1, 2025.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://mtc.ca.gov/whats-happening/news/tolls-seven-bay-area-bridges-set-rise-next-month | title=Tolls on Seven Bay Area Bridges Set to Rise Next Month | publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Commission | date=December 11, 2018 | accessdate=December 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, the MTC approved a $4 million plan to eliminate toll takers and convert all seven of the state-owned bridges to [[all-electronic tolling]], citing that 80 percent of drivers are now using Fastrak and the change would improve traffic flow.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/california/article234765937.html | title=Do you drive to the Bay Area? A big change is coming to toll booths at the bridges | first=Darrell | last=Smith | newspaper=The Sacramento Bee | date=September 7, 2019 | accessdate=April 12. 2020}}</ref> On March 20, 2020, at midnight, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], all-electronic tolling was temporarily placed in effect for all seven state-owned toll bridges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mtc.ca.gov/whats-happening/news/cash-toll-collection-suspended-bay-area-bridges|title=Cash Toll Collection Suspended at Bay Area Bridges|date=March 20, 2020|website=Metropolitan Transportation Commission|language=en|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Improvements==\n\n===Seismic retrofit===\n[[Image:R-SR Pier Seismic Reconstruction Compared.png|thumb|left|250px|Comparison of piers at eastern cantilever span in 2003 before reconstruction (top) and at western cantilever span in 2011 after reconstruction (bottom).]]\nIn the fall of 2001, the bridge commenced an extensive [[seismic retrofit]] program,<ref name=Welcome-Retrofit>{{cite web |url=http://66.120.196.62/rsrbridge/ |title=Welcome to the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Seismic Retrofit Project |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2004 |website=Caltrans |accessdate=March 1, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040404101112/http://66.120.196.62/rsrbridge/ |archivedate=April 4, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> similar to other bridges in the area.<ref name=\"sfgate\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/SAN-RAFAEL-Seismic-work-jolts-commute-2784147.php |title=SAN RAFAEL / Seismic work jolts commute / Retrofit on Richmond Bridge on schedule, but drivers fuming |author=Cabanatuan, Michael |date=May 3, 2004 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=September 29, 2013}}</ref> The retrofit was designed by a three-way joint venture between [[COWI A/S|Gerwick]]/[[Sverdrup & Parcel|Sverdrup]]/[[AECOM|DMJM]] under a {{US$|19000000|1995|round=-5}} design contract awarded in 1995.<ref name=Ger9509>{{cite web |url=http://www.gerwick.com/document.asp?DocumentID=3 |title=Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Seismic Retrofit |author=Vincent, John |date=September 1995 |website=Ben C. Gerwick, Inc. |accessdate=March 1, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040429081357/http://www.gerwick.com/document.asp?DocumentID=3 |archivedate=April 29, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The retrofit is intended to allow the two-tier bridge to withstand a 7.4 magnitude earthquake on the [[Hayward Fault Zone|Hayward Fault]] and an 8.3 magnitude quake on the [[San Andreas Fault]]. The foundation piers were strengthened by wrapping the lower section of structural steel in a concrete casing, installing new shear piles, and adding bracing to the structural steel towers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gerwick.com/project-detail.asp?ProjectID=259 |title=Project Description: Richmond-San Rafael Bridge |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1998 |website=Ben C. Gerwick, Inc. |accessdate=March 1, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040405132128/http://www.gerwick.com/project-detail.asp?ProjectID=259 |archivedate=April 5, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Isolation joints and bearings were also added to the main bridge structures (cantilever spans over the navigation channels) to strengthen the structure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://66.120.196.62/rsrbridge/construction/default.asp |title=Construction |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2004 |website=Caltrans |accessdate=March 1, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040405103107/http://66.120.196.62/rsrbridge/construction/default.asp |archivedate=April 4, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe fifty-year-old bridge was showing its age and also needed age-related maintenance, which was performed in conjunction with the seismic upgrade work. There were reports of cars being damaged while traveling on the lower deck by fist-sized concrete chunks falling from the joints of upper deck slabs.\n\nA major part of the retrofit involved the long concrete causeway on the Marin side, which as part of the retrofit program, was nearly completely replaced. Because of the active use of the bridge, Caltrans designed the project to allow the bridge to remain open to traffic. For economy, schedule efficiency and traffic impact mitigation, much of the repair work was fabricated off site and shipped to the bridge by barge.\n\nTo reduce impacts to traffic the major work was performed at night.  Caltrans kept two lanes of traffic moving in each direction during daylight hours, then reduced that flow to a single lane in each direction at night. Thus, one trestle was completely closed, and the other trestle had two-way traffic.\n\nThe concrete segments of the trestle were precast in [[Petaluma, California|Petaluma]] and barged to the site. At monthly intervals, tugs positioned barges with one or two {{convert|100|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}}, 500-ton pre-cast concrete roadway segments, which a 900-ton barge-mounted crane lifted into place. Earlier, either two or four of the corroded, {{convert|50|ft|m|adj=mid}} concrete segments of the old roadway were removed by crane. Then, a pile driver moved into position and drove new piles. After the new concrete road segment was in place, steel plates were used to temporarily fill the gaps, and the roadway was ready for morning traffic. At times, construction backed up traffic to Highway 101 into central San Rafael.\n\nThe completion of this retrofit, on September 22, 2005 was celebrated as a success despite the many challenges, including the deaths of two workers.\n\nThe retrofit was originally estimated by Caltrans engineers at {{US$|329000000|1999|round=-5}},<ref name=\"sfgate\" /> but Caltrans adjusted the estimate to {{US$|393272000|2000|round=-5}} in 2000 during the bidding process.<ref name=Bid-Summary>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/esc/tollbridge/Rich-SR/0438U4/docs/bidsummary.pdf |title=Bid Summary, Contract No. 04-0438U4 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=August 9, 2000 |website=State of California Department of Transportation |accessdate=March 1, 2016}}</ref> While most of the resulting bids were close to {{US$|545000000|2000|round=-5}}, the low bid came in at {{US$|484403479|2000|round=-5}} from the Tutor-Saliba/Koch/Tidewater Joint Venture.<ref name=Bid-Summary /> Caltrans revised their estimate to {{US$|665000000|2001|round=-5}} in May 2001 when more funds were appropriated for California's Toll Bridge Seismic Retrofit Program in Assembly Bill 1171.<ref>{{cite California statute |year=2001 |chapter=907 |page=7396}} {{cite web |url=ftp://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/01-02/bill/asm/ab_1151-1200/ab_1171_bill_20011014_chaptered.html |title=Assembly Bill 1171 |publisher=California Legislative Information |format=PDF |access-date=November 20, 2015}}</ref> The cost was again adjusted during an August 2004 review by Caltrans, this time to {{US$|914000000|2004|round=-5}}.<ref name=\"programreport\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/baybridge/seismic_retrofit_program_reports/TBSRPSecondQuarterReportEndingJune302005.pdf |title=Toll Bridge Seismic Retrofit Program Report, Second Quarter 2005 |author=California Department of Transportation| access-date=November 20, 2015}}</ref> The final cost of the retrofit, however, was $778 million, or $136 million below this August 2004 estimate.<ref name=\"programreport\" />\n\n===Third lanes===\n[[File:Richmond California.JPG|thumb|right|Aerial photo of bay]]\n[[Image:Wfm richmond bridge.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial photo of the bridge and the surrounding area]]\n\nIn both directions, the bridge is wide enough to accommodate three lanes of traffic. Currently the third lane on the lower deck is used as a right-hand shoulder or a \"breakdown lane\" and is marked along the bridge with the signs \"Emergency Parking Only\". The third lane on the upper deck is a separated bicycle and pedestrian path<ref name=\"bike\"/>.\n\nIn 1977, Marin County was suffering one of its worst droughts in history. A temporary on-surface pipeline, six miles (10&nbsp;km) long, was placed in the third lane. The pipe transferred 8,000,000 gallons of water a day from the [[East Bay Municipal Utility District]]'s mains in Richmond to Marin's 170,000 residents.  By 1978, the drought subsided and the pipeline was removed.  The disused third lane was then restriped as a shoulder.\n\nIn 1989, after the [[Loma Prieta earthquake]], the third lane was opened up as a normal lane to accommodate increased traffic after the [[San Francisco\u2013Oakland Bay Bridge|Bay Bridge]] was shut down because of a failure of that span.{{cn|date=May 2018}} Many commuters from San Francisco drove across the Golden Gate Bridge into Marin and then across the Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge to go to Oakland (and vice versa). After the Bay Bridge was reopened, the third lane was again closed.\n\nOn February 11, 2015, the [[Bay Area Toll Authority]] approved a plan to install a protected bike and pedestrian path on the wide shoulder of the upper deck of the bridge. The path was expected to be complete in 2017, <ref name=\"bike\">{{cite web|last1=Rivera|first1=Renee|title=Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Bike Path approved|url=https://bikeeastbay.org/news/richmond-san-rafael-bridge-bike-path-approved|website=bikeeastbay.org|publisher=East Bay Bicycle Coalition|accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> however it opened on November 16, 2019.<ref>https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/11/17/long-awaited-richmond-san-rafael-bridge-transbay-bike-lane-opens/</ref> As part of the same project, a third eastbound lane<ref>{{cite news|last1=Prado|first1=Mark|title=Big changes planned for Richmond-San Rafael Bridge|url=http://www.marinij.com/general-news/20150211/big-changes-planned-for-richmond-san-rafael-bridge|accessdate=August 5, 2015|work=Marin Independent Journal|date=February 11, 2015}}</ref> was added the previous year on the lower deck to be available for evening commutes.<ref name=3rdLane>{{cite news|last1=Prado|first1=Mark|title=Third lane on Richmond-San Rafael Bridge open for business|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2018/04/23/third-lane-on-richmond-san-rafael-bridge-open-for-business/|accessdate=May 3, 2018|agency=East Bay Times|date=April 23, 2018}}</ref> \n\n\n\n{{Wide image|Richmond-San Rafeal Bridge wide.jpg<!--Note: The filename of this photo is a misspelling of the bridge's name.-->|500px|View from the east end of the bridge (Richmond) looking southwest toward Southern Marin. San Quentin State Prison is at the far end of the bridge (San Rafael), just beyond the edge of the picture on the right. Top right above the bridge is Mount Tamalpais. The broken pilings in the water in the middle left of the picture are the remains of the pier where the Richmond\u2013San Rafael ferry docked before the bridge was built.|alt=Looking west, across the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge.}}\n\n==Closures==\nLike most San Francisco Bay bridges, this bridge is occasionally closed due to strong crosswinds. The bridge was closed on the morning of Friday, January 4, 2008 as a southerly wind gusting to nearly {{convert|70|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} buffeted the span, knocking over four trucks on the lower deck and one truck on the upper deck. The bridge was closed for six hours. It was re-opened by late afternoon as the strong winds subsided.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nThis was not the first closure due to high winds. A tractor-trailer overturned in high winds in 1963, forcing the closure of two lanes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19630131.1.1 |title=Storm, Wind Lash Bay City |author= |agency=AP |date=January 31, 1963 |newspaper=San Bernardino Sun |accessdate=April 16, 2018}}</ref> At least one previous event occurred in the late 1970s when high northerly winds forced the CHP to close the bridge. Wind gusts (reported in the Marin Independent Journal) reached 80&nbsp;mph.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nOn October 27, 2000 the toll plaza allowed people to cross free of charge due to a \"shelter in place\" order affecting toll booth operators.  The order was given by the [[Richmond Fire Department]] in response to a release of toxic gas from a recycling plant.<ref>[http://www.berkeleydailyplanet.com/issue/2000-10-27/article/1831?headline=Man-dies-in-recycling-plant-explosion--Daily-Planet-wire-reports- Man dies in recycling plant explosion], October 27, 2000, access date July 3, 2012</ref>\n\nOn February 7, 2019 the bridge was closed for several hours due to concrete falling from the upper deck to the lower.<ref>[https://www.sfgate.com/traffic/article/580-richmond-san-rafael-bridge-closed-concrete-13598563.php Falling concrete closes Richmond-San Rafael Bridge in both directions] February 7, 2019</ref>\n\n==In popular culture & film==\nThe novel ''Abuse of Power'' by [[Michael Savage]] has several important scenes set on the bridge. In one, the hero Jack Hatfield escapes his enemies by climbing the work ladders built into the piers.In the film ''Magnum Force'', the bridge is in the background when Dirty Harry and the rookie cop are on motorcycles on the ship's decks where they attempt to subdue each other.<ref>Scene 34. Not Enough Experience. ''Magnum Force''</ref> The bridge is also visible in the 1982 film [[48 Hours (film)|48 Hours]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Richmond-San Rafael Bridge}}\n* [http://www.marinij.com/marin/ci_4271565 With Little Fanfare... ''Marin IJ'' article on the 50th anniversary of the bridge]\n* [http://www.mtc.ca.gov/news/info/RSR_bridge.htm Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge Retrofit Completed]\n*[http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/esc/tollbridge/Rich-SR/Rich-SR.html Caltrans Seismic Retrofit overview]\n* [http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/traffops/hwybrdg/tollbridge/History/richmond.html California Dept. of Transportation: Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge History & Information]\n* {{Structurae|id=20000539|title=Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge}}\n* [http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/news_events/exhibits/bridge/rsr.html Univ. of California, Berkeley: Bridging the Bay: Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge]\n* [http://www.marinbike.org/Campaigns/Infrastructure/RSRBridge.shtml Decades of Struggle for Bicycle Access]\n* [http://bata.mtc.ca.gov/bridges/richmond-sr.htm Bay Area Toll Authority\u2014Bridge Facts\u2014Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge]\n* [http://diva.sfsu.edu/collections/sfbatv/bundles/189372 Footage of the official bridge opening ceremony from September 1956]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/schuberts/5129108197 Eastern cantilever span from Point Richmond looking West]\n* [http://www.batolls.info/bridges/richmond_san_rafael_bridge.html Live Toll Prices for Richmond-San Rafael Bridge]\n* {{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1953_novdec.pdf |title=New Bay Crossing: Story of the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge |pages=1\u20136; 64 |author=Raab, Norman A. |date=November\u2013December 1953 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}\n* {{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1954_marapr.pdf |title=Pier Construction: Rapid Progress on Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Project |pages=20\u201325; 32\u201333; 64 |author=Raab, Norman A. |date=March\u2013April 1954 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}\n* {{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1954_julaug.pdf |title=Bridge Innovations: New Operation Facilities On Richmond-San Rafael Span |pages=14\u201315; 32\u201333 |author=Raab, Norman C. |date=July\u2013August 1954 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}\n* {{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1956_julaug.pdf |title=Record Span New Crossing: Richmond-San Rafael Bridge About Ready for Traffic |pages=1\u20134; 22 |author=Raab, Norman C. |date=July\u2013August 1956 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}\n* {{cite journal |url=http://libraryarchives.metro.net/DPGTL/Californiahighways/chpw_1957_novdec.pdf |title=Freeway Approach to Bridge Opened in Marin County |page=29 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=November\u2013December 1957 |journal=California Highways and Public Works |publisher=California Department of Public Works |accessdate=February 18, 2016 }}\n* {{cite report |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000055913 |title=Richmond-San Rafael Bridge report |author=Raab, N.C. |date=1953 |publisher=Division of San Francisco Bay Toll Crossings |accessdate=July 12, 2016}}\n* {{cite report |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/002026761 |title=A preliminary report to Department of Public Works on a San Francisco-Tiburon crossing of San Francisco Bay |author=Raab, N.C. |date=1953 |publisher=Division of San Francisco Bay Toll Crossings |accessdate=July 12, 2016}}\n\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure        = Crossings\n|place            = [[San Francisco Bay]]\n|bridge           = Richmond\u2013San Rafael Bridge\n|bridge signs     = [[Image:I-580 (CA).svg|24px|Interstate 580]]\n|upstream text    = North\n|upstream         = [[Carquinez Bridge]]\n|upstream signs   = [[Image:I-80 (CA).svg|20px|Interstate 80]]\n|downstream text  = South\n|downstream       = [[Golden Gate Bridge]]\n|downstream signs = [[Image:US 101 (CA).svg|23px|U.S. Route 101]] [[Image:California 1.svg|20px|State Route 1]]\n}}\n\n{{Richmond, California}}\n{{San Francisco Bay watershed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richmond-San Rafael Bridge}}\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1956]]\n[[Category:Bridges in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Richmond, California]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Bay]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in California]]\n[[Category:Tolled sections of Interstate Highways]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Contra Costa County, California]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Marin County, California]]\n[[Category:Double-decker bridges]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in California]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in San Rafael, California]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the Interstate Highway System]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Bay Trail]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cantilever bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Pratt truss bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Trestle bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:1956 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": ". -> ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richmond%E2%80%93San_Rafael_Bridge"}
{"title_page": "Fiona Apple", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer-songwriter}}\n{{citation style | reason = many citations are incomplete, and style of presentation is inconsistent|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Fiona Apple\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Fiona Apple by Sachyn Mital (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Apple performing in New York City, 2015\n| birth_name = Fiona Apple MacAfee-Maggart\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|9|13|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| parents = Brandon Maggart, Diane Macafee\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Art pop]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-idler-wheel-20120619 |title=The Idler Wheel... |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=April 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/chi-fiona-apple-album-review-the-idler-wheel-reviewed-20120618-column.html|title=Album review: Fiona Apple, 'The Idler Wheel ...'|work=Chicago Tribune|date=June 18, 2012|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/entertainment/article305770/Fiona-Apple-performs-at-the-Midland.html|title=Fiona Apple performs at the Midland|work=[[The Kansas City Star]]|date=July 17, 2012|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref>\n<!--Aim for generality and use two to four genres: [[Template:Infobox musical artist/doc#genre]]-->\n*[[baroque pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://exclaim.ca/amparticle/fiona_apple-anything_we_want_every_single_nightlive_at_sxsw|title= \"Anything We Want\" / \"Every Single Night\" (live at SXSW)|publisher= Exclaim|accessdate= 10 October 2019}}</ref>}}\n| occupation = Singer-songwriter\n| instrument = {{hlist| Vocals| piano}}<!-- only those primarily known for using, per [[Template:Infobox musical artist/doc#instrument]]-->\n| years_active = 1994\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n*[[Epic Records|Epic]]\n*[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n*Clean Slate\n}}\n| website = {{url|fiona-apple.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Fiona Apple McAfee-Maggart''' (born September 13, 1977) is an American singer-songwriter and pianist. [[List of awards and nominations received by Fiona Apple|Her accolades]] include one [[Grammy Award for Best Female Rock Vocal Performance|Grammy Award]], and an additional seven Grammy Award nominations in various categories.\n\nThe daughter of actor [[Brandon Maggart]], Apple was born in [[New York City]] but was raised alternating between New York and her father's home in [[Los Angeles]]. Classically trained on piano as a child, she began composing her own songs when she was eight years old. Her debut album, ''[[Tidal (album)|Tidal]]'', containing songs written when Apple was 17, was released in 1996 and received a Grammy Award for Best Female Vocal Rock Performance for the single \"[[Criminal (Fiona Apple song)|Criminal]]\". She followed with ''[[When the Pawn...]]'' (1999), produced by [[Jon Brion]], which was also critically and commercially successful and was certified platinum.\n\nFor her third album, ''[[Extraordinary Machine]]'' (2005), Apple again collaborated with Brion, and began recording the album in 2002. However, Apple was reportedly unhappy with the production and opted not to release the record, leading fans to protest [[Epic Records]], erroneously believing that the label was withholding its release. The album was eventually re-produced without Brion and released in October 2005. The album was certified [[Gold album|gold]], and nominated for a [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album]]. In 2012, she released her fourth studio album, ''[[The Idler Wheel...]]'', which received critical praise and was followed by a tour of the United States and was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album]] in 2013. Apple's upcoming fifth studio album, ''[[Fetch the Bolt Cutters]]'', is scheduled to be released on April 17th, 2020.\n\nShe has sold over 10 million albums worldwide and has received numerous [[List of awards and nominations received by Fiona Apple|awards and nominations]], including a [[Grammy Award]], 2 [[MTV Video Music Awards]] and a [[Billboard Music Award]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in 1977 and raised on the [[Upper West Side]] of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], Apple is the daughter of singer Diane McAfee and actor [[Brandon Maggart]], who met when both were cast in the Broadway musical ''[[Applause (musical)|Applause]]''.<ref><!--?REPEAT1?-->{{cite news|url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/06/hiding-out-with-fiona-apple-musical-hermit.html|title=\u2018I Just Want to Feel Everything\u2019: Hiding Out With Fiona Apple, Musical Hermit|date=June 17, 2012|accessdate=March 1, 2016|work=Vulture}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/05/arts/a-message-far-less-pretty-than-the-face.html | title=A Message Far Less Pretty Than the Face | last=Ehrlich | first=Dimitri | work=The New York Times | date=January 5, 1997}}</ref> Her father is from [[Tennessee]], and through him, Apple has [[Melungeon]] ancestry.<ref name=wtf /> Her maternal grandparents were dancer Millicent Green and [[big band]] vocalist Johnny McAfee. Her sister, Amber, sings [[cabaret]] under the stage name [[Maude Maggart]], and actor [[Garett Maggart]] is her half brother. Apple grew up in [[Morningside Gardens]] in [[Harlem]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2QKeg6Q9KAwC&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=fiona+apple+harlem&source=bl&ots=qnhyAgUpOm&sig=oa3VgQoIMkV5BAXByAUyp1X2gWU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CEsQ6AEwB2oVChMIlpOLu-nvxwIVRT0-Ch1yewKM#v=onepage&q=fiona%20apple%20harlem&f=false|title=Harlem Travel Guide|last=Johnson|first=Carolyn D.|page=94}}</ref> with her mother and sister, but spent summers with her father in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref name=\"notable\" />\n\nApple was classically trained on piano as a child, and began composing her own pieces by the age of eight.<ref name=\"notable\">{{cite web|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2006-A-Ec/Apple-Fiona.html|website=Notable Biographies|title=Fiona Apple|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref> When learning to play piano, she would often take sheet music and translate [[guitar tablature]] into the corresponding notes.<ref name=\"notable\" /> Apple later began to play along with [[jazz standard]] compositions after becoming proficient, through which she discovered [[Billie Holiday]] and [[Ella Fitzgerald]], who became major influences on her.<ref>{{Cite news|work=Tribeca 75|title=Fiona Apple|date=1996|author=Bevilacqua, Rachele|url=http://www.neverisapromise.com/interviews/Tribeca.html|series=Interviews}}</ref>\n\nAt age 12, Apple was raped outside the apartment she shared with her mother, step-father and sister in Harlem.<ref name=Heath>{{cite magazine|first=Chris|last=Heath |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/fiona-the-caged-bird-sings-244221/ |title=Fiona: The Caged Bird Sings|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=22 January 1998|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> She then developed an [[eating disorder]], purposely slimming her developing body, which she saw as \"bait\". After the incident, she spent hours at a Model Mugging class, practicing self-defense by punching a man in a padded suit.<ref name=radical/> After the incident, Apple also suffered [[panic attack]]s while walking home from school, which led to her relocating to Los Angeles to live with her father for one year.<ref name=wtf /> In an interview in 2000, she stated that she did not write songs about this trauma: \"It doesn't get into the writing. It's a boring pain. It's such a fuckin' old pain that, you know, there's nothing ''poetic'' about it.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Phil|last=Sutcliffe|title=Hard Core Pawn|magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|location=London, England|date=March 2000|pages=46\u201348}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1994\u20132001: ''Tidal'' and ''When the Pawn...''===\nApple was introduced to the music industry in 1994, when she gave a demo tape containing the songs \"[[Never Is a Promise#Track listing|Never Is a Promise]]\", \"Not One of Those Times\", and \"He Takes a Taxi\" to her friend who was the babysitter for music publicist Kathryn Schenker.<ref name=\"nyrock\">{{cite news|last=Luck|first=Otto|url=http://www.nyrock.com/fiona.htm|title=Fiona Apple Suffers for Her Sins (and So Do We)|work=NY Rock|date=November 1997|accessdate=September 23, 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716180856/http://www.nyrock.com/fiona.htm|archivedate=July 16, 2012}}</ref> Schenker then passed the tape along to [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music]] executive Andy Slater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imagesjournal.com/issue05/features/fiona.htm |title=Images \u2013 Fiona Apple |website=Imagesjournal.com |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref> Apple's abilities captured his attention, and Slater signed her to a record deal.<ref name=\"New Yorker\">[http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2005/10/10/051010crmu_music New Yorker] Apple's robust contralto, though sometimes heavy on vibrato, gave her line readings a pleasingly sinister feel.</ref><ref name=\"San Diego Arts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.com/arts/fiona-apple-with-david-garza-and-damien-rice |website=San Diego Arts|title=Fiona Apple with David Garza and Damien Rice}} Though most of her lyrics are sung in a straightforward pop contralto, she judiciously adds vibrato, sudden jumps into her head voice, and rapid reiterations of the same pitch (what academics in the classical music field call a \"Monteverdi vibrato\").</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Apple's debut album, ''[[Tidal (album)|Tidal]]'', was released by [[Work Records]] and [[Columbia Records]]. The album sold 2.7 million copies and was certified three times [[platinum album|platinum]] in the U.S.<ref name=RIAA>\"[https://www.riaa.com/gp/database/default.asp Gold and Platinum Searchable Database]\" {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070228071417/http://www.riaa.com/gp/database/default.asp |date=February 28, 2007}}. [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].com.</ref><ref name=AP-MSNBC>{{cite news|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/loyal-fans-helped-free-fiona-apple-s-cd-wbna9601227 |title=Loyal fans helped free Fiona Apple's CD|agency= [[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Today.com]] Entertainment|date= October 5, 2005}}</ref> \"[[Criminal (Fiona Apple song)|Criminal]]\", the third single, became a hit and the song reached the [[Top 40]] on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The song's controversial [[Mark Romanek]]-directed music video played on [[MTV]].<ref name=\"Spin Magazine\">''Spin'', October 1997.</ref> Other singles from ''Tidal'' included \"[[Shadowboxer (song)|Shadowboxer]]\", \"[[Sleep to Dream]]\", and \"Never Is a Promise\". Apple accepted the [[MTV Video Music Award for Best New Artist]] at the [[1997 MTV Video Music Awards]] for her song \"Sleep to Dream\", during her acceptance speech she said:\n\n{{quote|This world is bullshit. And you shouldn't model your life\u2014wait a second\u2014you shouldn't model your life about what you think that we think is cool and what we're wearing and what we're saying and everything. Go with yourself.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jason|last=Bailey|url=http://flavorwire.com/609617/this-world-is-bullshit-on-the-20th-anniversary-of-fiona-apples-memorable-vma-moment|title='This World is Bullshit': On the 20th Anniversary of Fiona Apple\u2019s Memorable VMA Moment|website=Flavorwire|publisher=Flavorpill Media|location=New York City|date=December 28, 2017|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\n''[[The New Yorker]]'' and ''NYRock'' criticized her MTV award show speech.<ref name=\"nyrock\" /><ref name=\"New Yorker\" /> \"When I have something to say, I'll say it,\" she said, responding to these criticisms in an article in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in January 1998.<ref name=Heath /> During this period, Apple also [[cover version|covered]] [[the Beatles]]' \"[[Across the Universe]]\" and [[Percy Mayfield]]'s \"[[Please Send Me Someone to Love]]\" for the soundtrack of the film ''[[Pleasantville (film)|Pleasantville]]''. She later canceled the last 21 dates on a tour in support of her album due to \"personal family problems\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1424968/fiona-apple-cancels-tour.jhtml |title=News \u2013 Articles \u2013 1424968 |website=MTV |date=March 3, 1998 |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nApple's second album, ''[[When the Pawn...]]'', was released in 1999. Its full title is a poem Apple wrote after reading letters that appeared in ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' regarding an article that had cast her in a negative light in an earlier issue.<ref name=\"Harrington\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPcap/1999-11/28/003r-112899-idx.html |title=Fiona Apple: The Time Is Ripe |last=Harrington |first=Richard |date=November 28, 1999 |work=The Washington Post |page=G1|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> The title's length earned it a spot in the ''[[Guinness Book of Records]]'' for 2001. However, as of October 2007, it no longer has the longest album title, as [[Soulwax]] released ''[[Most of the Remixes]]'', a [[remix]] album whose title surpasses ''When the Pawn''<nowiki />'s length by 100 characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevinenjoyce.com/soulwax/ |title=soulwax.info |website=Kevinenjoyce.com |accessdate=February 12, 2013}}</ref> ''When the Pawn'' was cultivated during Apple's relationship with film director [[Paul Thomas Anderson]]. ''When the Pawn,'' which was produced by [[Jon Brion]], used more expressive lyrics, experimented more with [[Music loop|drum loops]], and incorporated both the [[Chamberlin]] and [[Matt Chamberlain|drummer Matt Chamberlain]].<ref>{{cite news |work = Seattle Weekly |title = Matt Chamberlain Talk About Recording With Apple |url = http://blogs.seattleweekly.com/reverb/2008/09/matt_chamberlain_drummer_for_t.php/1 |accessdate = September 17, 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131213072758/http://blogs.seattleweekly.com/reverb/2008/09/matt_chamberlain_drummer_for_t.php/1 |archivedate = December 13, 2013 |df = mdy-all}}</ref> The album received a positive reception from publications such as ''[[The New York Times]]''{{cn|date=March 2020}} and ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Sheffield|first=Rob |title=When the Pawn Hits the Conflicts He Thinks Like a King\u2026|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/when-the-pawn-hits-the-conflicts-he-thinks-like-a-king-244877/|date=25 November 1999|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> It did not fare as well commercially as her debut, though it was an [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]-certified [[Music recording sales certification|platinum album]]<ref name=RIAA /> and sold one million copies in the U.S.<ref name=AP-MSNBC /> The album's lead single, \"[[Fast as You Can]]\", reached the top twenty on ''Billboard'''s [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] chart and became Apple's first Top 40 hit in the UK. The videos for two follow-up singles, \"[[Paper Bag (song)|Paper Bag]]\" and \"[[Limp (Song)|Limp]]\" (directed by then-boyfriend Anderson), received very little play.\n\nIn an infamous February 2000 'meltdown', after performing for forty minutes in a set hampered by equipment issues to 3,000 audience members at the New York City [[Roseland Ballroom]], a frustrated Apple left the stage without returning. Her performance saw Apple appearing distraught at the sound quality, apologizing numerous times for the sound and crying.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.music-slam.com/music-slam-concert-review-fiona-apple-roseland-ballroom-02292000/|title=Music-Slam Concert Review\u2014Fiona Apple @ Roseland Ballroom (02.29.2000) |website=Music-slam.com |date=June 30, 2005 |accessdate=March 22, 2015}}</ref> After completing a [[concert tour]] in support of her second album in 2000, Apple relocated to Los Angeles.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n===2002\u20132010: ''Extraordinary Machine'' ===\nDuring her hiatus, Apple contemplated retiring from her recording career. Apple sang with [[Johnny Cash]] on a cover of [[Simon & Garfunkel]]'s \"[[Bridge over Troubled Water (song)|Bridge over Troubled Water]]\" that ended up on his album ''[[American IV: The Man Comes Around]]'' and was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for \"[[Best Country Collaboration with Vocals]]\". She also collaborated with Cash on [[Cat Stevens]]'s \"[[Father and Son (song)|Father and Son]]\", which was included in his 2003 collection ''[[Unearthed (Johnny Cash album)|Unearthed]]''.\n\n[[File:Free Fiona protest outside Sony BMG headquarters in NYC 28-01-2005.jpg|left|thumb|upright=.9|Fans in support of Fiona Apple demonstrating outside the [[New York City|NYC]] headquarters of [[Sony BMG Music Entertainment]] in January 2005.]]\n\nApple's third album, ''[[Extraordinary Machine]]'', was originally produced by [[Jon Brion]]. In spring 2002, Apple and Brion, her longtime friend and producer on ''When the Pawn,'' met for their weekly lunch meeting. Brion reportedly \"begged\" Apple to make another album. Apple agreed, and Brion went to Apple's label, [[Epic Records]], with strict stipulations (including no deadline), which the label eventually agreed to. Recording sessions began in 2002, at [[Ocean Way studios]] in Nashville, Tennessee, but later moved to the [[Paramour Mansion]] in Los Angeles. Work on the album continued until 2003, and in May of that year it was submitted to Sony executives. In 2004 and 2005, tracks were leaked on the Internet in MP3 format and played on U.S. and international radio. Subsequently, MP3s of the entire album went online. Although a Web site distributing the album was quickly shut down, it soon reached [[peer-to-peer|P2P]] networks and was downloaded by fans.<ref name=\"spin\" /> A fan-led campaign supported the album's official release.\n\n[[Mike Elizondo]], who had previously played bass on ''Pawn'', was brought back as co-producer to complete the tracks he had begun with Brion and Apple. ''Spin'' later reported the following: \"Fans erroneously thought that Apple's record label, [[Epic Records|Epic]], had rejected the first version of ''Extraordinary Machine''...&nbsp;in reality, according to Elizondo, Apple was unhappy with the results, and it was her decision to redo the record, not her label's.\"<ref name=\"spin\" /> In August 2005, the album was given an October release date.<ref name=\"spin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/features/news/2005/08/050815_fiona_apple/ |title=Fiona Apple's ''Machine'' Finally Turned On|website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date= August 15, 2005|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref> Production had been largely redone \"from scratch\" by Elizondo and was co-produced by [[Brian Kehew]]. Two of the 11 previous leaked tracks were relatively unchanged, and one new song was also included.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/15/arts/music/15appl.html |work=The New York Times|title=Fiona Apple Retools Her Leaked Album|accessdate= August 15, 2005}}</ref> Despite suggestions that the album had caused a rift between Brion and Apple, they regularly perform together at [[Largo (nightclub)|Largo]], a club in Los Angeles, including a joint appearance with Elizondo on bass just before the news broke of an official release.<ref name=Elizondo>{{cite web|title=Music: Fiona Apple|url=http://www.studentsoftheworld.info/sites/music/7104.php|website=studentsoftheworld.info|accessdate=August 25, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927143738/http://www.studentsoftheworld.info/sites/music/7104.php|archivedate=September 27, 2011}}</ref> ''Extraordinary Machine'' debuted at number seven and was nominated for a Grammy Award for \"[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]]\". It was eventually certified [[gold album|gold]],<ref name=RIAA /> though its singles (\"[[Parting Gift]]\", \"[[O' Sailor]]\", \"[[Not About Love]]\", and \"[[Get Him Back]]\") failed to enter any ''Billboard'' charts.<ref name=Billboard-Apr2006>{{cite news|author=Cohen, Jonathan|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/58703/fiona-taps-rice-garza-for-summer-trek |title=Fiona Taps Rice, Garza For Summer Trek|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date= April 19, 2006}}</ref> Apple went on a live tour to promote the album in late 2005.\n\n[[File:Fiona-Apple.jpg|thumb|upright=.9|Apple performing in [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]], 2006]]\nIn June 2006, Apple appeared on the joke track \"Come Over and Get It (Up in 'Dem Guts)\" by comedian [[Zach Galifianakis]]. Galifianakis previously appeared in the music video for Apple's \"Not About Love\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stereogum.com/22421/new_zach_galifianakis_fiona_apple_up_in_them_guts/mp3s/ |last1=Galifianakis|first1=Zach|last2=Apple|first2=Fiona|title=Up In Them Guts|website=Stereogum.com|accessdate= June 8, 2011}}</ref> Apple recorded a cover of \"Sally's Song\" for the 2006 special edition release of the soundtrack for the [[Tim Burton]] film ''[[The Nightmare Before Christmas]]''. In May 2006, Apple paid tribute to [[Elvis Costello]] on [[VH1]]'s concert series ''[[Decades Rock Live]],'' by performing Costello's hit \"I Want You\". Her version was subsequently released as a digital single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EiOmhOumh-w |title=Decades Rock Live |website=YouTube.com |accessdate=April 12, 2014}}</ref> Apple toured the East Coast during August 2007, with [[Nickel Creek]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Hasty, Kate|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1052031/apple-nickel-creek-teaming-for-tour |title=Apple, Nickel Creek Teaming For Tour|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date= May 18, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Madison, Tjames|url=http://www.livedaily.com/news/12126.html|title=Fiona Apple joins Nickel Creek's 'farewell' tour|work=[[LiveDaily]]|date=May 17, 2007|accessdate=March 2, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410022102/http://www.livedaily.com/news/12126.html|archivedate=April 10, 2008}}</ref> In 2008, Apple recorded a duet titled \"Still I\" with Christophe Deluy. In 2009, Apple covered \"Why Try to Change Me Now\" and \"I Walk A Little Faster\" for ''The Best Is Yet to Come \u2013 The Songs of [[Cy Coleman]]''.\n\nIn January 2010, Fiona Apple and [[Jon Brion]] performed together at \"Love and Haiti, Too: A Music Benefit\", a charity concert for the people hurt by the [[Haiti earthquake]]. Fiona sang a cover of \"(S)he's Funny That Way\", composed by Neil Moret, lyrics by Richard Whiting, which is often associated with the singer [[Billie Holiday]]. In June 2010, Fiona released a song titled \"So Sleepy\", produced by [[Jon Brion]] and written by children involved with the non-profit organization [[826LA]]. The song was included on a compilation album released by the organization titled ''[[Chickens in Love]]''. Apple collaborated with [[Margaret Cho]] on her album ''[[Cho Dependent]]'', which was released on August 24, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Maerz |first=Melissa |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/06/07/margaret-cho-album-murder-ballad/ |title=Margaret Cho's Murder Ballad |website=Popwatch.ew.com |date=June 7, 2010 |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132018: ''The Idler Wheel...''===\n[[File:Fiona Apple 2012 NYC T5.jpg|thumb|upright=.9|left|Apple performing at [[Terminal 5 (venue)|Terminal 5]], New York, 2012]]\n\nIn late 2010, ''Billboard'' published an article stating that Apple was planning on releasing a new album in spring 2011, with musician [[Michelle Branch]] claiming to have heard some of the new tracks.<ref name=\"bill\">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/956287/fiona-apple-releasing-new-album-in-spring-2011|work=Billboard|title=Fiona Apple Releasing New Album in Spring 2011|author=Maples, Jillian|date=September 16, 2010|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref> Drummer [[Charley Drayton]] also told ''Modern Drummer'' magazine that he was co-producing the record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/510706/fiona-apple-to-release-new-music-in-the-next-few-weeks-says-la-reid |title=Fiona Apple To Release New Music 'In The Next Few Weeks,' says L.A. Reid |website=Billboard.com |date=September 14, 2009 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> However, the album was not released in the spring and ''Billboard'' reported later that Epic was not aware of a record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/469132/11-anticipated-album-updates-madonna-dmx-nickelback-and-more |title=11 Anticipated Album Updates: Madonna, DMX, Nickelback And More |website=Billboard |date=September 14, 2009 |accessdate=May 1, 2012}}</ref> Apple delayed the album's release until 2012, explaining that she was waiting \"until her label found a new president and that she didn't want her work to be mishandled amid corporate disarray.\"<ref name=\"NYTimes1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/03/arts/music/fiona-apples-new-album-the-idler-wheel.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all |title=Fiona Apple Faces Outward |first=Jon |last=Pareles |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 30, 2012 |accessdate=June 3, 2012}}</ref> In January 2012, after its new record label head, [[LA Reid]] hinted at new music from Apple, Epic Records announced that the album would be released later in the year.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://entertainment.time.com/2012/01/24/fiona-apple-has-new-music-coming-out-but-not-in-the-next-few-weeks/|title=Release date for new album | work=Time| accessdate=January 24, 2012| date=January 24, 2012}}</ref> Apple announced performances at the [[South by Southwest]] Festival and [[The Idler Wheel Tour|a spring 2012 tour]] soon after.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2012/02/21/fiona-apple-tour-dates-2012-sxsw/ |title=Concert dates including South by Southwest Festival| work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | date=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Idler Wheel...|The Idler Wheel Is Wiser Than the Driver of the Screw and Whipping Cords Will Serve You More Than Ropes Will Ever Do]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Perpetua, Matthew |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/fiona-apple-unveils-23-word-album-title-20120307 |title=Fiona Apple Unveils 23-Word Album Title &#124; Music News |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=March 7, 2012 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"pitchfork.com\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/45671-fiona-apple-reveals-album-title/ |title=Fiona Apple Reveals Album Title &#124; News |website=Pitchfork |date=March 7, 2012 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> Apple's fourth studio album, was released on June 19, 2012, in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiona-apple.com |title=Welcome &#124; The Official Fiona Apple site |website=Fiona-apple.com |accessdate=May 1, 2012}}</ref> It received critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-idler-wheel-is-wiser-than-the-driver-of-the-screw-and-whipping-cords-will-serve-you-more-than-ro |title=The Idler Wheel Is Wiser than the Driver of the Screw and Whipping Cords Will Serve You More than Ropes Will Ever Do \u2013 Fiona Apple |website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher= [[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref> According to an article in ''[[American Songwriter]]'' \"''The Idler Wheel'' isn't always pretty, but it pulses with life, brutal and true.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2012/06/fiona-apple-the-idler-wheel/ |title=Fiona Apple: The Idler Wheel... |website=[[American Songwriter]] |accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Fiona Apple 2012.png|thumb|Apple performing in Miami Beach, 2012]]\n\nApple contributed a previously unreleased song entitled \"[[Dull Tool]]\" to the soundtrack of the 2012 [[Judd Apatow]] film ''[[This Is 40]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/listen-fiona-apples-dull-tool-from-the-this-is-40-soundtrack-paul-rudd-hearts-ween-in-new-poster-20121117 |title=Listen: Fiona Apple's \"Dull Tool\" From The 'This Is 40' Soundtrack; Paul Rudd Hearts Ween In New Poster |website=[[IndieWire]] |first=Edward |last=Davis |date=November 17, 2012 |accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref> Another song recorded for the film that was not included in the soundtrack has yet to be released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/9011-judd-apatow/|title=Judd Apatow|website=Pitchfork}}</ref> In September 2013, a [[Chipotle Mexican Grill|Chipotle]] ad appeared online with a soundtrack of Apple covering \"[[Pure Imagination]]\" from the 1971 film ''[[Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory]]''. The video, which follows a scarecrow as he discovers the truth about [[factory farming]] and processed food, was described as \"haunted,\" \"dystopian,\" \"bizarre,\" and \"beautiful.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/pop/Watch-Fiona-Apple-Chipotle-Partner-Bizarre-Beautiful-Pure-Imagination-Cover-59072.html |title=Watch: Fiona Apple And Chipotle Partner For Bizarre And Beautiful Pure Imagination Cover|website=CinemaBlend}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/52274-watch-fiona-apple-covers-pure-imagination-from-willy-wonka-for-chipotle-ad-on-factory-farming/|title=Watch: Fiona Apple Covers \"Pure Imagination\" From Willy Wonka for Chipotle Ad on Factory Farming |website= Pitchfork}}</ref>\nIn 2014, Apple wrote the opening theme, \"[[Container (song)|Container]]\", for the Showtime drama series ''[[The Affair (TV series)|The Affair]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title='The Affair' opening credits feature new Fiona Apple song: Listen|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/10/02/fiona-apple-affair-credits/|accessdate=December 20, 2014|website=EW}}</ref> During 2014, Apple also appeared at a number of performances by [[Blake Mills]], including in New York City and Cambridge, MA, during his tour in support of his second full-length album, ''Heigh Ho''. The pair first publicly collaborated on an acoustic version of Apple's song \"I Know\" in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=I Know, Apple and Mills|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rza0XycpyA8|accessdate=April 5, 2015|website=YouTube}}</ref> Fiona Apple has collaborated with [[Andrew Bird]], and in 2016, she was featured in the song \"Left Handed Kisses\" from the album ''[[Are You Serious (Andrew Bird album)|Are You Serious]]''.\n\nIn 2017, she released \"[[Tiny Hands]]\" for the [[2017 Women's March|Women's March on Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Bromwich, Jonah|title=Fiona Apple Releases a Trump Protest Chant|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/18/arts/music/fiona-apple-tiny-hands-womens-march.html|work=The New York Times|date=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she joined [[Shirley Manson]] at the female-driven Girl School Festival in Los Angeles for a cover of \"[[You Don't Own Me]]\" by [[Lesley Gore]], wearing a white T-shirt with \"KNEEL, PORTNOW\" written across it in ink. This was considered in response to Grammy head [[Neil Portnow]]'s heavily criticized comments that women need to \"step up\" in order to earn more Grammy nods.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ortega, Mark|title=WATCH: Shirley Manson and Fiona Apple cover \"You Don't Own Me\"|url=http://www.passtheaux.co/girl-school-2018-shirley-manson-fiona-apple/|work=Pass The Aux|date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters''===\nIn January 2019, Apple collaborated with [[King Princess]] on a version of her 1999 song \"I Know\". The song was released for Spotify's RISE program on January 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/01/25/688618778/king-princess-and-fiona-apple-collaborate-on-new-version-of-i-know|title=King Princess And Fiona Apple Collaborate On New Version Of 'I Know'|website=NPR.org}}</ref> Apple was featured in the documentary and [[Echo in the Canyon (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] for [[Echo in the Canyon]] with [[Jakob Dylan]] covering songs by artists such as [[the Beach Boys]] and [[the Byrds]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/fiona-apple-jakob-dylan-beach-boys-in-my-room-839505/|title=Hear Fiona Apple, Jakob Dylan Cover the Beach Boys' 'In My Room'|first=Claire|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Shaffer|date=May 24, 2019}}</ref> In November, she covered \"Whole of the Moon,\" a [[The Waterboys|Waterboys]] song, for the series finale of [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s ''[[The Affair (TV series)|The Affair]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/fiona-apple-waterboys-whole-of-the-moon-cover-907809/|title=Hear Fiona Apple's Full-Throated Cover of the Waterboys' 'The Whole of the Moon'|first1=Jon|last1=Blistein|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=November 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/fiona-apple-covers-the-waterboys%E2%80%99-%E2%80%9Cthe-whole-of-the-moon%E2%80%9D-listen/ar-AAJQ1bU|title=Fiona Apple Covers the Waterboys\u2019 \u201cThe Whole of the Moon\u201d: Listen|website=Msn.com}}</ref>\n\nIn two Instagram posts in March 2019, Apple hinted at the recording of a fifth album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-fiona-apple-tease-and-record-new-music-at-home-studio/|title=Watch Fiona Apple Tease and Record New Music at Home Studio|website=pitchfork.com}}</ref> In a September 2019 interview with Vulture, she confirmed that the album was in its final stages, recorded with a band and planned for an early 2020 release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/fiona-apple-is-still-calling-bullshit.html|title=Fiona Apple Is Still Calling Bullshit|website=vulture.com}}</ref> In a follow-up interview with Vulture in January 2020, she said her new album would probably be out \"in a few months.\"<ref name=\"vulture\">{{cite news |last1=Handler |first1=Rachel |title=15 Minutes With Fiona Apple |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-updates.html |accessdate=24 January 2020 |publisher=Vulture |date=22 January 2020}}</ref> On March 8, 2020, Apple posted a video showcasing her saying \"M-Y-R-E-C-O-R-D-I-S-D-O-N-E\" in [[American Sign Language]].<ref name=radical>\n{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/03/23/fiona-apples-art-of-radical-sensitivity |title=Fiona Apple's Art of Radical Sensitivity|date=16 March 2020 |work=The New Yorker}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[The New Yorker]]'' it was announced the new album will be called ''[[Fetch the Bolt Cutters]]''. Apple later announced that the album would be released on April 17, 2020. The album is entirely self-produced and consists of 13 songs.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u3yH33epGJY |title=Fiona Apple \u2013 5 |date=16 March 2020 |website=newyorker.com|publisher=Fiona Apple Rocks}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xERU-0nrGHE |title=Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters |date=1 April 2020 |website=youtube.com|publisher=Fiona Apple Rocks}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n{{expert needed | Biography | section = yes | reason = the section is a dumping ground of out-of-date content, with no rhyme or reason in its ordering | date = March 2020}}\nApple is a [[vegan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/music/fiona-apple-interview|title=Fiona Apple: Interview|magazine=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|first=John|last=Lewis|date=April 4, 2006|accessdate=June 17, 2016}}</ref> During an in-depth interview on [[Marc Maron]]'s [[WTF with Marc Maron|''WTF'' podcast]] she revealed that she has battled [[obsessive\u2013compulsive disorder]] throughout her adult life and had recently decided to quit drinking.<ref name=wtf>{{cite podcast |host=Marc Maron |work=[[WTF with Marc Maron]]| |url=http://www.wtfpod.com/podcast/episodes/episode_297_-_fiona_apple|title=Episode 297|date=July 16, 2012|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref> She has also gone on record about struggling with [[clinical depression|depression]], [[self-harm]], [[post-traumatic stress]] and trust issues with men, particularly in the wake of her rape.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/fiona-the-caged-bird-sings-244221/|title=Fiona: The Caged Bird Sings|last=Heath|first=Chris|date=January 22, 1998|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=August 3, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe fallout from Apple's breakup with her first serious boyfriend, Tyson, was the basis for her first album, ''[[Tidal (album)|Tidal]].'' According to a 1998 profile in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', the two of them managed to stay on good terms.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\"/> In the late 1990s, she was linked with [[illusionist]] and [[endurance artist]] [[David Blaine]], followed by writer/director [[Paul Thomas Anderson]] during the 2000s and writer/TV creator [[Jonathan Ames]] in the mid to late 2000s.<ref>{{Cite journal|author = Hopper, Jessica | date=April 24, 2012 | title=Fiona Apple's Bad, Bad Girl Moments|journal=Rolling Stone| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/fiona-apples-bad-bad-girl-moments-22292/|access-date=August 3, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/06/fiona-apple-is-not-insane/258660/|title=Fiona Apple Is Not Insane|last=Kornhaber|first=Spencer|date=June 19, 2012|work=The Atlantic|access-date=August 3, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Bustle|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/2603-fiona-apple-paul-thomas-anderson-reunite-to-make-a-simple-yet-stunning-new-music-video|title=Fiona Apple & Paul Thomas Anderson Reunite to Make a Simple Yet Stunning New Music Video|author=Semigran, Aly|date=July 25, 2013|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref> She has admitted she maintains friendships with all of her ex-boyfriends, noting \"I really care about them. I care about their lives with their girlfriends. I feel like maybe an annoying mother or something.\"<ref>{{Cite web|first=John|last=Norris|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/fiona-apple-idling-no-more/|title=Fiona Apple: Idling No More|magazine=[[V (American magazine)|V]]|publisher=[[Visionaire]]|location=New York City|date=June 26, 2012|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=Craig|last=McLean|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/jan/29/popandrock.fionaapple|title=Craig McLean profiles Fiona Apple, best-selling artist|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|language=en|date=January 29, 2006|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> In a June 2012 interview, she revealed she had briefly married a French photographer \"for complicated reasons\" and had a passing liaison with a younger woman.<ref name=Lee><!--?REPEAT2?-->{{cite web|first=Dan P.|last=Lee|url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/06/hiding-out-with-fiona-apple-musical-hermit.html|title='I Just Want to Feel Everything\u2019: Hiding Out With Fiona Apple, Musical Hermit|website=[[vulture.com|Vulture]]|publisher=[[New York Media]]|location=New York City|date=June 17, 2012|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 19, 2012, Apple was arrested at an [[United States Border Patrol Interior Checkpoints|internal U.S. Border Patrol checkpoint]] in [[Sierra Blanca, Texas]], and charged with possession of [[hashish]], detaining her en route to a concert in [[Austin, Texas]], at the [[Hudspeth County, Texas|Hudspeth County]] Jail.<ref name=\"NYMN September 2012\">{{cite web | author = McDougan, Farfel | date = September 20, 2012 | title = Fiona Apple Arrested | work = New York Music News | url = http://nymn.com/fiona-apple-arrested-new-york-music-news/ | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120923150232/http://nymn.com/fiona-apple-arrested-new-york-music-news/ | archive-date = September 23, 2012 | accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TMZ September 2012\">{{cite web | title=Fiona Apple Arrested for Hash in Texas |url=http://www.tmz.com/2012/09/20/fiona-apple-arrested-drugs-weed-hash-texas-hashish/ |work=TMZ.com |date=September 20, 2012 |accessdate=September 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Apple wrote a letter to her fans \u2013 a scan of which was posted to her website and her [[Facebook]] page \u2013 postponing the South American leg of her tour due to the health of her dog, Janet. According to the letter, the dog has [[Addison's disease]] and has had a tumor \"idling in her chest\" for two years.<ref>{{cite web| author = Apple, Fiona | url=http://www.lettersofnote.com/2012/11/she-is-my-best-friend.html |title=She is my best friend |work=Letters of Note | date=November 21, 2012 |accessdate=February 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 30, 2019, Apple pledged to donate two years' worth of earnings from TV and movie placements of her song \"[[Criminal (Fiona Apple song)|Criminal]]\" to the [[While They Wait]] fund, which assists refugees with basic necessities, immigration fees and legal services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/fiona-apple-criminal-royalties-refugees-854497/|title=Fiona Apple Pledges Two Years of \u2018Criminal\u2019 Royalties to Refugees|last=Reed|first=Ryan|date=July 2, 2019|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref> In 2020, While They Wait's Scott Hechinger revealed to ''Vulture'' that Fiona has donated $90,000, and that donation will help out 15 families.<ref name=\"vulture\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Fiona Apple discography|List of songs recorded by Fiona Apple}}\n* ''[[Tidal (album)|Tidal]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[When the Pawn...]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Extraordinary Machine]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Idler Wheel...]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Fetch the Bolt Cutters]]'' (2020)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Fiona Apple}}\nApple's debut album earned her a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Female Rock Vocal Performance|Best Female Rock Vocal Performance]] for \"Criminal\" and the [[MTV Video Music Award]] for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist in a Video]] for \"Sleep to Dream\". For ''When the Pawn...'', Apple won the California Music Award for Outstanding Female Vocalist. For ''Extraordinary Machine'', she won an Esky Music Award for Best Songbird.\n\n==See also==\n*\"[[Apple of Sodom (song)|Apple of Sodom]]\", a [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]] song inspired by Apple\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Fiona Apple}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n*{{DMOZ|Arts/Music/Bands_and_Artists/A/Apple%2C_Fiona/}}\n* {{IMDb name|4712}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alanis Morissette]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[MTV Video Music Award for Best New Artist]]|years=1997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Natalie Imbruglia]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Fiona Apple}}\n{{Portal bar|1990s|Los Angeles|Music|New York City}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Apple, Fiona}}\n[[Category:Fiona Apple| ]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women pianists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Alexander Hamilton High School (Los Angeles) alumni]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock singers]]\n[[Category:American contraltos]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American pop pianists]]\n[[Category:Art pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Ballad musicians]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Epic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Harlem]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper West Side]]\n[[Category:People with obsessive\u2013compulsive disorder]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer-songwriter}}\n{{citation style | reason = many citations are incomplete, and style of presentation is inconsistent|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Fiona Apple\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Fiona Apple by Sachyn Mital (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Apple performing in New York City, 2015\n| birth_name = Fiona Apple MacAfee-Maggart\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|9|13|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| parents = Brandon Maggart, Diane Macafee\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Art pop]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-idler-wheel-20120619 |title=The Idler Wheel... |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=April 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/chi-fiona-apple-album-review-the-idler-wheel-reviewed-20120618-column.html|title=Album review: Fiona Apple, 'The Idler Wheel ...'|work=Chicago Tribune|date=June 18, 2012|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/entertainment/article305770/Fiona-Apple-performs-at-the-Midland.html|title=Fiona Apple performs at the Midland|work=[[The Kansas City Star]]|date=July 17, 2012|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref>\n<!--Aim for generality and use two to four genres: [[Template:Infobox musical artist/doc#genre]]-->\n*[[baroque pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://exclaim.ca/amparticle/fiona_apple-anything_we_want_every_single_nightlive_at_sxsw|title= \"Anything We Want\" / \"Every Single Night\" (live at SXSW)|publisher= Exclaim|accessdate= 10 October 2019}}</ref>}}\n| occupation = Singer-songwriter\n| instrument = {{hlist| Vocals| piano}}<!-- only those primarily known for using, per [[Template:Infobox musical artist/doc#instrument]]-->\n| years_active = 1994\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n*[[Epic Records|Epic]]\n*[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n*Clean Slate\n}}\n| website = {{url|fiona-apple.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Fiona Apple McAfee-Maggart''' (born September 13, 1977) is an American singer-songwriter and pianist. [[List of awards and nominations received by Fiona Apple|Her accolades]] include one [[Grammy Award for Best Female Rock Vocal Performance|Grammy Award]], and an additional seven Grammy Award nominations in various categories.\n\nThe daughter of actor [[Brandon Maggart]], Apple was born in [[New York City]] but was raised alternating between New York and her father's home in [[Los Angeles]]. Classically trained on piano as a child, she began composing her own songs when she was eight years old. Her debut album, ''[[Tidal (album)|Tidal]]'', containing songs written when Apple was 17, was released in 1996 and received a Grammy Award for Best Female Vocal Rock Performance for the single \"[[Criminal (Fiona Apple song)|Criminal]]\". She followed with ''[[When the Pawn...]]'' (1999), produced by [[Jon Brion]], which was also critically and commercially successful and was certified platinum.\n\nFor her third album, ''[[Extraordinary Machine]]'' (2005), Apple again collaborated with Brion, and began recording the album in 2002. However, Apple was reportedly unhappy with the production and opted not to release the record, leading fans to protest [[Epic Records]], erroneously believing that the label was withholding its release. The album was eventually re-produced without Brion and released in October 2005. The album was certified [[Gold album|gold]], and nominated for a [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album]]. In 2012, she released her fourth studio album, ''[[The Idler Wheel...]]'', which received critical praise and was followed by a tour of the United States and was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album]] in 2013. Apple's upcoming fifth studio album, ''[[Fetch the Bolt Cutters]]'', is scheduled to be released on April 17th, 2020.\n\nShe has sold over 10 million albums worldwide and has received numerous [[List of awards and nominations received by Fiona Apple|awards and nominations]], including a [[Grammy Award]], 2 [[MTV Video Music Awards]] and a [[Billboard Music Award]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in 1977 and raised on the [[Upper West Side]] of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], Apple is the daughter of singer Diane McAfee and actor [[Brandon Maggart]], who met when both were cast in the Broadway musical ''[[Applause (musical)|Applause]]''.<ref><!--?REPEAT1?-->{{cite news|url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/06/hiding-out-with-fiona-apple-musical-hermit.html|title=\u2018I Just Want to Feel Everything\u2019: Hiding Out With Fiona Apple, Musical Hermit|date=June 17, 2012|accessdate=March 1, 2016|work=Vulture}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/05/arts/a-message-far-less-pretty-than-the-face.html | title=A Message Far Less Pretty Than the Face | last=Ehrlich | first=Dimitri | work=The New York Times | date=January 5, 1997}}</ref> Her father is from [[Tennessee]], and through him, Apple has [[Melungeon]] ancestry.<ref name=wtf /> Her maternal grandparents were dancer Millicent Green and [[big band]] vocalist Johnny McAfee. Her sister, Amber, sings [[cabaret]] under the stage name [[Maude Maggart]], and actor [[Garett Maggart]] is her half brother. Apple grew up in [[Morningside Gardens]] in [[Harlem]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2QKeg6Q9KAwC&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=fiona+apple+harlem&source=bl&ots=qnhyAgUpOm&sig=oa3VgQoIMkV5BAXByAUyp1X2gWU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CEsQ6AEwB2oVChMIlpOLu-nvxwIVRT0-Ch1yewKM#v=onepage&q=fiona%20apple%20harlem&f=false|title=Harlem Travel Guide|last=Johnson|first=Carolyn D.|page=94}}</ref> with her mother and sister, but spent summers with her father in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref name=\"notable\" />\n\nApple was classically trained on piano as a child, and began composing her own pieces by the age of eight.<ref name=\"notable\">{{cite web|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2006-A-Ec/Apple-Fiona.html|website=Notable Biographies|title=Fiona Apple|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref> When learning to play piano, she would often take sheet music and translate [[guitar tablature]] into the corresponding notes.<ref name=\"notable\" /> Apple later began to play along with [[jazz standard]] compositions after becoming proficient, through which she discovered [[Billie Holiday]] and [[Ella Fitzgerald]], who became major influences on her.<ref>{{Cite news|work=Tribeca 75|title=Fiona Apple|date=1996|author=Bevilacqua, Rachele|url=http://www.neverisapromise.com/interviews/Tribeca.html|series=Interviews}}</ref>\n\nAt age 12, Apple was raped outside the apartment she shared with her mother, step-father and sister in Harlem.<ref name=Heath>{{cite magazine|first=Chris|last=Heath |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/fiona-the-caged-bird-sings-244221/ |title=Fiona: The Caged Bird Sings|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=22 January 1998|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> She then developed an [[eating disorder]], purposely slimming her developing body, which she saw as \"bait\". After the incident, she spent hours at a Model Mugging class, practicing self-defense by punching a man in a padded suit.<ref name=radical/> After the incident, Apple also suffered [[panic attack]]s while walking home from school, which led to her relocating to Los Angeles to live with her father for one year.<ref name=wtf /> In an interview in 2000, she stated that she did not write songs about this trauma: \"It doesn't get into the writing. It's a boring pain. It's such a fuckin' old pain that, you know, there's nothing ''poetic'' about it.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Phil|last=Sutcliffe|title=Hard Core Pawn|magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|location=London, England|date=March 2000|pages=46\u201348}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1994\u20132001: ''Tidal'' and ''When the Pawn...''===\nApple was introduced to the music industry in 1994, when she gave a demo tape containing the songs \"[[Never Is a Promise#Track listing|Never Is a Promise]]\", \"Not One of Those Times\", and \"He Takes a Taxi\" to her friend who was the babysitter for music publicist Kathryn Schenker.<ref name=\"nyrock\">{{cite news|last=Luck|first=Otto|url=http://www.nyrock.com/fiona.htm|title=Fiona Apple Suffers for Her Sins (and So Do We)|work=NY Rock|date=November 1997|accessdate=September 23, 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716180856/http://www.nyrock.com/fiona.htm|archivedate=July 16, 2012}}</ref> Schenker then passed the tape along to [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music]] executive Andy Slater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imagesjournal.com/issue05/features/fiona.htm |title=Images \u2013 Fiona Apple |website=Imagesjournal.com |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref> Apple's abilities captured his attention, and Slater signed her to a record deal.<ref name=\"New Yorker\">[http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2005/10/10/051010crmu_music New Yorker] Apple's robust contralto, though sometimes heavy on vibrato, gave her line readings a pleasingly sinister feel.</ref><ref name=\"San Diego Arts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.com/arts/fiona-apple-with-david-garza-and-damien-rice |website=San Diego Arts|title=Fiona Apple with David Garza and Damien Rice}} Though most of her lyrics are sung in a straightforward pop contralto, she judiciously adds vibrato, sudden jumps into her head voice, and rapid reiterations of the same pitch (what academics in the classical music field call a \"Monteverdi vibrato\").</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Apple's debut album, ''[[Tidal (album)|Tidal]]'', was released by [[Work Records]] and [[Columbia Records]]. The album sold 2.7 million copies and was certified three times [[platinum album|platinum]] in the U.S.<ref name=RIAA>\"[https://www.riaa.com/gp/database/default.asp Gold and Platinum Searchable Database]\" {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070228071417/http://www.riaa.com/gp/database/default.asp |date=February 28, 2007}}. [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].com.</ref><ref name=AP-MSNBC>{{cite news|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/loyal-fans-helped-free-fiona-apple-s-cd-wbna9601227 |title=Loyal fans helped free Fiona Apple's CD|agency= [[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Today.com]] Entertainment|date= October 5, 2005}}</ref> \"[[Criminal (Fiona Apple song)|Criminal]]\", the third single, became a hit and the song reached the [[Top 40]] on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The song's controversial [[Mark Romanek]]-directed music video played on [[MTV]].<ref name=\"Spin Magazine\">''Spin'', October 1997.</ref> Other singles from ''Tidal'' included \"[[Shadowboxer (song)|Shadowboxer]]\", \"[[Sleep to Dream]]\", and \"Never Is a Promise\". Apple accepted the [[MTV Video Music Award for Best New Artist]] at the [[1997 MTV Video Music Awards]] for her song \"Sleep to Dream\", during her acceptance speech she said:\n\n{{quote|This world is bullshit. And you shouldn't model your life\u2014wait a second\u2014you shouldn't model your life about what you think that we think is cool and what we're wearing and what we're saying and everything. Go with yourself.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jason|last=Bailey|url=http://flavorwire.com/609617/this-world-is-bullshit-on-the-20th-anniversary-of-fiona-apples-memorable-vma-moment|title='This World is Bullshit': On the 20th Anniversary of Fiona Apple\u2019s Memorable VMA Moment|website=Flavorwire|publisher=Flavorpill Media|location=New York City|date=December 28, 2017|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\n''[[The New Yorker]]'' and ''NYRock'' criticized her MTV award show speech.<ref name=\"nyrock\" /><ref name=\"New Yorker\" /> \"When I have something to say, I'll say it,\" she said, responding to these criticisms in an article in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in January 1998.<ref name=Heath /> During this period, Apple also [[cover version|covered]] [[the Beatles]]' \"[[Across the Universe]]\" and [[Percy Mayfield]]'s \"[[Please Send Me Someone to Love]]\" for the soundtrack of the film ''[[Pleasantville (film)|Pleasantville]]''. She later canceled the last 21 dates on a tour in support of her album due to \"personal family problems\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1424968/fiona-apple-cancels-tour.jhtml |title=News \u2013 Articles \u2013 1424968 |website=MTV |date=March 3, 1998 |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nApple's second album, ''[[When the Pawn...]]'', was released in 1999. Its full title is a poem Apple wrote after reading letters that appeared in ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' regarding an article that had cast her in a negative light in an earlier issue.<ref name=\"Harrington\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPcap/1999-11/28/003r-112899-idx.html |title=Fiona Apple: The Time Is Ripe |last=Harrington |first=Richard |date=November 28, 1999 |work=The Washington Post |page=G1|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> The title's length earned it a spot in the ''[[Guinness Book of Records]]'' for 2001. However, as of October 2007, it no longer has the longest album title, as [[Soulwax]] released ''[[Most of the Remixes]]'', a [[remix]] album whose title surpasses ''When the Pawn''<nowiki />'s length by 100 characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevinenjoyce.com/soulwax/ |title=soulwax.info |website=Kevinenjoyce.com |accessdate=February 12, 2013}}</ref> ''When the Pawn'' was cultivated during Apple's relationship with film director [[Paul Thomas Anderson]]. ''When the Pawn,'' which was produced by [[Jon Brion]], used more expressive lyrics, experimented more with [[Music loop|drum loops]], and incorporated both the [[Chamberlin]] and [[Matt Chamberlain|drummer Matt Chamberlain]].<ref>{{cite news |work = Seattle Weekly |title = Matt Chamberlain Talk About Recording With Apple |url = http://blogs.seattleweekly.com/reverb/2008/09/matt_chamberlain_drummer_for_t.php/1 |accessdate = September 17, 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131213072758/http://blogs.seattleweekly.com/reverb/2008/09/matt_chamberlain_drummer_for_t.php/1 |archivedate = December 13, 2013 |df = mdy-all}}</ref> The album received a positive reception from publications such as ''[[The New York Times]]''{{cn|date=March 2020}} and ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Sheffield|first=Rob |title=When the Pawn Hits the Conflicts He Thinks Like a King\u2026|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/when-the-pawn-hits-the-conflicts-he-thinks-like-a-king-244877/|date=25 November 1999|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> It did not fare as well commercially as her debut, though it was an [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]-certified [[Music recording sales certification|platinum album]]<ref name=RIAA /> and sold one million copies in the U.S.<ref name=AP-MSNBC /> The album's lead single, \"[[Fast as You Can]]\", reached the top twenty on ''Billboard'''s [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] chart and became Apple's first Top 40 hit in the UK. The videos for two follow-up singles, \"[[Paper Bag (song)|Paper Bag]]\" and \"[[Limp (Song)|Limp]]\" (directed by then-boyfriend Anderson), received very little play.\n\nIn an infamous February 2000 'meltdown', after performing for forty minutes in a set hampered by equipment issues to 3,000 audience members at the New York City [[Roseland Ballroom]], a frustrated Apple left the stage without returning. Her performance saw Apple appearing distraught at the sound quality, apologizing numerous times for the sound and crying.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.music-slam.com/music-slam-concert-review-fiona-apple-roseland-ballroom-02292000/|title=Music-Slam Concert Review\u2014Fiona Apple @ Roseland Ballroom (02.29.2000) |website=Music-slam.com |date=June 30, 2005 |accessdate=March 22, 2015}}</ref> After completing a [[concert tour]] in support of her second album in 2000, Apple relocated to Los Angeles.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n===2002\u20132010: ''Extraordinary Machine'' ===\nDuring her hiatus, Apple contemplated retiring from her recording career. Apple sang with [[Johnny Cash]] on a cover of [[Simon & Garfunkel]]'s \"[[Bridge over Troubled Water (song)|Bridge over Troubled Water]]\" that ended up on his album ''[[American IV: The Man Comes Around]]'' and was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for \"[[Best Country Collaboration with Vocals]]\". She also collaborated with Cash on [[Cat Stevens]]'s \"[[Father and Son (song)|Father and Son]]\", which was included in his 2003 collection ''[[Unearthed (Johnny Cash album)|Unearthed]]''.\n\n[[File:Free Fiona protest outside Sony BMG headquarters in NYC 28-01-2005.jpg|left|thumb|upright=.9|Fans in support of Fiona Apple demonstrating outside the [[New York City|NYC]] headquarters of [[Sony BMG Music Entertainment]] in January 2005.]]\n\nApple's third album, ''[[Extraordinary Machine]]'', was originally produced by [[Jon Brion]]. In spring 2002, Apple and Brion, her longtime friend and producer on ''When the Pawn,'' met for their weekly lunch meeting. Brion reportedly \"begged\" Apple to make another album. Apple agreed, and Brion went to Apple's label, [[Epic Records]], with strict stipulations (including no deadline), which the label eventually agreed to. Recording sessions began in 2002, at [[Ocean Way studios]] in Nashville, Tennessee, but later moved to the [[Paramour Mansion]] in Los Angeles. Work on the album continued until 2003, and in May of that year it was submitted to Sony executives. In 2004 and 2005, tracks were leaked on the Internet in MP3 format and played on U.S. and international radio. Subsequently, MP3s of the entire album went online. Although a Web site distributing the album was quickly shut down, it soon reached [[peer-to-peer|P2P]] networks and was downloaded by fans.<ref name=\"spin\" /> A fan-led campaign supported the album's official release.\n\n[[Mike Elizondo]], who had previously played bass on ''Pawn'', was brought back as co-producer to complete the tracks he had begun with Brion and Apple. ''Spin'' later reported the following: \"Fans erroneously thought that Apple's record label, [[Epic Records|Epic]], had rejected the first version of ''Extraordinary Machine''...&nbsp;in reality, according to Elizondo, Apple was unhappy with the results, and it was her decision to redo the record, not her label's.\"<ref name=\"spin\" /> In August 2005, the album was given an October release date.<ref name=\"spin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/features/news/2005/08/050815_fiona_apple/ |title=Fiona Apple's ''Machine'' Finally Turned On|website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date= August 15, 2005|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref> Production had been largely redone \"from scratch\" by Elizondo and was co-produced by [[Brian Kehew]]. Two of the 11 previous leaked tracks were relatively unchanged, and one new song was also included.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/15/arts/music/15appl.html |work=The New York Times|title=Fiona Apple Retools Her Leaked Album|accessdate= August 15, 2005}}</ref> Despite suggestions that the album had caused a rift between Brion and Apple, they regularly perform together at [[Largo (nightclub)|Largo]], a club in Los Angeles, including a joint appearance with Elizondo on bass just before the news broke of an official release.<ref name=Elizondo>{{cite web|title=Music: Fiona Apple|url=http://www.studentsoftheworld.info/sites/music/7104.php|website=studentsoftheworld.info|accessdate=August 25, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927143738/http://www.studentsoftheworld.info/sites/music/7104.php|archivedate=September 27, 2011}}</ref> ''Extraordinary Machine'' debuted at number seven and was nominated for a Grammy Award for \"[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]]\". It was eventually certified [[gold album|gold]],<ref name=RIAA /> though its singles (\"[[Parting Gift]]\", \"[[O' Sailor]]\", \"[[Not About Love]]\", and \"[[Get Him Back]]\") failed to enter any ''Billboard'' charts.<ref name=Billboard-Apr2006>{{cite news|author=Cohen, Jonathan|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/58703/fiona-taps-rice-garza-for-summer-trek |title=Fiona Taps Rice, Garza For Summer Trek|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date= April 19, 2006}}</ref> Apple went on a live tour to promote the album in late 2005.\n\n[[File:Fiona-Apple.jpg|thumb|upright=.9|Apple performing in [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]], 2006]]\nIn June 2006, Apple appeared on the joke track \"Come Over and Get It (Up in 'Dem Guts)\" by comedian [[Zach Galifianakis]]. Galifianakis previously appeared in the music video for Apple's \"Not About Love\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stereogum.com/22421/new_zach_galifianakis_fiona_apple_up_in_them_guts/mp3s/ |last1=Galifianakis|first1=Zach|last2=Apple|first2=Fiona|title=Up In Them Guts|website=Stereogum.com|accessdate= June 8, 2011}}</ref> Apple recorded a cover of \"Sally's Song\" for the 2006 special edition release of the soundtrack for the [[Tim Burton]] film ''[[The Nightmare Before Christmas]]''. In May 2006, Apple paid tribute to [[Elvis Costello]] on [[VH1]]'s concert series ''[[Decades Rock Live]],'' by performing Costello's hit \"I Want You\". Her version was subsequently released as a digital single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EiOmhOumh-w |title=Decades Rock Live |website=YouTube.com |accessdate=April 12, 2014}}</ref> Apple toured the East Coast during August 2007, with [[Nickel Creek]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Hasty, Kate|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1052031/apple-nickel-creek-teaming-for-tour |title=Apple, Nickel Creek Teaming For Tour|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date= May 18, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Madison, Tjames|url=http://www.livedaily.com/news/12126.html|title=Fiona Apple joins Nickel Creek's 'farewell' tour|work=[[LiveDaily]]|date=May 17, 2007|accessdate=March 2, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410022102/http://www.livedaily.com/news/12126.html|archivedate=April 10, 2008}}</ref> In 2008, Apple recorded a duet titled \"Still I\" with Christophe Deluy. In 2009, Apple covered \"Why Try to Change Me Now\" and \"I Walk A Little Faster\" for ''The Best Is Yet to Come \u2013 The Songs of [[Cy Coleman]]''.\n\nIn January 2010, Fiona Apple and [[Jon Brion]] performed together at \"Love and Haiti, Too: A Music Benefit\", a charity concert for the people hurt by the [[Haiti earthquake]]. Fiona sang a cover of \"(S)he's Funny That Way\", composed by Neil Moret, lyrics by Richard Whiting, which is often associated with the singer [[Billie Holiday]]. In June 2010, Fiona released a song titled \"So Sleepy\", produced by [[Jon Brion]] and written by children involved with the non-profit organization [[826LA]]. The song was included on a compilation album released by the organization titled ''[[Chickens in Love]]''. Apple collaborated with [[Margaret Cho]] on her album ''[[Cho Dependent]]'', which was released on August 24, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Maerz |first=Melissa |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/06/07/margaret-cho-album-murder-ballad/ |title=Margaret Cho's Murder Ballad |website=Popwatch.ew.com |date=June 7, 2010 |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132018: ''The Idler Wheel...''===\n[[File:Fiona Apple 2012 NYC T5.jpg|thumb|upright=.9|left|Apple performing at [[Terminal 5 (venue)|Terminal 5]], New York, 2012]]\n\nIn late 2010, ''Billboard'' published an article stating that Apple was planning on releasing a new album in spring 2011, with musician [[Michelle Branch]] claiming to have heard some of the new tracks.<ref name=\"bill\">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/956287/fiona-apple-releasing-new-album-in-spring-2011|work=Billboard|title=Fiona Apple Releasing New Album in Spring 2011|author=Maples, Jillian|date=September 16, 2010|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref> Drummer [[Charley Drayton]] also told ''Modern Drummer'' magazine that he was co-producing the record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/510706/fiona-apple-to-release-new-music-in-the-next-few-weeks-says-la-reid |title=Fiona Apple To Release New Music 'In The Next Few Weeks,' says L.A. Reid |website=Billboard.com |date=September 14, 2009 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> However, the album was not released in the spring and ''Billboard'' reported later that Epic was not aware of a record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/469132/11-anticipated-album-updates-madonna-dmx-nickelback-and-more |title=11 Anticipated Album Updates: Madonna, DMX, Nickelback And More |website=Billboard |date=September 14, 2009 |accessdate=May 1, 2012}}</ref> Apple delayed the album's release until 2012, explaining that she was waiting \"until her label found a new president and that she didn't want her work to be mishandled amid corporate disarray.\"<ref name=\"NYTimes1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/03/arts/music/fiona-apples-new-album-the-idler-wheel.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all |title=Fiona Apple Faces Outward |first=Jon |last=Pareles |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 30, 2012 |accessdate=June 3, 2012}}</ref> In January 2012, after its new record label head, [[LA Reid]] hinted at new music from Apple, Epic Records announced that the album would be released later in the year.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://entertainment.time.com/2012/01/24/fiona-apple-has-new-music-coming-out-but-not-in-the-next-few-weeks/|title=Release date for new album | work=Time| accessdate=January 24, 2012| date=January 24, 2012}}</ref> Apple announced performances at the [[South by Southwest]] Festival and [[The Idler Wheel Tour|a spring 2012 tour]] soon after.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2012/02/21/fiona-apple-tour-dates-2012-sxsw/ |title=Concert dates including South by Southwest Festival| work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | date=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Idler Wheel...|The Idler Wheel Is Wiser Than the Driver of the Screw and Whipping Cords Will Serve You More Than Ropes Will Ever Do]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Perpetua, Matthew |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/fiona-apple-unveils-23-word-album-title-20120307 |title=Fiona Apple Unveils 23-Word Album Title &#124; Music News |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=March 7, 2012 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"pitchfork.com\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/45671-fiona-apple-reveals-album-title/ |title=Fiona Apple Reveals Album Title &#124; News |website=Pitchfork |date=March 7, 2012 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> Apple's fourth studio album, was released on June 19, 2012, in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiona-apple.com |title=Welcome &#124; The Official Fiona Apple site |website=Fiona-apple.com |accessdate=May 1, 2012}}</ref> It received critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-idler-wheel-is-wiser-than-the-driver-of-the-screw-and-whipping-cords-will-serve-you-more-than-ro |title=The Idler Wheel Is Wiser than the Driver of the Screw and Whipping Cords Will Serve You More than Ropes Will Ever Do \u2013 Fiona Apple |website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher= [[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref> According to an article in ''[[American Songwriter]]'' \"''The Idler Wheel'' isn't always pretty, but it pulses with life, brutal and true.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2012/06/fiona-apple-the-idler-wheel/ |title=Fiona Apple: The Idler Wheel... |website=[[American Songwriter]] |accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Fiona Apple 2012.png|thumb|Apple performing in Miami Beach, 2012]]\n\nApple contributed a previously unreleased song entitled \"[[Dull Tool]]\" to the soundtrack of the 2012 [[Judd Apatow]] film ''[[This Is 40]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/listen-fiona-apples-dull-tool-from-the-this-is-40-soundtrack-paul-rudd-hearts-ween-in-new-poster-20121117 |title=Listen: Fiona Apple's \"Dull Tool\" From The 'This Is 40' Soundtrack; Paul Rudd Hearts Ween In New Poster |website=[[IndieWire]] |first=Edward |last=Davis |date=November 17, 2012 |accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref> Another song recorded for the film that was not included in the soundtrack has yet to be released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/9011-judd-apatow/|title=Judd Apatow|website=Pitchfork}}</ref> In September 2013, a [[Chipotle Mexican Grill|Chipotle]] ad appeared online with a soundtrack of Apple covering \"[[Pure Imagination]]\" from the 1971 film ''[[Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory]]''. The video, which follows a scarecrow as he discovers the truth about [[factory farming]] and processed food, was described as \"haunted,\" \"dystopian,\" \"bizarre,\" and \"beautiful.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/pop/Watch-Fiona-Apple-Chipotle-Partner-Bizarre-Beautiful-Pure-Imagination-Cover-59072.html |title=Watch: Fiona Apple And Chipotle Partner For Bizarre And Beautiful Pure Imagination Cover|website=CinemaBlend}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/52274-watch-fiona-apple-covers-pure-imagination-from-willy-wonka-for-chipotle-ad-on-factory-farming/|title=Watch: Fiona Apple Covers \"Pure Imagination\" From Willy Wonka for Chipotle Ad on Factory Farming |website= Pitchfork}}</ref>\nIn 2014, Apple wrote the opening theme, \"[[Container (song)|Container]]\", for the Showtime drama series ''[[The Affair (TV series)|The Affair]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title='The Affair' opening credits feature new Fiona Apple song: Listen|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/10/02/fiona-apple-affair-credits/|accessdate=December 20, 2014|website=EW}}</ref> During 2014, Apple also appeared at a number of performances by [[Blake Mills]], including in New York City and Cambridge, MA, during his tour in support of his second full-length album, ''Heigh Ho''. The pair first publicly collaborated on an acoustic version of Apple's song \"I Know\" in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=I Know, Apple and Mills|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rza0XycpyA8|accessdate=April 5, 2015|website=YouTube}}</ref> Fiona Apple has collaborated with [[Andrew Bird]], and in 2016, she was featured in the song \"Left Handed Kisses\" from the album ''[[Are You Serious (Andrew Bird album)|Are You Serious]]''.\n\nIn 2017, she released \"[[Tiny Hands]]\" for the [[2017 Women's March|Women's March on Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Bromwich, Jonah|title=Fiona Apple Releases a Trump Protest Chant|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/18/arts/music/fiona-apple-tiny-hands-womens-march.html|work=The New York Times|date=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she joined [[Shirley Manson]] at the female-driven Girl School Festival in Los Angeles for a cover of \"[[You Don't Own Me]]\" by [[Lesley Gore]], wearing a white T-shirt with \"KNEEL, PORTNOW\" written across it in ink. This was considered in response to Grammy head [[Neil Portnow]]'s heavily criticized comments that women need to \"step up\" in order to earn more Grammy nods.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ortega, Mark|title=WATCH: Shirley Manson and Fiona Apple cover \"You Don't Own Me\"|url=http://www.passtheaux.co/girl-school-2018-shirley-manson-fiona-apple/|work=Pass The Aux|date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters''===\nIn January 2019, Apple collaborated with [[King Princess]] on a version of her 1999 song \"I Know\". The song was released for Spotify's RISE program on January 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/01/25/688618778/king-princess-and-fiona-apple-collaborate-on-new-version-of-i-know|title=King Princess And Fiona Apple Collaborate On New Version Of 'I Know'|website=NPR.org}}</ref> Apple was featured in the documentary and [[Echo in the Canyon (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] for [[Echo in the Canyon]] with [[Jakob Dylan]] covering songs by artists such as [[the Beach Boys]] and [[the Byrds]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/fiona-apple-jakob-dylan-beach-boys-in-my-room-839505/|title=Hear Fiona Apple, Jakob Dylan Cover the Beach Boys' 'In My Room'|first=Claire|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Shaffer|date=May 24, 2019}}</ref> In November, she covered \"Whole of the Moon,\" a [[The Waterboys|Waterboys]] song, for the series finale of [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s ''[[The Affair (TV series)|The Affair]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/fiona-apple-waterboys-whole-of-the-moon-cover-907809/|title=Hear Fiona Apple's Full-Throated Cover of the Waterboys' 'The Whole of the Moon'|first1=Jon|last1=Blistein|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=November 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/fiona-apple-covers-the-waterboys%E2%80%99-%E2%80%9Cthe-whole-of-the-moon%E2%80%9D-listen/ar-AAJQ1bU|title=Fiona Apple Covers the Waterboys\u2019 \u201cThe Whole of the Moon\u201d: Listen|website=Msn.com}}</ref>\n\nIn two Instagram posts in March 2019, Apple hinted at the recording of a fifth album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-fiona-apple-tease-and-record-new-music-at-home-studio/|title=Watch Fiona Apple Tease and Record New Music at Home Studio|website=pitchfork.com}}</ref> In a September 2019 interview with Vulture, she confirmed that the album was in its final stages, recorded with a band and planned for an early 2020 release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/fiona-apple-is-still-calling-bullshit.html|title=Fiona Apple Is Still Calling Bullshit|website=vulture.com}}</ref> In a follow-up interview with Vulture in January 2020, she said her new album would probably be out \"in a few months.\"<ref name=\"vulture\">{{cite news |last1=Handler |first1=Rachel |title=15 Minutes With Fiona Apple |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-updates.html |accessdate=24 January 2020 |publisher=Vulture |date=22 January 2020}}</ref> On March 8, 2020, Apple posted a video showcasing her saying \"M-Y-R-E-C-O-R-D-I-S-D-O-N-E\" in [[American Sign Language]].<ref name=radical>\n{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/03/23/fiona-apples-art-of-radical-sensitivity |title=Fiona Apple's Art of Radical Sensitivity|date=16 March 2020 |work=The New Yorker}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[The New Yorker]]'' it was announced the new album will be called ''[[Fetch the Bolt Cutters]]''. Apple later announced that the album would be released on April 17, 2020. The album is entirely self-produced and consists of 13 songs.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u3yH33epGJY |title=Fiona Apple \u2013 5 |date=16 March 2020 |website=newyorker.com|publisher=Fiona Apple Rocks}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xERU-0nrGHE |title=Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters |date=1 April 2020 |website=youtube.com|publisher=Fiona Apple Rocks}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n{{expert needed | Biography | section = yes | reason = the section is a dumping ground of out-of-date content, with no rhyme or reason in its ordering | date = March 2020}}\nApple is a [[vegan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/music/fiona-apple-interview|title=Fiona Apple: Interview|magazine=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|first=John|last=Lewis|date=April 4, 2006|accessdate=June 17, 2016}}</ref> During an in-depth interview on [[Marc Maron]]'s [[WTF with Marc Maron|''WTF'' podcast]] she revealed that she has battled [[obsessive\u2013compulsive disorder]] throughout her adult life and had recently decided to quit drinking.<ref name=wtf>{{cite podcast |host=Marc Maron |work=[[WTF with Marc Maron]]| |url=http://www.wtfpod.com/podcast/episodes/episode_297_-_fiona_apple|title=Episode 297|date=July 16, 2012|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref> She has also gone on record about struggling with [[clinical depression|depression]], [[self-harm]], [[post-traumatic stress]] and trust issues with men, particularly in the wake of her rape.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/fiona-the-caged-bird-sings-244221/|title=Fiona: The Caged Bird Sings|last=Heath|first=Chris|date=January 22, 1998|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=August 3, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe fallout from Apple's breakup with her first serious boyfriend, Tyson, was the basis for her first album, ''[[Tidal (album)|Tidal]].'' According to a 1998 profile in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', the two of them managed to stay on good terms.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\"/> In the late 1990s, she was linked with [[illusionist]] and [[endurance artist]] [[David Blaine]], followed by writer/director [[Paul Thomas Anderson]] during the 2000s and writer/TV creator [[Jonathan Ames]] in the mid to late 2000s.<ref>{{Cite journal|author = Hopper, Jessica | date=April 24, 2012 | title=Fiona Apple's Bad, Bad Girl Moments|journal=Rolling Stone| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/fiona-apples-bad-bad-girl-moments-22292/|access-date=August 3, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/06/fiona-apple-is-not-insane/258660/|title=Fiona Apple Is Not Insane|last=Kornhaber|first=Spencer|date=June 19, 2012|work=The Atlantic|access-date=August 3, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Bustle|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/2603-fiona-apple-paul-thomas-anderson-reunite-to-make-a-simple-yet-stunning-new-music-video|title=Fiona Apple & Paul Thomas Anderson Reunite to Make a Simple Yet Stunning New Music Video|author=Semigran, Aly|date=July 25, 2013|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref> She has admitted she maintains friendships with all of her ex-boyfriends, noting \"I really care about them. I care about their lives with their girlfriends. I feel like maybe an annoying mother or something.\"<ref>{{Cite web|first=John|last=Norris|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/fiona-apple-idling-no-more/|title=Fiona Apple: Idling No More|magazine=[[V (American magazine)|V]]|publisher=[[Visionaire]]|location=New York City|date=June 26, 2012|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=Craig|last=McLean|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/jan/29/popandrock.fionaapple|title=Craig McLean profiles Fiona Apple, best-selling artist|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|language=en|date=January 29, 2006|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> In a June 2012 interview, she revealed she had briefly married a French photographer \"for complicated reasons\" and had a passing liaison with a younger woman.<ref name=Lee><!--?REPEAT2?-->{{cite web|first=Dan P.|last=Lee|url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/06/hiding-out-with-fiona-apple-musical-hermit.html|title='I Just Want to Feel Everything\u2019: Hiding Out With Fiona Apple, Musical Hermit|website=[[vulture.com|Vulture]]|publisher=[[New York Media]]|location=New York City|date=June 17, 2012|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 19, 2012, Apple was arrested at an [[United States Border Patrol Interior Checkpoints|internal U.S. Border Patrol checkpoint]] in [[Sierra Blanca, Texas]], and charged with possession of [[hashish]], detaining her en route to a concert in [[Austin, Texas]], at the [[Hudspeth County, Texas|Hudspeth County]] Jail.<ref name=\"NYMN September 2012\">{{cite web | author = McDougan, Farfel | date = September 20, 2012 | title = Fiona Apple Arrested | work = New York Music News | url = http://nymn.com/fiona-apple-arrested-new-york-music-news/ | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120923150232/http://nymn.com/fiona-apple-arrested-new-york-music-news/ | archive-date = September 23, 2012 | accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TMZ September 2012\">{{cite web | title=Fiona Apple Arrested for Hash in Texas |url=http://www.tmz.com/2012/09/20/fiona-apple-arrested-drugs-weed-hash-texas-hashish/ |work=TMZ.com |date=September 20, 2012 |accessdate=September 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Apple wrote a letter to her fans \u2013 a scan of which was posted to her website and her [[Facebook]] page \u2013 postponing the South American leg of her tour due to the health of her dog, Janet. According to the letter, the dog has [[Addison's disease]] and has had a tumor \"idling in her chest\" for two years.<ref>{{cite web| author = Apple, Fiona | url=http://www.lettersofnote.com/2012/11/she-is-my-best-friend.html |title=She is my best friend |work=Letters of Note | date=November 21, 2012 |accessdate=February 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 30, 2019, Apple pledged to donate two years' worth of earnings from TV and movie placements of her song \"[[Criminal (Fiona Apple song)|Criminal]]\" to the [[While They Wait]] fund, which assists refugees with basic necessities, immigration fees and legal services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/fiona-apple-criminal-royalties-refugees-854497/|title=Fiona Apple Pledges Two Years of \u2018Criminal\u2019 Royalties to Refugees|last=Reed|first=Ryan|date=July 2, 2019|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref> In 2020, While They Wait's Scott Hechinger revealed to Vulture that Fiona has donated $90,000, and that donation will help out 15 families.<ref name=\"vulture\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Fiona Apple discography|List of songs recorded by Fiona Apple}}\n* ''[[Tidal (album)|Tidal]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[When the Pawn...]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Extraordinary Machine]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Idler Wheel...]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Fetch the Bolt Cutters]]'' (2020)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Fiona Apple}}\nApple's debut album earned her a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Female Rock Vocal Performance|Best Female Rock Vocal Performance]] for \"Criminal\" and the [[MTV Video Music Award]] for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist in a Video]] for \"Sleep to Dream\". For ''When the Pawn...'', Apple won the California Music Award for Outstanding Female Vocalist. For ''Extraordinary Machine'', she won an Esky Music Award for Best Songbird.\n\n==See also==\n*\"[[Apple of Sodom (song)|Apple of Sodom]]\", a [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]] song inspired by Apple\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Fiona Apple}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n*{{DMOZ|Arts/Music/Bands_and_Artists/A/Apple%2C_Fiona/}}\n* {{IMDb name|4712}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alanis Morissette]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[MTV Video Music Award for Best New Artist]]|years=1997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Natalie Imbruglia]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Fiona Apple}}\n{{Portal bar|1990s|Los Angeles|Music|New York City}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Apple, Fiona}}\n[[Category:Fiona Apple| ]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women pianists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Alexander Hamilton High School (Los Angeles) alumni]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock singers]]\n[[Category:American contraltos]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American pop pianists]]\n[[Category:Art pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Ballad musicians]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Epic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Harlem]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper West Side]]\n[[Category:People with obsessive\u2013compulsive disorder]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Abbyjjjj96", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiona_Apple"}
{"title_page": "Michael Woodhouse", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name             = Michael Woodhouse\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=NZL|MP|size=100%}}\n| image            =Michael Woodhouse.jpg\n| imagesize        =\n| constituency_MP  = \n| parliament       =\n| majority         =\n| order            = [[New Zealand Parliament|Deputy Leader of the House]]\n| term_start       = 2 May 2017\n| term_end         = 26 October 2017 \n| primeminister    = [[Bill English]]\n| predecessor      = [[Simon Bridges]]\n| successor        = [[Iain Lees-Galloway]] \n| office1          = [[Accident Compensation Corporation|Minister for ACC]]\n| term_start1      = 20 December 2016\n| term_end1        = 26 October 2017\n| primeminister1   = [[Bill English]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Nikki Kaye]]\n| successor1       = [[Iain Lees-Galloway]] \n| office2          = 55th [[Minister of Immigration (New Zealand)|Minister of Immigration]]\n| term_start2      = 31 January 2013\n| term_end2        = 26 October 2017\n| primeminister2   = [[John Key]]<br />[[Bill English]]\n| predecessor2     = [[Nathan Guy]]\n| successor2       = [[Iain Lees-Galloway]] \n| office3          = 1st Minister for Workplace Relations and Safety\n| term_start3      = 8 October 2014\n| term_end3        = 26 October 2017\n| primeminister3   = [[John Key]]<br />[[Bill English]]\n| predecessor3     = [[Simon Bridges]] {{small|(as Minister of Labour)}}\n| successor3       = [[Iain Lees-Galloway]]\n| office4          = 28th [[Inland Revenue Department (New Zealand)#List of Ministers|Minister of Revenue]]\n| term_start4      = 14 December 2015\n| term_end4        = 20 December 2016\n| primeminister4   = [[John Key]]<br />[[Bill English]]\n| predecessor4     = [[Todd McClay]]\n| successor4       = [[Judith Collins]]\n| birth_date       = <!--{{Birth date and age|1965|df=yes}}-->\n| birth_place      = [[South Dunedin]], [[New Zealand]]\n| nationality      = New Zealand\n| spouse           =\n| party            = [[New Zealand National Party|National]]\n| relations        =\n| children         =\n| residence        =\n| alma_mater       =\n| occupation       =\n| profession       =\n| religion         =\n| signature        =\n| website          = {{url|http://www.michaelwoodhouse.co.nz}}\n| footnotes        =\n}}\n'''Michael Allan Woodhouse''' (born {{circa}}1965) is a [[New Zealand National Party|National]] member of the [[New Zealand Parliament]].\n\n==Early years==\nWoodhouse was born and raised in [[South Dunedin]], the fifth of nine children. He attended St Patrick's, St Edmund's and St Pauls High School, now [[Kavanagh College]], which he left at the end of sixth form in 1982.<ref name=\"National Party bio\">{{cite web | url=https://www.national.org.nz/team/mps/detail/michael.woodhouse | title=Hon Michael Woodhouse | work=national.org.nz | accessdate=16 December 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216090042/https://www.national.org.nz/team/mps/detail/michael.woodhouse | archivedate=16 December 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe worked for the [[National Bank of New Zealand]] in Dunedin and [[Wellington]] until 1987 when he embarked on a [[rugby union|rugby]] sojourn to Scotland and England, playing for [[Dunfermline RFC|Dunfermline]] 1987/88 and [[Broughton Park RUFC|Broughton Park]] in [[Manchester]] 1988/89.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} He then returned to Dunedin where he studied [[Commerce]] and [[Accounting]] at the [[University of Otago]], which he graduated from in 1993.<ref name=\"National Party bio\" />\n\nHe worked at Taylor Mclachlan Accountants in Dunedin, [[Dunedin Hospital]] and [[Accident Compensation Corporation|ACC]]. In 2005 he earned a Masters of Health Administration<ref> Degree check from UNSW [https://graduateregister.unsw.edu.au/?form%5BlastName%5D=Woodhouse&form%5BfirstName%5D=Michael&form%5Bdegree%5D=Master+of+Health+Administration&form%5B_token%5D=jzV4xfFOxlvqp-9qUTNzgeQmI2H-6YupC1GOdKYgMXc graduateregister.unsw.edu.au]</ref> at the [[University of New South Wales]] in [[Australia]].\nPrior to his political career, Woodhouse was the CEO of [[Mercy Hospital (Dunedin)|Mercy Hospital]] in Dunedin from 2001 to 2008.<ref name=\"National Party bio\" />\n\nWoodhouse was convicted for [[drink-driving]] when he was 21 years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/10677179/Police-ministers-drink-drive-confession |title=Police minister's drink-drive confession|last=Shadwell |first=Talia |date=30 October 2014 |work=[[The Dominion Post (New Zealand)|The Dominion Post]]|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\n{{NZ parlbox header|align=left}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |term       = 49th\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|2008}}\n |end        = 2011\n |electorate = [[Party lists in the 2008 New Zealand general election#National Party|List]]\n |party      = New Zealand National Party\n |list       = 49\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |term=50th\n |start={{NZ election link year|2011}}\n |end=2014\n |electorate = [[Party lists in the 2011 New Zealand general election#National Party|List]]\n |list=31\n |party=New Zealand National Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |term=51st\n |start={{NZ election link year|2014}}\n |end=2017\n |electorate = List\n |list=20\n |party=New Zealand National Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |term=51st\n |start={{NZ election link year|2017}}\n |end=present\n |electorate = List\n |list=10\n |party=New Zealand National Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox footer}}\n\n===Fifth National Government, 2008\u20132017===\nWoodhouse stood in [[Dunedin North (New Zealand electorate)|Dunedin North]] in 2008 and, though he received 30.64% (9972) of the votes he was defeated by incumbent electorate [[Pete Hodgson]] who received 52.62% of the vote. He was still however elected to the [[New Zealand House of Representatives]] through National's party [[list MP|list]]. In the {{NZ election link|2011}}, Woodhouse reduced the majority from 7,155 in 2008<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2005/electorate-10.html |title=Official Count Results \u2013 Dunedin North |publisher=Electionresults.govt.nz |date= |accessdate=27 May 2012}}</ref> to 3,489 against [[David Clark (New Zealand politician)|David Clark]].<ref>{{cite web| author=New Zealand Electoral Commission |url=http://www.electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2011/electorate-8.html |title=Official Count Results \u2013 Dunedin North |publisher=Electionresults.govt.nz |date= |accessdate=2012-05-27}}</ref> National also lost the party vote by 420 votes. Clark beat Woodhouse with an increased majority in the {{NZ election link|2014}}.<ref>{{cite news |title=Agony and ecstasy for Dunedin party faithful |url= http://www.odt.co.nz/news/election-2014/316617/agony-and-ecstasy-dunedin-party-faithful |accessdate=27 September 2014 |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |date=20 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nA member of the Health and Transport & Industrial Relations Select Committees in the [[49th New Zealand Parliament|49th Parliament]], Woodhouse was elected as the National Party's senior [[whip (politics)|whip]] on 20 December 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=National's whips Woodhouse and Upston |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/6166714/Nationals-whips-Woodhouse-and-Upston |accessdate=28 August 2018 |publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]], [[Fairfax New Zealand]] |date=20 December 2011}}</ref> He is the head of the Parliamentarians for Arthritis group and is active in the Parliamentary Sports Trust as a rugby player and referee.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nIn a reshuffle in January 2013, Woodhouse was made a minister outside cabinet and was given the Immigration, Veteran's Affairs and associate transport portfolios.<ref name=\"NZ Parliament\">{{cite web |title=Hon Michael Woodhouse |url=https://www.parliament.nz/en/mps-and-electorates/members-of-parliament/woodhouse-michael/ |publisher=[[New Zealand Parliament]] |accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref> During his time in Parliament,  Woodhouse voted against the [[Marriage (Definition of Marriage) Amendment Act 2013|Marriage (Definition of Marriage) Amendment Bill]], a bill allowing same-sex couples to marry in New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/7575780/Two-Canty-MPs-vote-against-gay-marriage-bill |title=Two Canty MPs vote against gay marriage bill |date=30 August 2012 |work=[[The Press]]|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> During the [[Fifth National Government of New Zealand|Fifth National Government]], Woodhouse served in various portfolios including immigration, transport, veteran's affairs, land information, workplace relations and safety, police, and the [[Accident Compensation Corporation]].<ref name=\"NZ Parliament\" /><ref name=\"National Party bio\" />\n\nIn August 2015, Michael Woodhouse caused controversy when he released a list of 57 high risk industries for his Health an Safety Reform Bill. This list was mocked by the Opposition because worm farming and mini golf were deemed \"high risk\", while dairy and cattle farming were not. Labour leader,  [[Andrew Little (New Zealand politician)|Andrew Little]], stated the new classifications were \"overly complicated, ill thought out and rushed through to appease National Party backers, putting the lives of New Zealanders at risk\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/71305806/government-deems-minigolf-and-worm-farming-more-risky-than-cattle-farming|title=Government deems mini-golf and worm farming more risky than cattle farming|last=Rutherford |first=Hamish |date=20 August 2015 |work=Stuff.co.nz |accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> While Labour's spokesperson for Labour issues, [[Iain Lees-Galloway]], said Woodhouse \"can\u2019t worm his way out of this. He will be forever ridiculed as the Minister who made killer worm farms safer but failed to protect people working in some of New Zealand's most dangerous industries\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Woodhouse wrote own worm farm risk list |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1510/S00205/woodhouse-wrote-own-worm-farm-risk-list.htm |accessdate=28 August 2018 |work=[[New Zealand Labour Party]] |publisher=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=14 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2017 New Zealand general election|2017 general election]], Michael Woodhouse was re-elected as a List MP on the National Party List. However, he failed to capture the [[Dunedin North]] electorate seat, which was held by Labour MP David Clark.<ref>{{cite web |title=2017 General Election list of successful candidates |url=https://www.elections.org.nz/sites/default/files/media/attachments/07_10_17_attachment_a_successful_candidates.pdf |publisher=[[Electoral Commission (New Zealand)|Electoral Commission]] |accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Sixth Labour Government, 2017\u2013present===\nFollowing the formation of a [[Sixth Labour Government of New Zealand|Labour-led coalition government]] with the support of [[New Zealand First]] and the [[Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand|Green Party]], National and its former support partner, the libertarian [[ACT New Zealand]] party, formed the opposition in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newshub.co.nz/home/election/2017/10/full-video-nz-first-leader-winston-peters-announces-next-government.html |title=Full video: NZ First leader Winston Peters announces next Government |author=Chapman, Grant |date=19 October 2017 |work=[[Newshub]] |accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newshub.co.nz/home/election/2017/10/an-historic-moment-for-the-green-party-james-shaw.html |title=An 'historic moment' for the Green Party \u2013 James Shaw |author=Hurley, Emma |date=19 October 2017 |work=[[Newshub]] |accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref> Michael Woodhouse became Deputy Shadow Leader of the House and the National Party's spokesperson for health and immigration. He is also currently a member of the health and privileges select committees.<ref name=\"NZ Parliament\" />\n\nIn early August 2018, Woodhouse in his capacity as National health spokesperson called for National Health Targets to be a legal requirement in response to the Labour Party's proposed Child Poverty legislation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kirk |first1=Stacey |title=National wants the Health Targets to be a legal requirement |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/105915451/national-wants-the-health-targets-to-be-a-legal-requirement |accessdate=28 August 2018 |publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Houlahan |first1=Mike |title=Woodhouse pushes health targets case |url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/health/woodhouse-pushes-health-targets-case |accessdate=28 August 2018 |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |date=6 August 2018}}</ref> In late August 2018, Woodhouse objected to United States whistleblower [[Chelsea Manning]]'s proposed tour of New Zealand in early September 2018, arguing that she should be banned due to her lack of remorse over her role in leaking sensitive US military documents to [[WikiLeaks]].<ref>{{cite news |title=National's Michael Woodhouse calls for whistleblower Chelsea Manning to be banned from New Zealand |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12114977 |accessdate=28 August 2018 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=28 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Garrick |first1=Gia |title=National wants Chelsea Manning banned from NZ |url=https://www.radionz.co.nz/news/political/365116/national-wants-chelsea-manning-banned-from-nz |accessdate=28 August 2018 |publisher=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWoodhouse is an avid [[Rugby union|rugby]] fan, having played for [[Otago]] in his youth. He has a wife Amanda and three children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michaelwoodhouse.co.nz/|title=HON MICHAEL WOODHOUSE List MP in Dunedin|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAn avid rugby follower, Woodhouse played age group rugby for Otago and South Island rep teams and premier rugby for Dunedin and Western Suburbs in Wellington. He also refereed 84 premier and approximately 20 representative colts and 'B' provincial matches. He also was a premier grade referee.<ref name=\"National Party bio\" />{{better source|date=December 2014}}\n\nHis three daughters are really cool and the youngest is by far the best\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Michael Woodhouse}}\n*[http://www.parliament.nz/en-nz/mpp/mps/current/51MP2991/woodhouse-michael Michael Woodhouse] at Parliament\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141216090042/https://www.national.org.nz/team/mps/detail/michael.woodhouse Michael Woodhouse] at the National Party\n*[http://www.michaelwoodhouse.co.nz Michael Woodhouse] \u2013 personal website\n\n{{Fifth National Government of New Zealand}}\n{{NZ National Party}}\n{{Current members of the New Zealand House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woodhouse, Michael}}\n[[Category:New Zealand National Party MPs]]\n[[Category:People from Dunedin]]\n[[Category:University of Otago alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand list MPs]]\n[[Category:People educated at Kavanagh College]]\n[[Category:1960s births]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Zealand House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand politicians]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2017 New Zealand general election]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|New Zealand politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name             = Michael Woodhouse\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=NZL|MP|size=100%}}\n| image            =Michael Woodhouse.jpg\n| imagesize        =\n| constituency_MP  = \n| parliament       =\n| majority         =\n| order            = [[New Zealand Parliament|Deputy Leader of the House]]\n| term_start       = 2 May 2017\n| term_end         = 26 October 2017 \n| primeminister    = [[Bill English]]\n| predecessor      = [[Simon Bridges]]\n| successor        = [[Iain Lees-Galloway]] \n| office1          = [[Accident Compensation Corporation|Minister for ACC]]\n| term_start1      = 20 December 2016\n| term_end1        = 26 October 2017\n| primeminister1   = [[Bill English]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Nikki Kaye]]\n| successor1       = [[Iain Lees-Galloway]] \n| office2          = 55th [[Minister of Immigration (New Zealand)|Minister of Immigration]]\n| term_start2      = 31 January 2013\n| term_end2        = 26 October 2017\n| primeminister2   = [[John Key]]<br />[[Bill English]]\n| predecessor2     = [[Nathan Guy]]\n| successor2       = [[Iain Lees-Galloway]] \n| office3          = 1st Minister for Workplace Relations and Safety\n| term_start3      = 8 October 2014\n| term_end3        = 26 October 2017\n| primeminister3   = [[John Key]]<br />[[Bill English]]\n| predecessor3     = [[Simon Bridges]] {{small|(as Minister of Labour)}}\n| successor3       = [[Iain Lees-Galloway]]\n| office4          = 28th [[Inland Revenue Department (New Zealand)#List of Ministers|Minister of Revenue]]\n| term_start4      = 14 December 2015\n| term_end4        = 20 December 2016\n| primeminister4   = [[John Key]]<br />[[Bill English]]\n| predecessor4     = [[Todd McClay]]\n| successor4       = [[Judith Collins]]\n| birth_date       = <!--{{Birth date and age|1965|df=yes}}-->\n| birth_place      = [[South Dunedin]], [[New Zealand]]\n| nationality      = New Zealand\n| spouse           =\n| party            = [[New Zealand National Party|National]]\n| relations        =\n| children         =\n| residence        =\n| alma_mater       =\n| occupation       =\n| profession       =\n| religion         =\n| signature        =\n| website          = {{url|http://www.michaelwoodhouse.co.nz}}\n| footnotes        =\n}}\n'''Michael Allan Woodhouse''' (born {{circa}}1965) is a [[New Zealand National Party|National]] member of the [[New Zealand Parliament]].\n\n==Early years==\nWoodhouse was born and raised in [[South Dunedin]], the fifth of nine children. He attended St Patrick's, St Edmund's and St Pauls High School, now [[Kavanagh College]], which he left at the end of sixth form in 1982.<ref name=\"National Party bio\">{{cite web | url=https://www.national.org.nz/team/mps/detail/michael.woodhouse | title=Hon Michael Woodhouse | work=national.org.nz | accessdate=16 December 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216090042/https://www.national.org.nz/team/mps/detail/michael.woodhouse | archivedate=16 December 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe worked for the [[National Bank of New Zealand]] in Dunedin and [[Wellington]] until 1987 when he embarked on a [[rugby union|rugby]] sojourn to Scotland and England, playing for [[Dunfermline RFC|Dunfermline]] 1987/88 and [[Broughton Park RUFC|Broughton Park]] in [[Manchester]] 1988/89.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} He then returned to Dunedin where he studied [[Commerce]] and [[Accounting]] at the [[University of Otago]], which he graduated from in 1993.<ref name=\"National Party bio\" />\n\nHe worked at Taylor Mclachlan Accountants in Dunedin, [[Dunedin Hospital]] and [[Accident Compensation Corporation|ACC]]. In 2005 he earned a Masters of Health Administration<ref> Degree check from UNSW [https://graduateregister.unsw.edu.au/?form%5BlastName%5D=Woodhouse&form%5BfirstName%5D=Michael&form%5Bdegree%5D=Master+of+Health+Administration&form%5B_token%5D=jzV4xfFOxlvqp-9qUTNzgeQmI2H-6YupC1GOdKYgMXc graduateregister.unsw.edu.au]</ref> at the [[University of New South Wales]] in [[Australia]].\nPrior to his political career, Woodhouse was the CEO of [[Mercy Hospital (Dunedin)|Mercy Hospital]] in Dunedin from 2001 to 2008.<ref name=\"National Party bio\" />\n\nWoodhouse was convicted for [[drink-driving]] when he was 21 years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/10677179/Police-ministers-drink-drive-confession |title=Police minister's drink-drive confession|last=Shadwell |first=Talia |date=30 October 2014 |work=[[The Dominion Post (New Zealand)|The Dominion Post]]|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\n{{NZ parlbox header|align=left}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |term       = 49th\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|2008}}\n |end        = 2011\n |electorate = [[Party lists in the 2008 New Zealand general election#National Party|List]]\n |party      = New Zealand National Party\n |list       = 49\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |term=50th\n |start={{NZ election link year|2011}}\n |end=2014\n |electorate = [[Party lists in the 2011 New Zealand general election#National Party|List]]\n |list=31\n |party=New Zealand National Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |term=51st\n |start={{NZ election link year|2014}}\n |end=2017\n |electorate = List\n |list=20\n |party=New Zealand National Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |term=51st\n |start={{NZ election link year|2017}}\n |end=present\n |electorate = List\n |list=10\n |party=New Zealand National Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox footer}}\n\n===Fifth National Government, 2008\u20132017===\nWoodhouse stood in [[Dunedin North (New Zealand electorate)|Dunedin North]] in 2008 and, though he received 30.64% (9972) of the votes he was defeated by incumbent electorate [[Pete Hodgson]] who received 52.62% of the vote. He was still however elected to the [[New Zealand House of Representatives]] through National's party [[list MP|list]]. In the {{NZ election link|2011}}, Woodhouse reduced the majority from 7,155 in 2008<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2005/electorate-10.html |title=Official Count Results \u2013 Dunedin North |publisher=Electionresults.govt.nz |date= |accessdate=27 May 2012}}</ref> to 3,489 against [[David Clark (New Zealand politician)|David Clark]].<ref>{{cite web| author=New Zealand Electoral Commission |url=http://www.electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2011/electorate-8.html |title=Official Count Results \u2013 Dunedin North |publisher=Electionresults.govt.nz |date= |accessdate=2012-05-27}}</ref> National also lost the party vote by 420 votes. Clark beat Woodhouse with an increased majority in the {{NZ election link|2014}}.<ref>{{cite news |title=Agony and ecstasy for Dunedin party faithful |url= http://www.odt.co.nz/news/election-2014/316617/agony-and-ecstasy-dunedin-party-faithful |accessdate=27 September 2014 |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |date=20 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nA member of the Health and Transport & Industrial Relations Select Committees in the [[49th New Zealand Parliament|49th Parliament]], Woodhouse was elected as the National Party's senior [[whip (politics)|whip]] on 20 December 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=National's whips Woodhouse and Upston |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/6166714/Nationals-whips-Woodhouse-and-Upston |accessdate=28 August 2018 |publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]], [[Fairfax New Zealand]] |date=20 December 2011}}</ref> He is the head of the Parliamentarians for Arthritis group and is active in the Parliamentary Sports Trust as a rugby player and referee.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nIn a reshuffle in January 2013, Woodhouse was made a minister outside cabinet and was given the Immigration, Veteran's Affairs and associate transport portfolios.<ref name=\"NZ Parliament\">{{cite web |title=Hon Michael Woodhouse |url=https://www.parliament.nz/en/mps-and-electorates/members-of-parliament/woodhouse-michael/ |publisher=[[New Zealand Parliament]] |accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref> During his time in Parliament,  Woodhouse voted against the [[Marriage (Definition of Marriage) Amendment Act 2013|Marriage (Definition of Marriage) Amendment Bill]], a bill allowing same-sex couples to marry in New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/7575780/Two-Canty-MPs-vote-against-gay-marriage-bill |title=Two Canty MPs vote against gay marriage bill |date=30 August 2012 |work=[[The Press]]|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> During the [[Fifth National Government of New Zealand|Fifth National Government]], Woodhouse served in various portfolios including immigration, transport, veteran's affairs, land information, workplace relations and safety, police, and the [[Accident Compensation Corporation]].<ref name=\"NZ Parliament\" /><ref name=\"National Party bio\" />\n\nIn August 2015, Michael Woodhouse caused controversy when he released a list of 57 high risk industries for his Health an Safety Reform Bill. This list was mocked by the Opposition because worm farming and mini golf were deemed \"high risk\", while dairy and cattle farming were not. Labour leader,  [[Andrew Little (New Zealand politician)|Andrew Little]], stated the new classifications were \"overly complicated, ill thought out and rushed through to appease National Party backers, putting the lives of New Zealanders at risk\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/71305806/government-deems-minigolf-and-worm-farming-more-risky-than-cattle-farming|title=Government deems mini-golf and worm farming more risky than cattle farming|last=Rutherford |first=Hamish |date=20 August 2015 |work=Stuff.co.nz |accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> While Labour's spokesperson for Labour issues, [[Iain Lees-Galloway]], said Woodhouse \"can\u2019t worm his way out of this. He will be forever ridiculed as the Minister who made killer worm farms safer but failed to protect people working in some of New Zealand's most dangerous industries\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Woodhouse wrote own worm farm risk list |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1510/S00205/woodhouse-wrote-own-worm-farm-risk-list.htm |accessdate=28 August 2018 |work=[[New Zealand Labour Party]] |publisher=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=14 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2017 New Zealand general election|2017 general election]], Michael Woodhouse was re-elected as a List MP on the National Party List. However, he failed to capture the [[Dunedin North]] electorate seat, which was held by Labour MP David Clark.<ref>{{cite web |title=2017 General Election list of successful candidates |url=https://www.elections.org.nz/sites/default/files/media/attachments/07_10_17_attachment_a_successful_candidates.pdf |publisher=[[Electoral Commission (New Zealand)|Electoral Commission]] |accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Sixth Labour Government, 2017\u2013present===\nFollowing the formation of a [[Sixth Labour Government of New Zealand|Labour-led coalition government]] with the support of [[New Zealand First]] and the [[Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand|Green Party]], National and its former support partner, the libertarian [[ACT New Zealand]] party, formed the opposition in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newshub.co.nz/home/election/2017/10/full-video-nz-first-leader-winston-peters-announces-next-government.html |title=Full video: NZ First leader Winston Peters announces next Government |author=Chapman, Grant |date=19 October 2017 |work=[[Newshub]] |accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newshub.co.nz/home/election/2017/10/an-historic-moment-for-the-green-party-james-shaw.html |title=An 'historic moment' for the Green Party \u2013 James Shaw |author=Hurley, Emma |date=19 October 2017 |work=[[Newshub]] |accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref> Michael Woodhouse became Deputy Shadow Leader of the House and the National Party's spokesperson for health and immigration. He is also currently a member of the health and privileges select committees.<ref name=\"NZ Parliament\" />\n\nIn early August 2018, Woodhouse in his capacity as National health spokesperson called for National Health Targets to be a legal requirement in response to the Labour Party's proposed Child Poverty legislation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kirk |first1=Stacey |title=National wants the Health Targets to be a legal requirement |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/105915451/national-wants-the-health-targets-to-be-a-legal-requirement |accessdate=28 August 2018 |publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Houlahan |first1=Mike |title=Woodhouse pushes health targets case |url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/health/woodhouse-pushes-health-targets-case |accessdate=28 August 2018 |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |date=6 August 2018}}</ref> In late August 2018, Woodhouse objected to United States whistleblower [[Chelsea Manning]]'s proposed tour of New Zealand in early September 2018, arguing that she should be banned due to her lack of remorse over her role in leaking sensitive US military documents to [[WikiLeaks]].<ref>{{cite news |title=National's Michael Woodhouse calls for whistleblower Chelsea Manning to be banned from New Zealand |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12114977 |accessdate=28 August 2018 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=28 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Garrick |first1=Gia |title=National wants Chelsea Manning banned from NZ |url=https://www.radionz.co.nz/news/political/365116/national-wants-chelsea-manning-banned-from-nz |accessdate=28 August 2018 |publisher=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWoodhouse is an avid [[Rugby union|rugby]] fan, having played for [[Otago]] in his youth. He has a wife Amanda and three children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michaelwoodhouse.co.nz/|title=HON MICHAEL WOODHOUSE List MP in Dunedin|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAn avid rugby follower, Woodhouse played age group rugby for Otago and South Island rep teams and premier rugby for Dunedin and Western Suburbs in Wellington. He also refereed 84 premier and approximately 20 representative colts and 'B' provincial matches. He also was a premier grade referee.<ref name=\"National Party bio\" />{{better source|date=December 2014}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Michael Woodhouse}}\n*[http://www.parliament.nz/en-nz/mpp/mps/current/51MP2991/woodhouse-michael Michael Woodhouse] at Parliament\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141216090042/https://www.national.org.nz/team/mps/detail/michael.woodhouse Michael Woodhouse] at the National Party\n*[http://www.michaelwoodhouse.co.nz Michael Woodhouse] \u2013 personal website\n\n{{Fifth National Government of New Zealand}}\n{{NZ National Party}}\n{{Current members of the New Zealand House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woodhouse, Michael}}\n[[Category:New Zealand National Party MPs]]\n[[Category:People from Dunedin]]\n[[Category:University of Otago alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand list MPs]]\n[[Category:People educated at Kavanagh College]]\n[[Category:1960s births]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Zealand House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand politicians]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2017 New Zealand general election]]\n", "name_user": "222.155.107.134", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Woodhouse"}
